<DOCNO> APW19990402.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:55:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Captured U.S. Soldiers To Be Tried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Three captured U.S. soldiers faced  
charges today in Kosovo, where NATO continued its bombing campaign 
against Serb targets in hopes of halting reported mass expulsions 
of ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	With the capture of three U.S. soldiers and trainloads of  
refugees reportedly being forced out of Kosovo, the allies have 
said bombardment of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces 
would proceed until he agrees to a peace deal granting autonomy to 
the southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic. 
</P>
<P>
	The three grim-faced U.S. soldiers, part of a NATO peacekeeping  
force in neighboring Macedonia, were shown on Serbian television 
Thursday dressed in camouflage, with bruises or abrasions on their 
faces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tanjug state news agency reported the three would face  
military court proceedings today, but it was unclear when the 
proceedings would take place. The charges were not immediately 
known. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said a Yugoslav  
court-martial of the three would violate international law. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO bombardment of targets in Yugoslavia continued, though  
it was deterred by what officials called poor weather that 
prevented some planes from carrying out missions. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO missiles hit an army barracks today in the town of Vranje  
in southeastern Serbia, state television reported. Initial reports 
said there were no casualties at the barracks, located in a 
populated area. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serb farmer was killed and his brother injured early today  
when a missile struck their house in the northern Kosovo village of 
Kursumlija, Tanjug reported. It said the house was near a power 
station, and speculated the station was the likely target. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian television reported that 200 refugees, mostly Serbs,  
Turks, Gypsies and some Albanians from the northern Kosovo town of 
Kosovska Mitrovica, arrived in Belgrade by train early today to 
escape ``the terrorists and NATO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of refugees also poured out of Kosovo with stories of  
an apparent Serb campaign that NATO officials contend is aimed at 
altering forever the ethnic makeup of the province. More than 
180,000 refugees have overwhelmed neighboring territories in the 
past week. 
</P>
<P>
	Two trains jammed with more than 10,000 people arrived Thursday  
at the Macedonian border, where U.N. refugee officials described 
scenes of pandemonium. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were ... crammed on to the train like sardines,'' said  
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees spokeswoman Judith Kumin in 
Geneva. ``Two old people died in the crush and three women gave 
birth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least eight cruise missiles were fired from U.S. ships in the  
Adriatic about midnight Thursday, and the Pentagon dispatched a 
dozen F-117A stealth fighters to the region to join 11 of the 
radar-evading planes already operating over Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian TV showed footage of what it said were abandoned  
strongholds of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army -- mostly houses 
fortified with sandbags -- in Dragobilje, Ovcarevo, Obrinje, Prekaz, 
Lapasnica, Pagarusa, Malisevo and Cicavica. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragobilje is where U.S. envoys met KLA leaders for negotiations  
over the past year. Prekaz was one of the birthplaces of the 
rebellion. Until late last summer, Malisevo was a major KLA 
stronghold. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Albanian capital, Tirana, KLA official Jakup Krasniqi  
told reporters Thursday night that the rebels were helping NATO 
bombing operations in Kosovo by locating targets. He gave no 
further details. 
</P>
<P>
	In a clear warning to remaining KLA rebels in the province, the  
Yugoslav army ordered all Kosovo Albanians to surrender weapons or 
face ``rigorous and unmerciful measures,'' the private Beta news 
agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview on ABC ``Nightline'' broadcast Thursday,  
Krasniqi said that after recent developments, the only possible 
solution would be independence for the majority ethnic Albanian 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	He also insisted that the KLA would not be ``extinguished or  
mopped out by the Serb forces,'' and said the rebels would launch 
an offensive ``in the next few days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo has been wracked by war since Milosevic launched a  
campaign against separatist ethnic Albanian rebels in February 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade on Thursday, Milosevic met with ethnic Albanian  
leader Ibrahim Rugova, who called for peace. The meeting was 
denounced by other ethnic Albanian leaders, and it was not clear 
whether Rugova was speaking freely. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic remained defiant, saying his country ``is leading a  
just battle, defending its citizens ... and will never give up its 
land and freedom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, Russian President Boris Yeltsin appealed for an end  
to the airstrikes and was considering sending more Russia warships 
to the Mediterranean. His government earlier announced a Russian 
naval vessel would depart for the region today. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's top military officer, said the  
missile and bombing raids had hit targets all over Yugoslavia, 
particularly air defenses, communication networks, military 
compounds and Serb forces carrying out attacks in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	But he acknowledged that NATO air power alone cannot stop  
alleged Serb atrocities being committed on the ground. He said it 
was up to NATO's political leaders to decide how to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav authorities call the NATO bombing a violation of  
international law and said refugees were fleeing Kosovo because of 
NATO attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the emissary of Pope John Paul II, French  
Archbishop Jean-Louis Tauran, met with Milosevic and called for the 
NATO attacks to halt in time for Easter. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials previously ruled out suspending the bombing  
campaign for Easter celebrations, which start today in the Western 
Christian Church. The Orthodox Church, to which most Serbs belong, 
celebrates Easter a week later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:55:18 </DATE_TIME>
