<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Assess Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the tales of Kosovo refugees grow more  
harrowing, President Clinton is dispatching a trusted aide to the 
Balkans and meeting with advisers and private aid officials to 
assess the U.S. response to the spreading humanitarian crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president wanted to get a full briefing both from his own  
government and the international organizations who are dealing with 
the humanitarian issues,'' said David Leavy, spokesman for the 
National Security Council. ``He wants to know what's being done and 
what more needs to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has sent $91 million in humanitarian aid to  
the region since last year. On Wednesday Clinton authorized another 
$50 million in support and directed the Pentagon to airlift food 
and other supplies to the countries neighboring the Kosovo province 
that are being swamped with refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	By Thursday, at least more than 190,000 Kosovo Albanians had  
fled the country since NATO airstrikes on Serb forces began March 
24. Many were forced into train cars at gunpoint. Others made the 
tearful trek on foot. 
</P>
<P>
	International organizations rushed to get more supplies to the  
refugees, while Western European nations met in an emergency 
conference in Bonn, Germany, to promise more aid. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-based AmeriCares disaster relief organization flew a  
relief flight to Skopje, Macedonia, to distribute medical supplies, 
and it planned four more flights in the next week. The Red Cross 
has been handling some of the U.S.-funded relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials and representatives from the U.S. Agency for  
International Development, which has sent disaster relief teams to 
Macedonia and Albania, were expected at the session in the Cabinet 
room today with officials from independent groups. 
</P>
<P>
	While there was a growing sense that NATO was failing to keep up  
with the flow of refugees, Leavy said the meeting was called to 
``make sure that everything is coordinated properly, that we are 
ahead of the curve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James Rubin said the seven-member  
USAID team dispatched Wednesday to Albania would immediately assess 
``the nutritional and health status of refugees, provide health 
care support, and provide recommendations for additional government 
support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the agency has moved crucial materials from warehouses  
in Italy to the Balkans, including $260,000 in tents, clothing and 
water to Albania and $430,000 in blankets, shelter material and 
health kits to Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Clinton dispatched Deputy Secretary of State Strobe  
Talbott to assess the affect of the Kosovo crisis on neighboring 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement issued by the White House said Talbott would lead an  
interagency delegation to Albania, Macedonia and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deputy secretary will thank these countries for their  
support of the NATO operation in Kosovo and underscore the U.S. 
commitment to provide support necessary to address the impact of 
the unfolding humanitarian, security and economic crisis in the 
region,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton on Thursday spoke to sailors, airmen and their families  
at the Norfolk Naval Base. His visit came a day after three U.S. 
Army soldiers were seized by Serbs along the Yugoslav-Macedonian 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Milosevic would be held responsible for safety of the  
three. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning to the White House, Clinton called British Prime  
Minister Tony Blair and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder to 
confer with them about the latest developments in the NATO 
campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
