<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expands Tree Quarantine List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Agriculture Department extended  
restrictions Friday on shipments of Christmas trees and other pine 
products from parts of six Eastern and Midwestern states. 
</P>
<P>
	New rules to prevent the spread of a tree-munching beetle were  
published Friday in the Federal Register, the government's bulletin 
of administrative regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules affirm emergency regulations issued Dec. 29 to add 19  
counties in Indiana, Michigan, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania and 
West Virginia to the quarantined area. Other counties in those six 
states, Illinois, Maryland and Wisconsin are covered under previous 
orders. 
</P>
<P>
	The department said the biggest impact will be on three  
Christmas tree farms in southwestern Pennsylvania's Blair and 
Greene counties. 
</P>
<P>
	The farms, which were not named, shipped all their trees and  
tree products outside the quarantined area in 1997, the government 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The pine shoot beetle, an insect the size of a match head, can  
cause stunted and distorted growth in pine trees. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Europe, the beetle was discovered at a Christmas  
tree farm near Cleveland in 1992. Since then, the Agriculture 
Department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service has sought 
to restrict its spread. 
</P>
<P>
	The restrictions, which apply only to interstate shipments,  
require businesses that want to ship outside the regulated areas to 
arrange for inspections and subject their products to special 
fumigation or cold treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspections are provided without charge, but businesses face  
treatment and other costs and possible marketing delays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
