<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pavarotti Returns to Las Vegas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Famed tenor Luciano Pavarotti says he doesn't  
know quite what to expect when he performs for a third time in Las 
Vegas next week. 
</P>
<P>
	But he knows there will be some roulette tables waiting to take  
his money again. 
</P>
<P>
	Pavarotti is to make a rare appearance in this gambling capital  
April 10, christening the 12,000-seat Mandalay Bay Resort &AMP; Casino 
Events Center. The concert will be his first here since March 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	He recalls being ``very comfortable'' with his Las Vegas  
audiences, and in the casino -- at least for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won a couple thousand dollars at roulette,'' he recalled  
this week. ``Then I lost it, like everybody does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pavarotti, 63, is having a good 1999 after undergoing hip and  
knee replacement surgery last year. In addition to solo 
engagements, he performed in Tokyo on Jan. 9 with Placido Domingo 
and Jose Carreras. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 06:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Population To Hit 8 Billion in 2026 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world's population, currently nearing 6  
billion, will climb to 8 billion by 2026, the Census Bureau 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	And the total will reach 9.3 billion by 2050, the agency  
projected in a report released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The growth of human population has been, is now, and in the  
future will be almost entirely determined in the world's less 
developed countries,'' the Census report said. 
</P>
<P>
	It concluded that 99 percent of natural increase -- the  
difference between births and deaths -- occurs in the developing 
regions of Africa, Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	By early in the next century deaths will exceed births in the  
more developed nations and all of the net growth will be in 
developing countries, the report added. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's age structure also will shift, becoming  
progressively older, in coming years with the population of those 
aged 65 and over more than doubling while the number of those under 
age 15 will grow by 6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 08:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> April Storm Pounds Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Plains residents braced for more stormy  
weather today after more than a foot of snow blanketed parts of the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Black Hills in South Dakota, Deadwood got 13 inches of  
snow Thursday and nearby Lead received about a foot. In North 
Dakota, Bismarck and Dickinson both received 9 inches of snow. 
</P>
<P>
	A winter storm watch was still in effect for parts of North  
Dakota, and as much as 6 inches of snow were possible by tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow wasn't the only problem. Wind and freezing rain downed  
power lines in eastern North Dakota, causing outages for as many as 
4,000 customers, said Bonnie Lund, a spokeswoman for Northern 
States Power. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews worked throughout the night and called for reinforcements  
this morning for the Grand Forks area. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been kind of an up-and-down situation,'' NSP spokesman  
Terry Thorstensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowed, broken tree limbs and branches covered city streets in  
Grand Forks, along with ice and frozen slush. Power was knocked out 
to nine sewer lift stations, and residents were being advised to 
reduce water use and plug basement sewer drains as a precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	Ice also knocked out a major electrical distribution line  
serving eastern North Dakota and western Minnesota, though back-up 
systems kept power on for most customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm made roads a mess. Melvin Walker was one of many  
truckers stranded at the Stamart Travel Center and Oasis Restaurant 
in Bismarck during Thursday's blizzard. He could only look out a 
truck stop window as he waited for his chance to deliver Washington 
state apples to Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	``You couldn't even see -- freezing rain, snow was blowing. It  
was just terrible,'' the truck driver from Ohio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Kibbel watched the snow from his home in Mott, in  
southwestern North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just holed up,'' he said. ``We can't even see out the  
window. It's not even fit for a dog to be out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The storm couldn't have come at a worse time for ranchers in the  
middle of calving season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can see across the farmstead now and the yard, but that's  
about it,'' said Steve Sprenger, who has about 225 cattle near 
Elgin. ``If you've got any cows that are calving -- if those cows 
aren't in the barn, they're going to be gone.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
