<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Hero Trainer Aiming High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Desert Hero has raced only twice, and not  
farther than a mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry, says Corey Nakatani, who will ride the colt  
Saturday in the Santa Anita Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's like an old pro,'' Nakatani said after Desert Hero and  
seven other 3-year-olds were entered Thursday for the 1 1/8-mile Santa 
Anita Derby, a major steppingstone to the Kentucky Derby on May 1 
at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Dick Mandella also likes what he's seen of Desert Hero,  
although he didn't see either of the colt's races. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a chance to get a couple of good works in him at  
seven-eighths and a mile,'' Mandella said. ``He does everything 
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mandella got Desert Hero after the colt beat Prime Timber by a  
neck in the 1-mile San Rafael on Feb. 29 at Santa Anita. The colt, 
owned by Prince Ahmed bin Salman of Saudi Arabia, was taken away 
from trainer Wally Dollase, Nakatani's father-in-law. A 
philosophical difference was cited as the reason for the change. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandella said he would watch a tape of the San Rafael before  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nakatani and Mandella aren't the only ones impressed by Desert  
Hero, who made his racing debut by winning a 6 1/2-furlong maiden race 
Feb. 7. The colt was made the 5-2 early favorite, followed by 
General Challenge (3-1) and Prime Timber (7-2) and the filly Honest 
Lady (4-1). 
</P>
<P>
	Desert Hero is the son of Sea Hero, the 1993 Kentucky Derby  
winner. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge and Prime Timber are trained by Bob Baffert,  
who finished 1-2 with Indian Charlie and Real Quiet in last year's 
Santa Anita Derby and who won the last two Kentucky derbies, with 
Silver Charm and Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought Prime Timber would be the favorite off his last race  
(a two-length win in the San Felipe on March 13),'' Baffert said. 
``He ran an incredible race. If he runs that race back, he's a 
galloping winner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber, a winner of three of five career starts, with two  
seconds, wore blinkers for the first time in the San Felipe. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, a gelding, will wear blinkers for the first  
time Saturday in his first start since he finished fifth in 1 
1-16-mile Louisiana Derby on March 14, his only loss in four 
starts. He wore blinkers for a workout March 23 at Santa Anita and 
sizzled five-eighths of a mile in 57 3-5 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Since General challenge is owned by John and Betty Mabee and  
Prime Timber is owned by Aaron and Marie Jones, they will not race 
as an entry. 
</P>
<P>
	Honest Lady, winner of two of three starts, will be facing colts  
for the second time. She finished fifth in the San Rafael, but was 
only one length behind winner Desert Hero. She is stabled at 
Hollywood Park in Inglewood. 
</P>
<P>
	Only three fillies have won the Santa Anita Derby, and only  
three have won the Kentucky Derby. Winning Colors, in 1988, was the 
last filly to win either race. 
</P>
<P>
	Post time for the $750,000 Santa Anita Derby, to be televised by  
Fox, is 2:40 p.m. PST. 
</P>
<P>
	The field in post-position order is Honest Lady, ridden by Kent  
Desormeaux; Prime Timber, David Flores; Desert Hero, Nakatani; 
Capsized, Alex Solis; Walk That Walk, Chris Antley; High Wire Act, 
Chris McCarron; General Challenge, Gary Stevens, and Charismatic, 
Laffit Pincay Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Capsized is trained by Lisa Lewis, only the fifth woman to train  
a Santa Anita Derby starter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
