<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arco Finds Put Alaska on Oil Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- When Richfield Oil Corp. arrived in  
Alaska, the only locally produced oil came from fish. 
</P>
<P>
	The year was 1955, and Alaska was still a federal territory  
fighting to become a state. Opposition to statehood was strong in 
Washington, D.C., largely because it wasn't clear that sprawling, 
thinly populated Alaska could support itself. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1957, Richfield's first Alaska well was in the Cook Inlet  
area, and it came in as a gusher. The worry about self-sufficiency 
ebbed, and the following year Congress voted overwhelmingly to make 
Alaska the 49th state. 
</P>
<P>
	The success at Swanson River marked the beginning of a  
four-decade relationship that produced huge riches for both the 
state and the company, whose name had been changed to Atlantic 
Richfield Co. when it discovered the real bonanza -- Prudhoe Bay, 
the largest oil field ever found in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say Alaska made Arco, and Arco certainly had a  
pervasive impact on the state,'' said Gil Mull, a former Richfield 
geologist. 
</P>
<P>
	Those heady days are long gone for Arco, and soon its name will  
be, too. The company, pounded hard by prolonged low prices, was 
swallowed by BP Amoco PLC this week for $25.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which still must be approved by regulators, won't be  
final until the end of the year. In the meantime, Arco will 
continue as its own company, but in the minds of former workers and 
others in Alaska, the obituary has already been printed. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us feel some loss,'' said Harold Heinze, a former Arco  
president in Alaska. ``Though I probably feel a little more for the 
current employees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're losing a hell of a friend,'' said former Gov. Walter  
Hickel. 
</P>
<P>
	Losing Arco would leave BP Amoco as the only company operating  
on the North Slope, which accounts for more than one-sixth of the 
nation's oil production. BP Amoco would control more than 70 
percent of Alaska's crude output, and have a similar stake in the 
800-mile trans-Alaska oil pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco now pumps far more oil off the North Slope, but Arco  
was seen as having the better prospects by virtue of being a more 
vigorous explorer. 
</P>
<P>
	What worries some in oil-dependent Alaska is that the loss of  
Arco as a North Slope competitor could mean less hunting for new 
fields there. 
</P>
<P>
	``BP has always gone for the elephants,'' said Jack Roderick,  
whose book ``Crude Dreams'' chronicled Alaska's oil history. ``Do 
they have the incentive to move out from what they know? They 
haven't done it yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``BP has not been the real aggressive organization in frontier  
exploration,'' said Mull, who now works for the state. ``Most of 
the major discoveries, I think, are made by smaller companies 
willing to step out and do outrageous things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outrageous would describe Arco's devotion to the North Slope in  
the late 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	The region's geology had attracted a lot of interest, but no one  
could find any oil -- more than a dozen expensive holes were 
drilled, and every one of them dry. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash-strapped Richfield was getting ready to join the corporate  
exodus in the spring of 1967. But the company decided to drill one 
more well at an obscure place called Prudhoe Bay, and ended up 
driving the bit down into an oil reservoir that has so far yielded 
more than 10 billion barrels of crude. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this had been a dry hole, the North Slope would have been  
dead for a few years,'' said retired Arco geologist Marvin Mangus, 
who helped choose the Prudhoe Bay drill site. ``Maybe it would 
still be dead.'' BP was among those ready to pack it in when Arco 
drilled the Prudhoe Bay discovery well. Arco had offered to buy its 
Prudhoe acreage for a good price, but apparently pushed a little 
too hard to close the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	A suspicious BP held out and soon came news of the discovery. It  
started drilling wells and, as luck would have it, the largest 
share of the oil lay under its land. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
