<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Courier Ready for Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) -- For Jim Courier, meeting Tim Henman  
before 9,400 screaming British fans was no big deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't misunderstand, Courier likes the fact that the United  
States and Britain are meeting again in the Davis Cup, just as they 
did 99 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	And he said he was proud to be representing his country again.  
</P>
<P>
	Other than that, ``for us it's pretty much business as usual,''  
he said on the eve of the match. ``We have a job to do, we come 
here, we prepare and try to do the job and that's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It may be a little bit more, certainly for Britain, and British  
captain David Lloyd is unconvinced by Courier's assertion that it's 
just another match. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that,'' Lloyd said. ``I think it's going to be  
very special. We want to win the cup. There's no two ways about it 
and it's a very big occasion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lloyd revealed that, at dinner on Wednesday, Courier and the  
rest of the players took the rare step of signing each others menus 
to keep as mementos. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't keep a Key Biscayne memento,'' the British captain  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain is back in the World Group after a seven-year spell in  
the tennis doldrums and the two nations who first contested the 
Davis Cup at the Longwood Cricket Club in Boston in 1900 meet 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the Americans have won the title a record 31 times,  
while the last of Britain's nine titles was in 1936 against 
Australia. Britain's last victory over the Americans was in 1935. 
</P>
<P>
	After Henman vs. Courier, Greg Rusedski went against Todd  
Martin, who has leapfrogged him in the rankings and now is No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The same British duo face Courier and Alex O'Brien in Saturday's  
doubles. Sunday's matches are Henman against Martin followed by 
Rusedski vs. Courier, and the winner of the tie faces either 
Zimbabwe or Australia in the next round. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. captain Tom Gullikson initially tried to persuade world No.  
1 Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi to play, but they declined. But 
he's confident that Courier, Martin, Jan-Michael Gambill and 
O'Brien is now the strongest team available to him. He pointed out 
that Courier and Martin had an 11-2 record against Henman and 
Rusedski in tournament play. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have got guys who are very good against Henman and Rusedski  
and I have no reason to think that it won't be different this 
week,'' Gullikson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin said he was hopeful that his injured stomach muscle had  
recovered enough for him to serve at full strength on a surface he 
described as on the fast side of medium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had it a couple of months, probably since I played Petr  
Korda in the Australian Open at Melbourne'' he said. ``It's not as 
huge liability. My only concern now is how well I recover from 
Friday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other six World Group ties have defending titlist Sweden  
against Slovakia, Germany vs. Russia, France vs. Netherlands, Spain 
vs. Brazil, Belgium vs. Czech Republic and Switzerland against last 
year's runner up, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis Cup champion Sweden begins defense of its title in a  
small, 2,500-capacity hall with no TV coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have absolutely nothing against Trollhattan (the city where  
the match against Slovakis is taking place),'' Swedish star Thomas 
Enqvist said. ``But it's a sign of weakness to play in such a small 
hall. By having a match here, one's status is drawn down a 
little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Enqvist and Thomas Johansson are playing singles, with Nicklas  
Kulti teaming with Jonas Bjorkman in doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, which entertains Russia at Frankfurt's Ballsporthalle,  
hasn't won the title since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Boris Becker teams in doubles with David Prinosil, while  
Germany's singles hopes rest with Nicolas Kiefer and Tommy Haas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians send Australian Open champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov  
against Kiefer and Marat Safin against Haas. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia goes to Harare to face Zimbabwe with a feud still  
hanging over the team between Mark Philippoussis and captain John 
Newcombe. 
</P>
<P>
	It dates to last year's loss to the Zimbabweans when  
Philippousis declined to play and relations between the two have 
been cool ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be silly to say we're one big happy family,'' said  
Newcombe, who sends Philippousis out to play Byron Black and 
Patrick Rafter to face Wayne Black. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there's no bitterness in our approach. I don't think  
there'll be any problems. And if we win here it will do a lot to 
help forget about the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winner of the Lipton Championship last weekend, Dutchman Richard  
Krajicek hopes to transfer his impressive tournament form over to 
the Davis Cup where he has won only four of 11 singles matches. 
</P>
<P>
	Krajicek faces Jerome Golmard in the match against France at  
Nimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Haarhuis meets Cedric Pioline, then teams with Jan  
Siemerink in Saturday's doubles against Golmard and Guillaume 
Raoux. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's former French Open champion, Gustavo Kuerten, meets  
Spain's Alex Corretja in today's singles before facing Carlos Moya 
on Sunday in the Spanish town of Lleida. 
</P>
<P>
	At Gent, Belgium, the Czech Republic's Slava Dosedel plays Filip  
Dewulf and Bohdan Ulihrach faces Xavier Malisse. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy, the losing finalist last year to Sweden, travels to  
Switzerland, with Davide Sanguinetti meeting Marc Rosset and 
Gianluca Pozzi facing Roger Federer in today's matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
