<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurdler Bryan Bronson Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTE CARLO, Monaco (AP) -- Bryan Bronson, the world's top-ranked  
400-meter hurdler the past two years and winner of three straight 
U.S. championships, was suspended by track and field's governing 
body for a failed drug test. 
</P>
<P>
	The test came at a Grand Prix meet last July 14 in Rome, the  
International Amateur Athletic Federation said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said the 26-year-old hurdler from  
Houston was suspended March 19 after his urine sample contained 
``abnormal steroid concentrations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bronson was not immediately available for comment. Kim Betts of  
USA Track &AMP; Field's legal department said, ``We can't comment on an 
athlete's eligibility matters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Pelletier, who was Bronson's agent, said he couldn't comment  
pending final action by USATF, which will review the case. Kim 
Wrinkle, the hurdler's former coach, said, ``If it's true, it's a 
shame. It's an incredible waste of talent. He's a tremendous 
athlete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pelletier said his relationship with Bronson ended Wednesday  
because of ``lack of communications'' the last few months. Wrinkle 
said he hasn't been in touch with Bronson since July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``He broke off relations with his friends, his relatives, his  
teammates, his coach, with everybody,'' Wrinkle said. ``He's done 
that before. He's a very private person. He goes into periods of 
seclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bronson was the bronze medalist at the 1997 world championships  
in Athens, Greece, and ran the third-fastest time in history (47.03 
seconds) in winning the national championship at New Orleans last 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said Bronson was not suspended immediately after the  
positive test because a letter from his doctor and lawyer said he 
had a ``medical problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some positive doping tests are closed when there is a genetic  
or medical explanation,'' Reineri said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said Bronson was allowed to compete last summer despite  
the test. He reached the Grand Prix final at Moscow in September -- 
undefeated in the Golden League series and unbeaten in 17 races 
overall in 1998 -- but lost in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have waited for a further, complete medical report from  
him,'' Reineri said. ``We have not received it and have decided to 
suspend him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bronson is the third elite track and field athlete suspended in  
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Vita Pavlysh of Ukraine won the women's shot put gold medal at  
last month's world indoor championships and lost the title after a 
failed drug test. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Doug Walker, the European 200 champion, was suspended  
by his country's ruling track body following a positive test for 
the anabolic steroid Nandrolone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
