<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Dismisses Marine Navigator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- The navigator of a Marine Corps jet  
that cut an Italian gondola cable, killing 20 people, said he 
respects a jury's decision to discharge him for destroying a 
personal videotape shot on the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., said Friday he  
harbored no bitterness against the Marine Corps and wants to ``wake 
up tomorrow and not have to deal with this for the first time in 14 
months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer had pleaded guilty to obstruction of justice and  
conspiracy -- charges that carried up to 10 years in prison. He 
admitted throwing the tape into a fire two days after his jet 
clipped an Alpine gondola cable. He said he was afraid his face 
would be used on Italian media. 
</P>
<P>
	After deliberating about three hours, a jury of nine Marine  
officers recommended that Schweitzer be dismissed from the military 
-- the equivalent of a dishonorable discharge for an enlisted 
person. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys said they will seek to have the sentence  
reduced, to no punishment or a letter of reprimand. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence isn't final until a commanding general reviews it  
and considers attorneys' pleadings. Once Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, 
commander of Marine Forces Atlantic, approves a sentence, it goes 
into the military appeals process. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer was the navigator, sitting in the right front seat,  
of an EA-6B Prowler that hit a gondola cable over Cavalese, Italy, 
on Feb. 3, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Manslaughter charges against him were dismissed after the pilot,  
Capt. Richard Ashby, was acquitted of manslaughter in March. Ashby, 
32, of Mission Viejo, Calif., still faces obstruction of justice 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer was using Ashby's camera during the low-level  
mountain training flight. After the jet's right wing was nearly 
sheared off by the cable, the jet made an emergency landing at its 
Aviano air base and the two men switched the tape before leaving 
the crippled jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Dave Beck said he will urge Pace to drop the  
charges against Ashby because it was Schweitzer who suggested 
getting rid of the tape, which he shot as a memento because he 
planned to leave the service and attend graduate school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
