<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Individual Stocks Took a Hit in 4th </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ouch! Individual stocks can really hurt a porfolio when they  
take a fall. 
</P>
<P>
	A sample portfolio for small investors that The Associated Press  
has tracked since October 1997 eked out just a 1 percent gain 
during the first quarter, because two of its individual stock 
holdings, IBM and Coca-Cola, dropped on poor sales outlooks. By 
comparison, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 6.6 percent 
during the first three months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3.9 percent decline in IBM and the 8.4 percent slide in Coke  
nearly offset healthier returns posted by Wal-Mart and the mutual 
funds in the portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	Volatility in individual stocks is the reason why millions of  
individual investors turn to mutual funds to diversify their 
holdings and cushion their portfolios against big losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP has followed the stock market's progress through the  
portfolio created at the close of trading on Oct. 23, 1997. The 
portfolio, consisting of three mutual funds and three widely held 
stocks, as of March 31 had increased 44.88 percent since its 
inception. 
</P>
<P>
	The portfolio was valued at $25,299.85 at its inception and was  
worth $36,654.91 as the first quarter ended. During the fourth 
quarter, the portfolio rose 27.38 percent, recovering from an 11.32 
percent drop in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	For the just-ended quarter, the portfolio's mutual funds turned  
in a respectable performance. The Vanguard Index Trust 500 
Portfolio fund, which tracks Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 large 
U.S. companies, rose 4.3 percent. The Morgan Stanley Dean Witter 
Pacific Growth Fund continued its recovery along with other funds 
with a big representation of Asian stocks. It rose 7.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole losing fund in the Portfolio was the T. Rowe Price U.S.  
Treasury Long-Term Fund, which fell 5.3 percent as investors 
switched from bonds to stocks to take advantage of Wall Street's 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart had the best return of of all the holdings in the  
portfolio, rising 13.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM fell during the quarter on news that its personal computer  
business was slumping. Coca-Cola dropped as it warned investors 
that its first-quarter sales volume would be disappointing. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Decries Mowed Lawns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- That sweet scent of a freshly mowed lawn may  
really be the smell of air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists studying the sources of chemicals in the air have  
found that injured grass gives off volatile compounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wounding, cutting and drying of leaves and stems occur both  
naturally and by human activities, wound-induced and drying-induced 
... compounds are expected to be significant in the atmosphere,'' a 
team of researchers says in a study scheduled to appear in a future 
issue of the journal Geophysical Research Letters. 
</P>
<P>
	``In urban areas, lawn mowing may contribute to the total ...  
emissions and impact air quality,'' the report says. 
</P>
<P>
	But do not panic. While total emissions from cutting grass and  
crops worldwide may seem large, it does not mean cutting the grass 
is dangerous for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just doesn't seem likely to me that the smell of newly mown  
grass is toxic,'' said Ray Fall of the University of Colorado, a 
biochemist and one of the researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mowing the lawn is no more hazardous than eating raw  
vegetables,'' he added, pointing out that chewing veggies also 
releases tiny amounts of the same chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the grazing of animals can release these compounds into the  
air, he said: ``Every time a cow chomps grass you get these little 
surges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, Fall said the team was surprised at the variety of  
chemicals released when crops were cut and during the drying 
process, including methanol, hexanal, acetaldehyde, acetone and 
butatone. Some, such as acetone, can contribute to the formation of 
smog, the paper notes. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists estimate that cutting crops adds about 1.6  
million tons of acetone to the atmosphere annually, compared with 
estimated total natural emissions of 8 million to 13 million tons. 
They have not estimated the totals for other compounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers studied red fescue grass cut from a lawn near  
their laboratory in Boulder, Colo., and clover grown in a 
greenhouse. This summer they plan a study of alfalfa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Environmental Protection Agency has a laboratory in North  
Carolina looking at biological emissions of chemicals, but has not 
studied grass or clover. 
</P>
<P>
	The new report says that in addition to lawn mowing, chemicals  
are given off by drying plant material in arid areas and during the 
harvest in agricultural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be expected that the resulting emissions have a  
significant impact on the chemistry of the atmosphere over these 
areas,'' said the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cut and drying organic material appears to be a significant  
global, and possibly regional, source of volatile organic 
compounds. One that we think may not have been well accounted for 
before,'' Carlton J. Howard of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration's Aeronomy Laboratory in Boulder said in a telephone 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard noted that emissions from lawn mowers and even barbecues  
have been identified as components of pollution in some urban areas 
and this study adds one more source of chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is something that needs to be looked at carefully,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:52:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Hits 29-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate fell to a  
29-year low of 4.2 percent in March, with Hispanics and high school 
dropouts among the groups registering the most dramatic 
improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a historic report,'' Labor Secretary Alexis Herman  
said Friday. ``It's an indication this is an economy that is 
lifting all boats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement in the rate, from 4.4 percent in February, came  
despite the smallest seasonally adjusted increase in three years in 
the number of jobs -- 46,000. That's the fewest since an outright 
decline in payrolls in January 1996 when a blizzard struck the 
Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists also attributed most of the latest deceleration in  
job growth to the weather -- milder-than-usual conditions in 
February followed by heavy snow in many states in March -- rather 
than to any significant deterioration in the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The slow growth in payrolls in March masks a firm underlying  
trend,'' said economist Joel Naroff, a consultant in Holland, Pa. 
``The economy remains in excellent shape ... when the weather 
effects are smoothed out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	March's unemployment rate was the lowest since February 1970,  
when it also was 4.2 percent. At that time, unemployment was 
actually increasing. An economic expansion that covered a ``good 
chunk'' of the 1960s -- when the unemployment rate dropped as low as 
3.4 percent -- had ended a few months earlier, said Tom Nardone, 
chief of labor force statistics at the Bureau of Labor Statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the rate for Hispanics fell from 6.7 percent to 5.8  
percent, the lowest since the Labor Department began calculating a 
rate for the group in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	``These economic indicators are more than just economic  
indicators,'' President Clinton said at a news conference. ``They 
mean wider opportunity and a better chance for millions of 
Americans to have stronger families and give their children a 
better chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the rate for adults who dropped out of high school  
fell from 7.5 percent to 6.1 percent. Rates were unchanged for high 
school graduates, at 3.4 percent, and for college graduates, at 1.9 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people who used to be hiring college grads are  
setting their sites lower ... or if they were hiring high school 
grads, they're saying, 'I can get by with a high-school dropout.' 
They're the only people left to hire,'' said economist David Wyss 
of DRI's McGraw Hill in Lexington, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The smaller-than-expected advance in payrolls in March followed  
gains of 297,000 in February and 217,000 in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers, many hit hard by the global economic slump that  
began in Asia near two years ago, cut 35,000 jobs last month, 
bringing the decline for the past year to 381,000. Over the past 
year, losses have been most severe at factories making industrial 
machinery, apparel and electrical equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction hiring fell by a seasonally adjusted 47,000 jobs in  
March after the actual gain in jobs fell short of the normal 
advance for the start of spring. Bureau of Labor Statistics 
Commissioner Katharine Abraham said construction workers that 
normally would have been hired in March were already on the 
payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Mining, which includes oil-drilling, lost 7,000 jobs in March,  
bringing losses over the past year to 55,000. Agricultural services 
and real estate also recorded declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiring at restaurants and bars fell on a seasonally adjusted  
basis, too. Wyss said that may partly reflect restaurant owners' 
difficulty in finding help. 
</P>
<P>
	Robust employment growth continued in engineering and management  
services, health care, educational services and amusement and 
recreation. There also were gains in computer and data processing 
and finance and insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	By demographic group, in addition to the drop for Hispanics, the  
jobless rate fell from 3.8 percent to 3.6 percent for whites, from 
8.3 percent to 8.1 percent for blacks and from 3.7 percent to 3.2 
percent for men. It rose from 3.8 percent to 3.9 percent for women 
and from 14.1 percent to 14.3 percent for teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	Average hourly earnings for non-farm, non-supervisory workers  
rose a modest 3 cents in March to $13.09. They're up 3.6 percent 
from a year earlier. The average workweek declined by a tenth of an 
hour to 34.5 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The inflation-wary bond market was cheered by the small rise in  
wages because it reinforced the view that the Federal Reserve need 
not raise interest rates to quell inflation pressures. The yield on 
the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.60 percent from 5.67 
percent late Thursday. The stock market was closed for Good Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:44:05 </DATE_TIME>
