<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:24:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins' Springer Wins Starting Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) -- Journeyman knuckleballer Dennis Springer  
has to fight for a job every season, which may be why his hair is 
gray at 34. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Springer won a spot in the Florida Marlins' rotation  
only because they decided to begin the season with five starters 
instead of four. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nice little release of pressure,'' said Springer, who  
went 3-11 with a 5.45 ERA for Tampa Bay last year. ``Every year 
it's been like this. I'm an insurance policy guy. I'm always the 
11th or 12th guy on a staff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins decided to keep Springer because he can be used as a  
reliever between starts. For example, he'll be in the bullpen for 
the first two games of the season Monday and Tuesday, then make his 
first start Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-handed Springer and lefty Kurt Ojala give the Marlins  
two knuckleballers, a rarity on one staff. That could be an 
effective contrast to their three relievers who throw in the upper 
90s -- closer Matt Mantei, setup man Braden Looper and Antonio 
Alfonseca. 
</P>
<P>
	With off days, the five-man rotation means the Marlins' starters  
will get five days off between starts early in the season. Manager 
John Boles said the extra rest will benefit youngsters Livan 
Hernandez, Jesus Sanchez and Brian Meadows, as well as Alex 
Fernandez, who is coming back from rotator cuff surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we have to provide some protection for our guys with  
cold weather early in the season,'' Boles said. ``And we have to 
watch Alex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins will begin the season with an 11-man pitching staff.  
Eight of the 11 were with the team last year, when Florida finished 
last in the National League in ERA and lost 108 games. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's reason to expect improvement from a young staff with  
nine pitchers in their 20s. The relief corps recently had a streak 
of 18 consecutive scoreless innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the bullpen,'' Boles said. ``The bullpen has been our  
strength so far. If we pitch during the season like we did during 
spring training, we're going to be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boles is encouraged by the starting rotation following the  
latest outings by Hernandez and Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel better about it than I did two weeks ago,'' he said.  
``We are going to have to pitch very well and play good defense, 
because we are not an offensive machine.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 08:35:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small Romanian Bank Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- General Electric Capital Corp. and the  
Portuguese Investment Bank signed a $43 million agreement Friday to 
buy a 45 percent stake of a Romanian state-owned bank. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric Capital will take a 35 percent stake and Banco  
Portugues de Investimento will take 10 percent of BancPost, a small 
Romanian state bank that has not been plagued by bad loans, as some 
other banks have. 
</P>
<P>
	They also will invest $50 million over five years improving the  
bank's technology, developing new products and training staff. 
</P>
<P>
	After the deal, Romania's privatization agency, the State  
Ownership Fund, will be left with a 25 percent stake in the bank, 
with the remaining 30 percent owned by several Romanian investment 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	BancPost is the second Romanian bank to be privatized. In  
November, Societe Generale de France signed a $200 million deal to 
buy a majority stake in Romanian Bank for Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 00:22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Casey Has High Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. (AP) -- Sean Casey is hoping for a smoother  
second season. It almost has to be better than the first. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Casey was traded from the Cleveland Indians to the  
Cincinnati Reds, was handed the Reds' starting first base job and 
had the bone below his right eye shattered by a thrown ball. 
</P>
<P>
	That was all in the first week of the season.  
</P>
<P>
	He had surgery, got his vision back, did some rehabilitation in  
the minors, got called up, struggled, was sent back down, got his 
swing together, came up and turned into the hitter the Reds 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't end there. He got engaged to a special education  
teacher, went back to school in the offseason and obtained his 
undergraduate degree in speech communication. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sat down this winter and thought about what went on last  
year,'' Casey said. ``It was no doubt a roller coaster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it ended on an upswing, and that's what Casey thought about  
the most. After the scare with his eye and an unsuccessful return 
to the majors soon after the injury, the 24-year-old first baseman 
showed why he was considered one of the Indians' top hitting 
prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey batted .316 in July and .305 in August, eliminating any  
concerns about his eye. He also established himself as the Reds' 
first baseman of the future. They traded first baseman Paul Konerko 
after the season, leaving the job to Casey. 
</P>
<P>
	That frenetic, frightful, frustrating rookie season ended up  
being pretty good after all. Casey hit .272 in 96 games with 21 
doubles, seven homers and 52 runs batted in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It turned out to be a good year,'' he said. ``You look at my  
numbers compared to all the rookies in the league and I think I was 
up there in the top 10 in most categories. And most of my numbers 
were second-half numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked to have seen what I could have done for a  
full year, but obviously the circumstances didn't happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His circumstances are much improved heading into his second  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no lingering concerns about his eye. When he was hit  
by a throw during infield practice one year ago Friday, he 
temporarily lost vision in the right eye. It took 20 stitches to 
close a gash around the eye and doctors installed a plate with five 
screws below it to stabilize the fractured bone. 
</P>
<P>
	There was concern that he might never get full vision back. One  
year later, his vision has improved. He no longer has to wear a 
contact lens in the right eye. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no much uncertainty when I got hit. Would I play  
again? How would I come back? Would I be the same player?'' Casey 
said. ``In fact, the vision came back to normal in that eye. It 
corrected itself. I think it's kind of a blessing the way things 
worked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casey was one of the Reds' most consistent hitters this spring,  
batting .343 with two homers and 13 RBIs -- second on the club -- 
after 22 games. He also began taking on a bigger role in the 
clubhouse as he became the team's assistant union representative. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a chance to have a role outside of baseball to help  
this team, which is good,'' he said. ``Hopefully as I play this 
game more and more, I'll have a chance to be a leader.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
