<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 00:22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC DiMaggio Monument in the Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WOBURN, Mass. (AP) -- A Massachusetts sculptor has landed a  
contract to memorialize Joe DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Shure of Burlington was asked to complete a bronze relief of  
DiMaggio. The bronze bust will be placed in Yankee Stadium 
alongside other memorials to baseball greats, including Babe Ruth 
and Lou Gehrig. 
</P>
<P>
	``To say I was thrilled was an underestimation,'' Shure told the  
Daily Times Chronicle of Woburn after being selected to do the 
portrait of DiMaggio, who died March 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Shure has made a clay mold of the portrait, which was presented  
to Yankees owner George Steinbrenner. The next step in the design 
will be a plaster model, then the bronze bust itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Shure previously made reliefs of Boston slugger Ted Williams for  
the tunnel named after him and another for pitcher Cy Young on 
Huntington Avenue in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Shire, whose studio is in Woburn, also worked on the Irish  
Famine Memorial on the Freedom Trail in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The dedication of the DiMaggio relief is slated for April 25.  
DiMaggio's family is scheduled to be there, as are Steinbrenner and 
Shure. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio, who died last month at 84, was immortalized in song  
and literature, a man respected as much for his dignity as for his 
accomplishments during 13 seasons with the Yankees. His 56-game 
hitting streak in 1941, one of the greatest feats in all sports, is 
still a record. 
</P>
<P>
	The wording on the relief for DiMaggio will read: Joseph Paul  
DiMaggio, ``The Yankee Clipper,'' 1914-1999. Recognized as 
Baseball's ``Greatest Living Player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The relief will also show DiMaggio's lifetime batting average of  
.325 and note that he won the Most Valuable Player awards in 1939, 
1941 and 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	It will also pay tribute to DiMaggio's other achievements,  
including his selection to the All-Star game 13 times and his 
American League batting titles in 1939 and 1940. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Results From Recent Gore Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from recent polls about Vice President Al Gore and  
the 2000 presidential race. When the results don't total 100 
percent, the remainder either didn't know or did not respond. 

</P>
<P>
	--If the election for president in the year 2000 were being held  
today and the candidates were Al Gore and George W. Bush, for whom 
would you vote? 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore, 41 percent; George W. Bush, 54 percent. (ABC/Washington  
Post) 

</P>
<P>
	--If the election for president in the year 2000 were being held  
today and the candidates were Al Gore and Elizabeth Dole, for whom 
would you vote? 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore, 43 percent; Elizabeth Dole, 51 percent. (ABC/Washington  
Post) 

</P>
<P>
	--Looking ahead to the next presidential election, would you like  
to see a president who offers policies and programs similar to 
those of the Clinton administration, or would you like to see a 
president who offers different policies and programs? 
</P>
<P>
	Policies similar to Clinton administration, 54 percent;  
different policies and programs, 41 percent. (Pew poll) 

</P>
<P>
	--Please tell me whether the following statement applies to Al  
Gore. He has high personal moral and ethical standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 67 percent; no, 18 percent; don't know, 15 percent.  
(ABC/Washington Post) 

</P>
<P>
	--Please tell me whether the following statement applies to Al  
Gore. He is a strong leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 41 percent; no, 47 percent; don't know, 12 percent.  
(ABC/Washington Post) 

</P>
<P>
	--Please tell me whether the following statement applies to Al  
Gore. He has new ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 47 percent; No, 36 percent; Don't know, 17 percent.  
(ABC/Washington Post) 

</P>
<P>
	--How much chance is there that you would vote for the following  
person if he/she is a candidate for president in 2000 -- is there a 
good chance, some chance or no chance? 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore: Good chance, 22 percent; some chance, 30 percent; no  
chance, 45 percent. (Pew poll) 

</P>
<P>
	The ABC/Post poll of 1,515 adults was conducted March 11-14. The  
Pew poll of 1,203 adults was taken Feb. 18-21. Both had error 
margins of plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
