<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:41:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jenny Jones' Case Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A sociologist said she told  
representatives of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' that having guests 
reveal intimate secrets could lead to violence -- and her warning 
was laughed at. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was a superficial, callous response to what they  
were doing with these people,'' Maryaltani Karpos, a University of 
Miami professor of criminology and sociology, testified Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Karpos said she gave the unsolicited warning a year before a  
gay guest was slain after admitting on the show that he had a crush 
on a heterosexual acquaintance. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Amedure's family has filed a $50 million wrongful death  
lawsuit naming the show, its distributor and producer. The lawsuit 
contends the show's ``ambush'' tactics humiliated Jonathan Schmitz 
and drove him to shoot Amedure in March 1995, three days after they 
appeared on the program. The episode never aired. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was invited on the show to meet a secret admirer only to  
discover it was Amedure. He was convicted of Amedure's murder, but 
the verdict was overturned due to an error in jury selection. His 
retrial is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial was in recess until Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Karpos said she spoke to the representatives by phone after  
recoiling at a ``Jenny Jones'' episode. She said she believes 
exposing secrets on camera can lead to an increased potential for 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``These emotions, once they are called for, don't just dissipate  
once you turn off the camera,'' she testified. ``There's some 
danger inherent in the period of time that follows the show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When questioned by defense lawyer James Feeney, Ms. Karpos  
acknowledged she had never done investigative work or primary 
research in relation to televised talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	In other testimony, a former emergency dispatcher said that  
Schmitz was sobbing and repeatedly mentioned ``The Jenny Jones 
Show'' when he called 911 just moments after the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It broke my heart to hear him,'' said Mary Jones, a former  
Auburn Hills police dispatcher. ``What stood out was he was upset. 
Jenny Jones, national television -- those were the things that kept 
coming up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who is not being sued, is expected to testify  
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:32:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Matadors Part-Owner Sues Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Robert Alterman, a minority owner of the Miami  
Matadors minor league hockey team, filed suit Friday against two of 
his partners for fraud, saying he was misled about how much the 
partners had invested in the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Alterman is seeking to recover his $500,000 investment in the  
team and an injunction keeping the team from being sold until the 
ownership dispute is resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the best scenario for him to get value out of the money he  
invested would be to take control of the team, that would be a 
scenario he would consider,'' said Alvin Lodish, Alterman's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Alterman is one of four people recruited by team president Bob  
Snyder and Robert Davis to bring the East Coast Hockey League team 
from Louisville, Ky., to South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the suit, Alterman agreed to join the purchasing  
group last November after being told by Snyder that they had 
combined to invest $875,000 in the partnership. He was given a 20 
percent stake in the team. 
</P>
<P>
	A subsequent review by Alterman's accountant found that Snyder  
and Davis had contributed just $130,000 in cash to the project, 
with much of the rest attributed to ``sweat equity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alterman also accused the partnership of violating its own  
agreement by negotiating to sell the team without his consent. The 
agreement states the team shall not be sold without the consent of 
more than 80 percent of the limited partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder has acknowledged that he is talking with a buyer who  
wants to move the team out of South Florida. An agreement could 
come within the next couple of months, he said, adding that the 
team likely would take next season off before playing in a new 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder called Alterman's lawsuit ``just an internal matter that  
we'll settle. Any conversations will remain internal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Matadors have struggled at the gate, ranking last in the  
27-team ECHL with an average of just 1,383 per game. Two games were 
moved out of Miami Arena to local ice rinks in an effort to save 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami failed to make the playoffs, meaning Friday night's game  
against Jacksonville likely was the team's final appearance in 
South Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
