<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Appeals Internet Porn Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Justice Department appealed a judge's  
ruling that blocked enforcement of a federal Internet pornography 
law. Government lawyers had until today to decide whether to appeal 
U.S. District Judge Lowell A. Reed's Feb. 1 preliminary injunction 
barring enforcement of the Child Online Protection Act. The law, 
signed into law by President Clinton last year, would require 
commercial Web sites to collect a credit card number or some other 
access code as proof of age before allowing Internet users to view 
online material deemed ``harmful to minors.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Hits 29-Year Low  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate fell to a  
29-year low of 4.2 percent in March, with Hispanics and high school 
dropouts among the groups registering the most dramatic 
improvement. ``This is a historic report,'' Labor Secretary Alexis 
Herman said. ``It's an indication this is an economy that is 
lifting all boats.'' The rate for Hispanics fell from 6.7 percent 
to 5.8 percent, the lowest since the Labor Department began 
calculating a rate for the group in 1973. The improvement in the 
rate, from 4.4 percent in February, came despite the smallest 
seasonally adjusted increase in three years in the number of jobs -- 
46,000. That's the fewest since an outright decline in payrolls in 
January 1996 when a blizzard struck the Northeast. Economists 
attributed much of the latest deceleration in job growth to the 
weather rather rather than to any significant deterioration in the 
economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Gates Pledges $1.5M for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and his wife,  
Melinda, have pledged $1.5 million to aid Kosovo refugees. The 
pledge from the William H. Gates Foundation includes $500,000 each 
to three charities: the American Red Cross International Response 
Fund, CARE and the International Rescue Committee. 

</P>
<P>
	'Melissa' Virus Suspect Nabbed  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A central New Jersey man has been arrested  
and charged with originating the virus known as Melissa that 
disrupted e-mail communications worldwide. The New Jersey state 
attorney general's office announced that David L. Smith, 30, of 
Aberdeen, was arrested last night, and that the virus originated 
from his home. It also said Smith faces various charges, including 
interruption of public communications. Attorney General Peter 
Verniero said that altogether, the charges carry a maximum penalty 
of 40 years in prison and a $480,000 fine. Smith was released on 
$100,000 bail and was scheduled to appear in state Superior Court 
in Monmouth County on Monday for arraignment. 

</P>
<P>
	BMW, Hyundai Sell More Cars in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- BMW and Hyundai Motor Co. posted significant  
sales gains in the United States last month, while Mazda Motor 
Corp. sustained a double-digit decline. The sales figures released 
today followed strong reports yesterday by DaimlerChrysler AG, 
Toyota Motor Corp., Honda Motor Co. and several other major 
automakers. The good showing by the industry in March and the first 
quarter is another sign of the strength of the U.S. economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Peritus Software President Quits  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The president of Peritus Software Services is  
resigning, the business software maker announced today. The 
company, which is based in Billerica, Mass, is also laying off 40 
people, mainly in sales and marketing, and taking a $250,000 charge 
against earnings. Chief financial officer John Giordano will take 
over the president's title from Dominic Chan, who is leaving. 
Peritus expects to post a loss for the quarter ended March 31 of up 
to $2.5 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Chip-Making Industry Feels Pinch  
</P>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- Worldwide shipments of equipment  
used to make computer chips fell 21 percent last year due to the 
Asian slowdown and an oversupply of smaller wafers and a delay in 
making the transition to larger wafers. ``The totals for 1998 
confirm what we knew and felt all year. 1998 was a tough year,'' 
said Stanley T. Myers, president of Semiconductor Equipment and 
Materials International. SEMI represents the businesses that 
manufacture the equipment used to make computer chips. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong Gov't. Gives Tax Rebates  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- For once, Hong Kong residents are looking  
forward to getting mail from the tax department. As part of the 
government's efforts to stimulate this territory's shrinking 
economy, taxpayers in Hong Kong started getting checks this week 
equal to 10 percent of what they had paid for income and profit 
taxes for the fiscal year ended Tuesday. Hong Kong's beleaguered 
retailers and restaurant owners are hoping the unprecedented rebate 
would give them a much-needed boost, but experts are divided how 
much good it will do. 

</P>
<P>
	Inprise Group Execs Quit Suddenly  
</P>
<P>
	SCOTTS VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Without notice or explanation, the  
chief executive officer and chief financial officer of Inprise 
Corp. -- which was Borland International until last year -- have quit 
the company. The resignations of CEO Delbert Yocam, a well-regarded 
veteran of Apple Computer Inc., and financial officer Kathleen 
Fisher raised concerns among financial analysts about the company, 
which makes software for businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Markets Closed Today  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock and most commodity markets were closed  
today in the United States and many other countries in observance 
of Good Friday. U.S. bond markets closed at noon and some commodity 
markets held abbreviated morning sessions. Government offices and 
most banks were open. Stocks closed mostly higher yesterday, with 
the Dow Jones industrials up 46.35 at 9,832.51 and the Nasdaq 
composite index up 31.97 at 2,493.37. 

</P>
