<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery Surrounds Louis Farrakhan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Is Louis Farrakhan, leader of the Nation of  
Islam, ``recuperating nicely'' from prostate cancer, as Jesse 
Jackson put it? Is he alert and looking forward to going home from 
Howard University Hospital? Or is he, as a Chicago associate says, 
seriously ill? 
</P>
<P>
	A tightlipped hospital staff, conflicting medical reports and  
the Nation of Islam's customary secrecy on its internal affairs are 
combining to raise more questions than to provide answers about the 
health of the 65-year-old Farrakhan, who is recovering from surgery 
he underwent on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan, who has won both worldwide praise and scorn during  
his 20 controversial years at the helm of the Nation of Islam, was 
flown from his Illinois home to the hospital here Tuesday night for 
the emergency surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan, organizer of the nation's largest black gathering in  
history, the Million Man March on Washington in 1995, remained in 
the hospital on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But little beyond that is certain.  
</P>
<P>
	Other than confirming Farrakhan is a patient, the hospital won't  
release information on his condition. And security is so tight on 
his hospital floor that even doctors who aren't working on his case 
are being asked to stay away, said a hospital source. 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the surgery, the Nation of Islam released a  
statement that Farrakhan was stable, resting and that his prognosis 
was excellent. Civil rights leader Jackson issued his own statement 
saying he visited with Farrakhan who was ``recuperating nicely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a report published in The Washington Post on Friday quoted a  
hospital source as saying Farrakhan was more seriously ill than 
Nation of Islam officials were letting on. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard F. Muhammad, Farrakhan's son-in-law and chief of staff,  
called the Post report totally inaccurate and said Farrakhan is 
alert and looked forward to leaving the hospital shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	``His spirits are good. He would like to see visitors but the  
doctors have recommended against that for now,'' Muhammad said. 
``He is very stable and his condition has only improved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conflicting reports have some Nation of Islam members and  
supporters deeply concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 black ministers in Chicago, Farrakhan's home city,  
are organizing a multi-church prayer service on Easter. A Nation of 
Islam source in Chicago said he heard that prayer services were 
being scheduled in at least seven other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are concerned for him because the situation is serious,''  
said a Chicago source, requesting anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muslim leader is beloved by many in the black community as  
an uncompromising voice in the fight for black empowerment. At the 
same time, Farrakhan has also drawn the contempt of many for 
statements against whites, Jews and gays. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan's fiery rhetoric has singed not only his opponents but  
also some who have attempted to move closer to him politically. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Kweisi Mfume, then chairman of the Congressional Black  
Caucus, announced the group had formed a ``sacred covenant'' with 
Farrakhan and civil rights groups to develop strategies to combat 
inner-city crime and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mfume was forced to back away when some caucus members said  
they weren't apprised of any arrangement with the Nation of Islam 
and disapproved of some of Farrakhan's language. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe Minister Farrakhan is perhaps the most authentic  
voice for the black disaffected in America,'' said Arthur Magida, 
author of Prophet of Rage, a Farrakhan biography published in 1996. 
``But what detracts from his legacy is his tendency to portray 
blacks as victims of themselves, of whites and of Jewish America.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
