<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 10:13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Osgood Celebrates 5 Years As Host </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A while back, Charles Osgood returned from a  
trip to learn that one of his ``Sunday Morning'' colleagues had 
taken a job over at ``The CBS Evening News.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After wishing him well, Osgood mentioned how, ``in the past 24  
hours, at least 20 people sought me out to tell me they love 
`Sunday Morning.' 
</P>
<P>
	``Do me a favor: Let me know the first time someone tells you  
they love `The Evening News.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Osgood tags this little story with a rascally laugh. Meaning:  
It's nice, really nice, to be part of something people don't just 
value, but adore. And have, for a long time. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, ``CBS News Sunday Morning'' marked two gracious  
decades on the air. Now April brings another milestone: Osgood's 
fifth anniversary as host. 
</P>
<P>
	In retrospect, it seems obvious that no one but Osgood could  
have followed Charles Kuralt, who in 1994 decided to step down from 
the broadcast he inspired and, after 37 years, to retire from CBS 
News. (He died in 1997.) 
</P>
<P>
	But Osgood says he had no designs on Kuralt's ``Sunday Morning''  
stool, ``and it never for a second occurred to me that someone 
would ask me to do that show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there were some people who thought I was a poor  
choice,'' he adds, ``but most of the audience has been supportive 
from the very beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Small wonder. Like Kuralt before him, Osgood comes across as  
erudite, yet folksy. A gentleman without a trace of la-di-da. An 
optimist. Someone pleasant-looking, but clearly put on camera to do 
more than look good. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Osgood has been invisible for much of his career. His  
background is principally in radio -- and that's where the bulk of 
his duties remains. Monday through Friday, he arises at 2:30 a.m. 
to prepare his ``Osgood Files'' news commentaries, which air on CBS 
Radio at 6:25, 7:25, 8:25 and 9:25 a.m. EST. 
</P>
<P>
	But each Sunday, after what he sugarcoats as ``sleeping in''  
until 5:30, Osgood arrives at CBS' Studio 45 and takes his place on 
the familiar terraced set. Seated beside his brawny easel, 
surrounded by Plexiglas panels branded with suns, he welcomes 
viewers to ``Sunday Morning'' at 9 a.m., then gently guides the 
broadcast through its 90 sublime minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Equipped with a voice that ripples like an underground stream  
and, more often than not, with a bow tie, the 66-year-old Osgood 
plays host to stories on Janet Reno or an opera star, on a new 
Broadway play or schoolgirls learning science. Then he introduces 
footage of saguaro cactuses. Just because. 
</P>
<P>
	Osgood also does the occasional story himself, with a feature on  
tap each Sunday in April. This week, he profiles Felipe Alou, 
Dominican manager of the Montreal Expos baseball team. 
</P>
<P>
	``But my role as host is pretty much that,'' Osgood says. ``I'm  
just one of the troops.'' For that, he won a 1998 Peabody Award -- 
known as broadcasting's Pulitzer Prize. 
</P>
<P>
	Osgood's entry into television was groundbreaking, and somewhat  
of a flop. He was general manager of the nation's first pay-TV 
service, marketed to viewers in Hartford, Conn., in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	Zenith had invented an over-the-air system called Phonevision.  
``It had a lot going for it,'' recalls Osgood. Then he smiles at 
its all-too-many shortcomings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would only work in black-and-white and took three hours to  
install. And if a plane flew overhead or a truck drove by, that 
would interfere not only with the picture, but with the 
(unscrambling) code, which would shut you down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few months, Osgood was shut down, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Lucking into a job at ABC News in Manhattan, the man born  
Charles Osgood Wood dropped his surname (the network already had a 
newsman named Charles Woods) and, on the air as Charles Osgood, 
spent four years reporting for ABC radio and TV. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1967, he took a job as reporter on the CBS-owned WCBS  
Newsradio 88. Then, one fateful weekend, he was summoned to fill in 
at the anchor desk for the TV network's Saturday newscast. He had 
never before anchored anything on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the broadcast was over, I got a phone call from Mike  
Wallace, whom I had met only a couple of times: 'Charlie, I have 
some things I have to tell you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Reviewing the tape of Osgood's TV debut, Wallace was typically  
direct: ``You look as if you're about to be executed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Osgood's self-appointed tutor wasn't finished. ``I'm gonna tell  
you something that nobody at CBS News will tell you: This is an 
acting job. You have to play the part.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The advice took.  
</P>
<P>
	``I really came to understand what he was talking about,''  
Osgood says. ``Nobody knows everything, but you have to project an 
air of authority -- and without talking down to the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	``After my second week, he called and said, `That was MUCH  
better.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971, Osgood joined the CBS network. He hasn't been lectured  
to since. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`DENNIS MILLER LIVE': Comic and brand-new sitcom star Norm  
Macdonald is this week's guest on ``Dennis Miller Live.'' Macdonald 
will discuss ``Bad Taste'' when the show airs live tonight at 11:30 
EST on HBO. The Emmy-winning series is a showcase for Miller's 
freewheeling commentaries. Each program includes a monologue, a 
rant about the week's topic, a chat with a celebrity or expert 
guest, viewer call-ins and a wrap-up of the week's events. (Other 
playdates: Sunday at 11:55 p.m. EDT and April 7 at 1:10 a.m. EDT). 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
