<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:34:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Pay the Cost of Higher Salaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The cost of those high baseball salaries is  
going straight to the fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The average price of a ticket increased 9.7 percent this year,  
from $13.59 to $14.91, according to the Team Marketing Report, 
which released its annual study Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox, who play in Fenway Park, the smallest stadium in  
the major leagues, remained the most expensive ticket in baseball 
after raising prices 16.6 percent to an average of $24.05 
</P>
<P>
	The World Series champion New York Yankees were once again  
second after a 13.8 percent rise to $23.33. The cost of the best 
box seats at Yankee Stadium has gone up from $25 in 1996 to $50 
this season. In addition, the Yankees last year added 60 
field-level seats that cost $16,000 per season -- $197.53 a game. 
The price of those seats remain unchanged this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle, which moves from the Kingdome to Safeco Field on July  
15, had the highest increase, a 27.2 percent rise to $19.01. The 
New York Mets raised prices 23.5 percent to an average of $19.98, 
Philadelphia 21.2 percent to $13.60, the Chicago Cubs 21.1 percent 
to $17.46 and Texas 20.9 percent to $19.93. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota again has the cheapest average ticket price, even  
after a 2.9 percent increase to $8.46. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal, which decreased its average price 6 percent to $9.38,  
was 29th and Cincinnati was 28th at $9.71 after a 16 percent 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Expos, two other teams lowered their average  
prices, with Oakland going down 4.5 percent to $10.10 and Tampa Bay 
going down 3.1 percent to $15.08. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's average ticket price has gone up 42.6 percent since  
the 1994 strike, when it was $10.45. The average has increased 72.6 
percent from 1991, when TMR began its annual studies. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, the Consumer Price Index has gone up 1.0 percent  
in the last year, 12.1 percent since 1994 and 18.7 percent since 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the increases, baseball tickets remain far cheaper than  
seats for the other major U.S. sports. NFL ticket prices rose 4.7 
percent last season to $42.86, NBA prices went up 3.4 percent this 
season to $42.54 and NHL prices went up 2.5 percent to $42.79. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL tickets have increased 70 percent since 1991 and NBA tickets  
have gone up 83 percent since the 1991-92 season. TMR's NHL studies 
go back only to 1994-95. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fan Cost Index, which includes two average-price tickets,  
two average-price child tickets, four small soft drinks, two small 
beers, four hot dogs, parking, two programs and two adult caps, 
increased 6.8 percent to $121.36. The Yankees remained No. 1 in the 
index at $166.84, followed by Boston ($160.21) and the Mets 
($154.58). 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal had the lowest index at $87.87, with Oakland 29th at  
$92.78 and Milwaukee 28th at $95.81. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's average was $244.98 last season. The NBA is at $240.26  
this season, the NHL at $238.97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 00:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grissom: `I Feel Young Again' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- He looks like the center fielder of old, and for  
Marquis Grissom, that means very, very young. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I'm a young man again,'' said Grissom, who  
refurbished his body and refashioned his mind this offseason after 
a year marked by physical breakdowns and mental fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't time that caught up with Grissom last season as much  
as it was his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think playing with injuries, he just realized that he  
shouldn't have done it, because it just hurt him more than it 
helped him,'' Milwaukee Brewers general manager Sal Bando said. 
``He wanted to set an example and he knows he's got that reputation 
of being a gamer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom, 31, was bothered much of last season by a high  
hamstring strain that forced him to alter his batting stance, his 
running style and his defensive techniques, which resulted in a bad 
back and a sore right throwing shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a mess,'' said Grissom, who managed to stay off the  
disabled list and appear in 142 games nevertheless. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the first time in his career, Grissom looked like an old  
man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I shouldn't have been out there,'' Grissom admitted. ``It all  
started with my heel in Cleveland (in 1997). I didn't rehab it and 
then I strained my hamstring. The last two years, I've been at 
about 50 or 60 percent. Last year it just caught up with me. My 
speed left. Balls were falling. Guys were running on me. People 
said my skills were eroding. I knew I was hurt and I didn't want to 
accept it. All those things are reversed now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't just Grissom's body that was hurting last year,  
either. 
</P>
<P>
	He was bogged down mentally and emotionally from the loss of his  
sister, Mary, to AIDS, and his separation from Tia, the mother of 
his three children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mentally, I feel like I was at 10 percent,'' Grissom said.  
``It's been a rough ride these last two years, both on the inside 
and the outside, being beat up and worn down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first thing Grissom did in the offseason after ironing  
things out with Tia was let all his injuries heal with the help of 
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, on Dec. 21, he hired a personal trainer to work on speed,  
agility balance, diet and nutrition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was mad, stuck in traffic, cursing. But I realized it's just  
something I had to do,'' Grissom said. ``I owe those guys big-time. 
I tell them they put me back together again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like all the king's horses and all the king's men.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best thing that ever happened to me,'' Grissom said  
of his work at Pro Train in suburban Atlanta. ``It's definitely a 
place I'll be at every year after this season. Now I feel good, eat 
good, sleep good. Now my goal is to spend 10 more years 
competing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom's renewal was evident from Day 1 at camp as he stretched  
doubles into triples, chased down balls in the gap and nailed 
runners trying to test his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to be here without feeling sore every day,'' Grissom  
said. ``Last year I had doubts if I could go out and do these 
things. But no more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bando said the difference in Grissom's game is amazing.  
</P>
<P>
	``I see a player that everyone else saw three years ago,'' Bando  
said. ``I don't know if he'll get the young legs back, but he'll 
obviously have better legs than he had last year and hopefully less 
injuries. He's still a young man now. He's not by any means at the 
end of his career or on the down cycle of his career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom said he enjoys the game like he used to.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm physically healthy. I'm eating right, working out right,  
running right. It's been wonderful,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like a kid again. I feel like I belong. I feel like my  
head's back out there with confidence. My kids are fine. Their 
mother and I get along, everything's great. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be all right this year.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
