<DOCNO> APW19990402.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:36:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Some Want Allies To Contribute More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Italy and France are contributing about 40  
warplanes apiece to the NATO war effort in Yugoslavia, while the 
Netherlands is providing 16 F-16 jet fighters, Turkey has chipped 
in 11, Belgium 10, Norway six. All told, America's NATO allies have 
earmarked more than 200 planes to operation Allied Force, roughly 
the same as the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some analysts feel the United States is shouldering a  
disproportionate share of NATO's burden, both in the current effort 
and in general. Some even believe the Europeans ought to deal with 
the Kosovo problem with no effort at all by Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sooner or later, we have to say (to the Europeans) that if the  
Russians attack, we are with you. But the brush fires are your 
responsibility,'' said David Acheson, president and chief executive 
officer of the Atlantic Council, a pro-NATO grouping. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon defends the American role in the air war and the  
European contribution to it, and does not consider the U.S. 
contribution disproportionate. 
</P>
<P>
	Helmut Sonnenfeldt, who monitors NATO issues from the Brookings  
Institution, says the equivalency in the number of planes between 
the U.S. and its allies in the Balkan war effort overstates the 
allies' contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	This comparison, he says, fails to account for the  
sophistication of some of the American aircraft -- each 
high-performance F-117 bomber costs $45 million, for example -- 
compared with the Europeans' planes, mostly the far cheaper F-16's. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Tomas Valasek of the Center for Defense Information:  
``Nobody has what the U.S. has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenfeldt also notes that only Britain among the European  
allies is capable of firing a sea-based cruise missile. The U.S. 
has six cruise missile-capable vessels deployed for Yugoslavia 
duty. 
</P>
<P>
	For some allied countries, participation in the Yugoslav war  
effort is out of the question. Luxembourg, for example, has no air 
force. Iceland has no military at all. 
</P>
<P>
	France's military budget, at $47 billion, is second among NATO  
allies to that of the United States, at $267 billion. Germany is 
third at $42 billion, according to CIA estimates. Given this 
century's history, there is little sympathy on either side of the 
Atlantic for a significant increase in German defense spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding just how much each NATO country should contribute to  
the alliance has never been an exact science. The United States 
spends about 3.4 percent of its gross national product on defense 
while the remaining allies spend an average of about 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans can justify the discrepancy by pointing out that  
the United States has security responsibilities well beyond Europe 
-- Japan and the Korean peninsula being the most noteworthy 
examples. 
</P>
<P>
	A counterargument is that the United States has only slightly  
more than half of the population of its 18 NATO allies combined yet 
the defense spending of these allies amounts to only about 60 
percent of the U.S. defense budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Acheson, son of the late Dean Acheson, a NATO founding father  
and former secretary of state, likens Europe to a dependent 
incapable of acting alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans ``ought to provide the forces, capability and the  
money to keep order in Europe,'' said Acheson, emphasizing that he 
was speaking for himself and not his organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Europeans lack the will because they always have looked to  
the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Kupchan, of the Council on Foreign Relations, says it's  
illusory to suppose the Europeans could handle the Yugoslavia 
operation on their own, saying they lack the intelligence 
capabilities and satellite reconnaissance. 
</P>
<P>
	Another source of concern is that the Europeans are reducing  
their defense spending while the Clinton administration, after 
slashing military spending for years, is planning sizable 
increases. This, presumably, will accelerate European dependence on 
its big neighbor to the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenfeldt says European defense thinking is still largely  
based on the Cold War era concept that large armies are needed to 
ward off a ground invasion from the East. 
</P>
<P>
	But he says he is encouraged by a British-French initiative that  
would let European Union countries act independently while 
retaining their role within NATO. The initiative was a recognition 
of Europe's need to handle crises when the United States does not 
get involved. Washington has welcomed the plan enthusiastically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:36:04 </DATE_TIME>
