<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alomar Happy To Put '98 Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Sandy Alomar remembers the jokes back in 1990  
when the San Diego Padres traded him to the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	``People would say to me, `You're going to Cleveland?' Now  
everybody wants to go to Cleveland,'' he said. ``It's been the 
comeback city of the century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Cleveland is hoping Alomar can make a comeback of his own.  
</P>
<P>
	Nagging injuries contributed to an awful 1998 season for  
Cleveland's six-time All-Star catcher. When the Indians' year ended 
in New York last October with a Game 6 loss in the AL championship 
series, Alomar was in so much pain he could barely make it to his 
clubhouse locker. 
</P>
<P>
	He had only been able to play that night after receiving an  
epidural block to ease the pain in his lower body. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so numb I couldn't feel my legs,'' he said. ``I was  
afraid of tripping running down to first base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With his left knee constantly throbbing and his back tight,  
Alomar batted just .235 -- his lowest average since 1991 -- with six 
homers and 44 RBIs in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	Those aren't the worst numbers in baseball history, but they  
came after a storybook season in 1997 when every ball he hit fell 
in and every big moment for the Indians' seemed to be Alomar's, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
	He played through the pain last year, somehow managing to stay  
off the disabled list while playing 117 games. After undergoing 
arthroscopic surgery on his knee in late October, he decided to 
stay away from baseball and didn't catch, throw or hit this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he rehabilitated the knee and worked out with hopes of  
catching 125 games this year. 
</P>
<P>
	He's healthy, he's happy and although he's not hitting this  
spring, Alomar has put the problems of 1998 behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really looking forward to this season,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the biggest reasons for Alomar's happiness is that he has  
been reunited this year with his brother, Robbie, the Indians' new 
second baseman. The two were teammates for seven games with San 
Diego in '90 before Sandy was dealt to Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having Robbie around is really going to help Sandy this  
season,'' first baseman Jim Thome said. ``It's great for us, but I 
think it's even better for Sandy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It'll certainly cut down on the Alomar brothers' phone bills.  
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Sandy, an emotional player, has taken his hitting  
slumps badly. It wouldn't be uncommon for him to call Robbie for 
advice following an 0-for-3 night. 
</P>
<P>
	All he has to do now is walk across the clubhouse.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to really hit me until we go out on the field  
(on opening day) and they say, `play ball,''' Sandy said. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Sandy has been working with Indians hitting coach  
Charlie Manuel on being more patient at the plate. By taking more 
pitches, Alomar hopes to get ahead in the count and create better 
hitting situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of my problem is I make contact,'' he said. ``I don't  
strike out much. Charlie and I talked and he said, `You've got a 
good problem.' What happened last year was I made contact early in 
the count. Late in the count I'm a pretty good defensive hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when you're hitting good balls early in the count, your  
batting average is going to suffer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being more selective with what he swings at,  
Alomar is trying to delay when he swings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm letting the ball get deeper in the zone,'' he said. ``so I  
can see it longer.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:14:24 </DATE_TIME>
