<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:30:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jerusalem Pilgrims Mark Good Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Thousands of pilgrims, some clutching large  
wooden crosses, walked through the rosemary-scented alleys of 
Jerusalem's Old City in a Good Friday procession today, retracing 
Jesus' step to his crucifixion. 
</P>
<P>
	Franciscan monks led pilgrims from around the world along the  
Via Dolorosa, or Way of Sorrows, which begins at the traditional 
site of Jesus' trial and ends at the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, 
believed to be built over the place of his crucifixion and burial. 
</P>
<P>
	Worshippers sang hymns and read prayers in Arabic, Italian,  
English and several other languages. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been my dream to get here and now after 60 years I  
finally made it,'' said Vinge Bester from Arlington, Va., as she 
and other members of her tour group joined the slow procession. 
</P>
<P>
	A California group re-enacted Jesus' last walk in full costume,  
with one man dressed as Jesus, crowned with thorns and his face 
streaked with blood. 
</P>
<P>
	The man playing Jesus, Gilbert Peru, collapsed from time to time  
under the weight of the cross as actors dressed as Roman soldiers 
whipped his bare back. ``Help him, he is innocent!'' shouted Joanne 
Petraella, a pilgrim portraying the Virgin Mary. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, the procession halted as tens of thousands of  
Muslims made their way home from noon prayers at the Al Aqsa 
Mosque, just a few yards from the Via Dolorosa. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some pushing and shoving as Christian and Muslim  
worshippers tried to squeeze through the congested alleys. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the Via Dolorosa, stations marked the events of Jesus'  
final walk. Worshippers stopped at each point to read aloud what 
happened, first in Latin, then in English. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli troops with assault rifles were posted along the route.  
The Old City, part of the city sector claimed by the Palestinians 
as a future capital, is traditionally an area of tension. 
</P>
<P>
	The procession ended at the Church of the Holy Sepulcher where  
pilgrims prayed over the marble slab where tradition says Jesus was 
laid after his death. Some were moved to tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel blessed,'' said 70 year-old Mary Lois Mullen from New  
York City. Last year, Mullen's trip to Jerusalem was canceled 
because organizers thought it was too dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	Mullen said she felt safe and was planning to visit the biblical  
West Bank town of Bethlehem in December to attend millennium 
celebrations. ``I figure the Lord won't let harm come to us while 
we are here,'' said Mullen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
