<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Defense Rests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The criminal trial of Whitewater figure  
Susan McDougal is expected to go to the jury early next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense rested Friday after getting an unusual endorsement  
from a woman charged by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's 
prosecutors. Julie Hiatt Steele testified that she, too, was 
indicted because she refused to give false testimony against 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal was indicted on charges of criminal contempt and  
obstruction of justice after she refused to answer federal grand 
jury questions about Clinton and his wife, Hillary, in the 
Whitewater investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	She testified for five days during the month-old trial and  
contended, among other things, that the prosecutor in her 1996 
fraud trial offered her a deal if she would give Starr's office 
something on the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Jahn, who helped prosecute the 1996 case, is expected to  
testify Monday to rebut Mrs. McDougal's testimony. The case could 
go to the jury Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, who testified Friday against the advice of her  
lawyer, told reporters, ``I came here today because Susan and I 
have both been relentlessly pursued by the Office of Independent 
Counsel. I believe everybody in America needs to know about this, 
and that it could happen to anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele has been charged with lying to grand jurors  
investigating former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey's claim 
that Clinton made an unwelcome sexual advance toward her in 1993. 
Ms. Steele's testimony undercut part of Mrs. Willey's account. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, 52, of Richmond, Va., told jurors that after  
testifying before two grand juries, she was ``invited to a secret 
meeting at the office of the independent counsel to clarify my 
testimony. I believed I was to support Kathleen Willey's version of 
the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, she said, ``I couldn't do it. I left the meeting in tears.  
I didn't know anything to tell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele said despite what she considered her minor role in  
the case, which grew out of the Monica Lewinsky investigation, 
prosecutors questioned one of her daughters, her brother, her 
former attorney and her neighbors and friends. Ms. Steele said she 
was upset that some family members also were asked about the 
adoption of her son Adam, now 8, from Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to a prosecutor's questions, Ms. Steele acknowledged  
that she first told a reporter for Newsweek magazine a story that 
supported Willey's account, then recanted. She admitted that within 
days of talking to the reporter, she sold a photograph of Clinton 
and Mrs. Willey to the National Enquirer for $9,000. She said she 
needed the money for her son's special-needs schooling. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courtroom, McDougal lawyer Mark Geragos contended  
that prosecutors aggressively pursued Ms. Steele even after she 
passed a lie-detector test and Clinton's accuser, Mrs. Willey, 
failed one. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors accepted Mrs. Willey's word ``because they liked her  
story,'' Geragos said. He could not say who administered the 
polygraph tests or offer more detail about the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's attorneys have asserted in court in Virginia that  
polygraph test results undermine the credibility of some 
prosecution witnesses, but they did not elaborate and would not 
comment Friday. Polygraph tests are seldom admissible in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey's lawyer, Daniel Gecker, did not return telephone  
calls seeking comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 10:53:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Witness Testifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Called to bolster Susan McDougal's  
complaints of unfair tactics, another woman indicted by Whitewater 
prosecutors testified today that she was pressured to back up the 
story of a presidential accuser and charged with crimes when she 
refused to lie. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual twist, Julie Hiatt Steele took the stand to say  
she was charged with obstruction of justice and making false 
statements after she refused to support the story of Kathleen 
Willey, who said President Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance 
toward her in 1993. Clinton has denied it under oath. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here today because Susan and I have both been  
relentlessly pursued by the office of independent counsel,'' Ms. 
Steele told reporters after her testimony. ``The people need to 
know this and that it could happen to anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's defense attorney, Mark Geragos, contended  
prosecutors aggressively pursued Ms. Steele even after she passed a 
lie detector test and Clinton's accuser, Mrs. Willey, failed one. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that she passed a polygraph test, and  
there's no question that Kathleen Willey failed a polygraph test,'' 
Geragos said outside the courtroom. He did not say who administered 
the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's attorneys have asserted in court in Alexandria,  
Va., that polygraph test results undermine the credibility of some 
prosecution witnesses, but they did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey's attorney could not be reached immediately for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Polygraph test results are not ordinarily admissible in court,  
but Mrs. Steele's lawyers could argue they are entitled to use the 
results to call into question the credibility of any Starr witness 
who testifies against her. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, who goes on trial May 3, testified that she could  
have saved herself $500,000 in legal bills ``by changing my story'' 
to support Mrs. Willey's version of events. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ms. Steele said she had lied about the case once -- to a  
Newsweek reporter investigating the Willey matter -- ``and felt 
horribly guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to lie anymore,'' Ms. Steele said under  
questioning by a defense lawyer. She was composed and assertive 
during her two hours on the witness stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey has said she confided in Ms. Steele about the  
Clinton encounter right after it happened. Ms. Steele has testified 
repeatedly that her friend didn't say anything like that to her 
back in 1993 but later asked Ms. Steele to lie to Newsweek and say 
she was told. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors, however, said they have evidence that Ms. Steele  
was told the story in 1993 -- statements by her friends who say she 
shared the tale with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Julie Myers asked Ms. Steele whether she had also  
told the story to the National Enquirer and Time magazine. Ms. 
Steele denied selling the story but admitted selling a photograph 
of Mrs. Willey and the president to the publications. She said she 
was embarrassed about it but needed the $9,000 for her son's 
special-needs schooling. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr investigated Mrs. Willey's  
allegation as part of the Monica Lewinsky matter. 
</P>
<P>
	After testifying before two grand juries, Ms. Steele said that  
in November 1998 she was ``invited to a secret meeting at the 
office of the independent counsel to clarify my testimony. I 
believed I was to support Kathleen Willey's version of the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Were you able to do that? asked defense attorney Mark Geragos.  
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't do it. I left the meeting in tears. I didn't know  
anything,'' she replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele was called by attorneys for Mrs. McDougal, who is on  
trial on charges of criminal contempt and obstruction of justice 
for refusing twice to answer federal grand jury questions about the 
Clintons' business dealings. Mrs. McDougal said she feared Starr 
would charge her with perjury if she didn't say what he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard decided to allow limited  
testimony from Ms. Steele ``to show modus operandi'' of Starr and 
his deputies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, who lives in Richmond, Va., said despite what she  
considered her minor role in the case, prosecutors questioned one 
of her daughters, her brother, her former attorney and her 
neighbors and friends. She said a grand jury subpoenaed her 
daughter's boyfriend and even ``asked if he had sex with me.'' The 
judge ordered jurors to disregard that remark. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele said she was upset that some family members also were  
asked about the adoption of her son Adam, now 8, from Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
