<DOCNO> APW19990402.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:43:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Campaign Focuses on Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore's presidential bid should be helped by  
the strong economy and the public's generally favorable view of 
Democratic positions on domestic issues. But polls suggest he needs 
to show he's a strong leader and a compelling candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president's advisers are developing a two-pronged  
strategy to address the problems: to let Gore tell his personal 
story to voters, and to project him as a leader separate from 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	They've started on the first chore, but the job of  
differentiating Gore from his boss is trickier given Clinton's 
identification with popular policies at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Gore advisers say privately that aides are debating how  
to make him look more presidential and how far in advance of the 
2000 election they have to start. Some suggest this be done soon to 
soothe supporters in light of Texas Republican Gov. George W. 
Bush's advantage in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	They've been testing some approaches such as Gore's small-scale  
initiatives to improve the quality of American life in areas such 
as traffic jams and clean drinking water. He's also said he would 
expand on Clinton education initiatives by limiting class sizes and 
providing preschool programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vice presidents have the strategic problem of trying to  
separate themselves as independent of the person they've served 
with,'' said Charles Jones, a presidential scholar, retired from 
the University of Wisconsin who has been teaching in Oxford, 
England. ``President Clinton has tried to use him more as a 
counselor, but the things Gore has been in charge of are not 
exactly sexy. Reinventing government is not the kind of thing you'd 
see on a bumper sticker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publicly, Gore aides dismiss head-to-head matchups that show  
Gore trailing Republicans like Bush and former Red Cross President 
Elizabeth Dole in the 2000 campaign. The aides contend Bush and 
Mrs. Dole two have easily recognizable names but have few public 
positions on the issues. Gore has a double-digit lead over former 
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley in the race for the Democratic 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Some voters think Gore will do fine, given time to explain his  
candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Annetta Giesmann, 80, of Sterling, Neb., voted for Ronald Reagan  
in the 1980s but thinks Gore would make a good president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he would carry on what President Clinton has done, and  
the country's in good shape,'' she said. ``He's been vice 
president, and vice presidents never do much. Give him a year, and 
he'll come across with his ideas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Gore campaign's strategy to connect their candidate with the  
voters is to share more about his personal background before his 
service in the Clinton administration. He now explains he's been a 
farm worker, journalist, businessman and Vietnam veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	But changing the public perception of Gore may be tough.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if he's got the spunk,'' said Alvin Watson, 42, a  
machine operator from Saratoga, N.Y., and lifelong Democrat. ``He 
doesn't look like the type of guy that's like an everyday person. 
He looks very strict, a little stiff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The circumstances should be ripe for a Gore candidacy. A  
February poll by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press 
and an ABC/Washington Post poll taken in mid-March said a majority 
wanted the country to continue in the policy direction charted by 
the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of Americans said in the ABC/Post poll they  
approved of Gore's character, and more than half said he has a 
vision for the future. But he lagged 27 percentage points behind 
Bush as a strong leader in the ABC/Post poll. In the Pew poll taken 
in February, almost half said there was no chance they would vote 
for him, while about a fourth of respondents said there was no 
chance they would vote for Bush or Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore says he will campaign ``door-to-door, family-to-family and  
one-on-one'' in Iowa and New Hampshire. Aides are working to get 
biographical profiles of Gore published in newspapers and 
magazines. They've counseled him to cut back on the jokes about his 
straight-faced demeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanderbilt University presidential scholar Erwin Hargrove said,  
``Gore has difficulty projecting warmth, which he does have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore political adviser Robert Squier said it isn't easy for the  
candidate to talk about himself in public and adds that all vice 
presidents have to define themselves as separate from the 
administrations they've served. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a process he's going through,'' Squier said. ``A very  
shy man is learning how to share himself with strangers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:22:34 </DATE_TIME>
