<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virus Underground Split By Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The close-knit underground of computer virus  
creators split into two camps at the news that one of their own may 
have been arrested for releasing malicious Melissa. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole community has really been shaken up by this,'' said  
B.K. Delong, who follows the virus scene. ``The first group is one 
that wants a better reputation. Then there's the community that 
wants to retaliate and come up with even more destructive 
viruses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Virus creators gather at the Virus Exchange Underground, a  
computer chat area where they swap ideas and gossip. Most are 
programmers interested in viruses and computer bugs. They often 
write viruses and swap them among themselves, Delong said. 
</P>
<P>
	They refer to themselves as ``Black Hats,'' interested in doing  
damage, and ``White Hats,'' often crack programmers looking for 
possible security hazards. The Black Hats sometimes release viruses 
through e-mail or Usenet newsgroups. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released on behalf of the VX Underground, as it's  
often called, the group warned the media and investigators not to 
quickly condemn the author of Melissa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead they should be more interested in the person who  
released the bug which caused the spread of the virus,'' said the 
statement, which was e-mailed to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa was originally posted on two sex discussion groups a  
week ago Friday, according to an online search. The VX Underground 
said it was highly unlikely those two posts out of thousands could 
have led to Melissa's vicious cascade. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, once released others posted the Melissa source code  
to additional newsgroups, Web sites and listservs (mailing lists), 
which meant anyone could turn it into the virus and continue to 
spread it,'' the statement continued. 
</P>
<P>
	David L. Smith, 30, of Aberdeen, N.J., was arrested Friday and  
charged with originating the destructive Melissa, which infected 
hundreds of thousands of computers and swamped hundreds of 
companies' e-mail systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer experts used unique identification numbers embedded in  
Microsoft Word documents to trace Melissa back to a well-known 
virus writer who calls himself VicodinES. 
</P>
<P>
	Rita Malley, spokeswoman for the New Jersey state attorney  
general's office said Smith was ``definitely not'' the person known 
by that handle. Instead, Smith took two viruses, one of which came 
from VicodinES, and combined them with another virus to create 
Melissa, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (the Black Hat programmers) are looking for someone to  
blame,'' said Delong. They resent the treatment VicodinES 
supposedly received at the hands of the media, and they're rallying 
around their own. They said he is a really nice guy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:32:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Adventure Magazine Set To Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The venerable National Geographic Society is  
moving to widen its appeal with a new magazine, National Geographic 
Adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	Scheduled to hit the newsstands Tuesday, Adventure becomes the  
fourth magazine in the society's 111-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	It's aimed at ``an active, young, hands-on audience that wants  
to get out and have these great adventures for themselves,'' said 
editor John Rasmus, who formerly edited Outside magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand that people don't necessarily aspire to do  
everything within our pages,'' he acknowledged, but added that 
``people love to read about adventure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its first issue, Adventure profiles seven famous explorers,  
including oceanographer Sylvia Earle, cave explorer Louise Hose and 
dinosaur-digger Paul Sereno. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes a feature on free climbing in Greenland; a look at  
Robert Ballard, finder of the Titanic; stories of two treks down a 
deep gorge in the Himalayas; a look at the safety of gorilla 
watching in Uganda; and a story about two 19th century fur trappers 
written by Sebastian Junger, author of ``The Perfect Storm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new magazine will sell for $3.95 in the United States and $5  
in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	It joins the National Geographic magazine, currently issued in  
English and several foreign languages. The society also publishes 
National Geographic Traveler, a more traditional travel magazine, 
and National Geographic World for children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:33:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A storm system continued Friday over the Plains and Rockies,  
where cold temperatures and high winds combined to create 
below-zero wind chill factors in areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest snow fell across the mountains of Colorado and  
Wyoming by Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of Wyoming, Casper received 14 inches and Lander  
had 2 feet of snow since the storm began Thursday. Sinks Canyon, 
eight miles southwest of Lander, had 31 inches. In Colorado, 
Evergreen received 10 inches of snow and Hot Sulphur Springs picked 
up 9 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Winds between 15 and 30 mph were associated with the storm. Wind  
gusts up to 45 mph made it feel like 27 below zero in Rock Springs, 
Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials closed schools, canceled flights and warned against  
unnecessary travel in parts of the central Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Snowfall was lighter in Arizona, New Mexico, the northern  
Rockies and northern Plains. Hundreds of North Dakotans remained 
without power late Friday afternoon as the state cleaned up from 
heavy snowfall Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures ranged no higher than the 40s for most of the area  
Friday. Winds ahead of the storm helped push temperatures from Iowa 
to Texas into the 60s and 70s. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides a few showers riding along the Mississippi River into  
far western areas of the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes, most of the 
rest of the nation was under fair and dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The morning low for the Lower 48 was 4 degrees in Yellowstone  
National Park, Wyo., while the afternoon high of 85 was recorded in 
Harlingen, Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:53:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Military Jury Says To Dismiss Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury on Friday recommended  
dismissal from the Marine Corps for a navigator who admitted 
destroying a personal videotape he made before his jet cut an 
Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-man panel of Marine officers deliberated 3 1/2 hours  
Friday before recommending the punishment for Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer sat stoically and the courtroom was silent as the  
judge, Col. Alvin Keller, imposed the recommended sentence. But 
after court adjourned, Schweitzer smiled at his lawyers and nodded 
his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty Monday to obstruction of justice and  
conspiracy for destroying the tape after his EA-6B Prowler hit the 
cable over Cavalese, Italy, on Feb. 3, 1998. The ski gondola 
plunged 370 feet into a valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge had the option of sentencing Schweitzer to a  
previously undisclosed punishment recommended as part of 
Schweitzer's guilty plea, or to accept the jury's recommendation -- 
whichever is more lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	He chose the jury's recommendation. The sentence proposed in the  
plea agreement, divulged after the jury made its recommendation, 
called for forfeiture of pay and allowance and dismissal from the 
Marine Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence doesn't take effect until it is approved by Lt.  
Gen. Peter Pace, who convened the court-martial. Pace, commander of 
Marine Forces Atlantic in Norfolk, Va., may approve the sentence or 
recommend a lighter one. Schweitzer then could choose to pursue his 
decision through the military appeals process. 
</P>
<P>
	A prosecutor, Maj. Stu Couch, urged the jury earlier Friday to  
recommend Schweitzer's dismissal from the service and prison, but 
said the government didn't wish to see him sentenced to the maximum 
10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this a character flaw or just a crime?'' Couch asked.  
``Everybody trusted him. ... That makes the perfect conspirator, 
somebody who has that amount of trust built up over a period of 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Dave Beck said the harshest punishment should  
be a letter of reprimand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Capt. Schweitzer has got to get up every day and know his  
career in the Marine Corps is over,'' Beck said. ``This good and 
faithful Marine, this outstanding Marine officer made some bad 
decisions over a three- to five-day period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck reminded the jurors that Schweitzer ``looked you in the  
eye. ... He told you things that nobody had any way of knowing 
until he came forward to tell the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch said the tape so worried Schweitzer and the pilot, Capt.  
Richard Ashby, that they stayed in the cockpit after making an 
emergency landing at the Aviano, Italy, air base to swap the tape 
for a blank one. Schweitzer said he later tossed the cassette into 
a bonfire. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's the one thing on his mind?'' Couch asked. ``That tape.  
That tape was stressing him out ... driving him nuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer testified Thursday that he stopped taping 10 minutes  
before the jet severed the cable, but said he smiled once into the 
camera and feared the image would be used in media reports of the 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	He described his destruction of the tape as the biggest mistake  
of his life and said he wanted to die after learning people in the 
gondola had been killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Involuntary manslaughter charges against Schweitzer were dropped  
after Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was acquitted last month 
of the same charges. Ashby still faces the two obstruction charges 
and his trial is scheduled April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Two back seat crewmen in the radar-jamming aircraft were charged  
after the accident, but the charges were dismissed last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:53:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Military Jury Says To Dismiss Marine </HEADLINE>
