<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Tries for Another 1-2 Finish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Because Aaron Jones listened to Bob  
Baffert, he has his first Santa Anita Derby starter and a possible 
serious Kentucky Derby contender in Prime Timber. 
</P>
<P>
	Because Baffert didn't listen to his 12-year-old son, Tyler, he  
is the trainer, but not the owner, of Prime Timber, who will try to 
give Baffert his second straight Santa Anita Derby victory, then 
try for an unprecedented third consecutive win for Baffert in the 
Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Baffert recalled a telephone conversation with Jones  
that led to Florida-bred Prime Timber being bought for $375,000 as 
a 2-year-old at the 1998 Ocala Sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Jones, we've got to buy this thing,'' Baffert said. ``He's  
unbelievable. He reminds me of Silver Charm (second in the Santa 
Anita Derby and winner of the Kentucky Derby in 1997).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 77-year-old Jones, in the lumber business in Oregon and a  
racehorse owner for nearly 30 years, admitted Friday that he was 
reluctant at first. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has no pedigree,'' Jones told Baffert. The colt is by  
Sultry Song out of the Nodouble mare Wine Taster. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's OK, he can run,'' Baffert replied.  
</P>
<P>
	After Baffert hung up with Jones, his son, who had been  
listening, said, ``Why are you buying it for him, buy it for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber, ridden by David Flores, probably will be the  
post-time favorite for the 1 1/8-mile Santa Anita Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last start, the colt, wearing blinkers for the first  
time, won the 1 1-16-mile San Felipe March 13. That was his first 
win in two starts as a 3-year-old and his third victory in five 
career races. 
</P>
<P>
	One of his two seconds came in his 3-year-old debut when, racing  
wide throughout, he was runner-up by a neck to Santa Anita Derby 
contender Desert Hero in the one-mile San Rafael Feb. 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert will not only be seeking his third Santa Anita Derby  
victory -- his first was in 1996 with Cavonnier, the Kentucky Derby 
runner-up -- he also will be trying for a second straight 1-2 
finish. He got that last year with Indian Charlie and Real Quiet. 
The latter won the Kentucky Derby, with Indian Charlie third. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's other Santa Anita Derby starter and Kentucky Derby  
hopeful is General Challenge, a California-bred gelding, ridden by 
Gary Stevens and owned by John and Betty Mabee. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, who won his only two starts last year and  
also his 3-year-old debut, finished fifth in his last start, the 1 
1-16-mile Louisiana Derby March 14. He will race with blinkers for 
the first time Saturday. He wore them for the first time when he 
worked five-eighths of a mile in 57 3-5 seconds March 23 at Santa 
Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel as confident going into this race as I did last year,  
and it's a tougher race this year,'' Baffert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the opposition that his pair will face, Baffert noted Desert  
Hero and the filly Honest Lady. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in the field for the $750,000 race are Capsized, Hire Wire  
Act, Charismatic and Walk That Walk. 
</P>
<P>
	Desert Hero, a son of 1993 Kentucky Derby winner Sea Hero, is  
ridden by Corey Nakatani and owned by Prince Ahmed bin Salman of 
Saudi Arabia. He did not race as a 2-year-old, making his debut 
with a victory Feb. 7 at Santa Anita, then winning the San Rafael. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Desert Hero wins this race, he's a super horse,'' Baffert  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Honest Lady, Baffert said, ``Bobby Frankel wouldn't let  
her in if he didn't think she had a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Frankel said Honest Lady has to win Saturday to earn a  
shot at the Kentucky Derby or if she doesn't win, ``I would think 
she would have to have a big excuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honest Lady, ridden by Kent Desormeaux and owned by Prince  
Khalid Abdullah, also of Saudi Arabia, won her first two starts, 
then made her debut against colts in the San Rafael. She finished 
fifth, but only one length behind winner Desert Hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Honest Lady will carry 115 pounds to 120 for each of the other  
starters. Three fillies have won the race -- Ciencia (1939), Silver 
Spoon (1959) and Winning Colors (1988). Winning Colors also was the 
third, and last, filly to win the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Capsized, third in the San Rafael, is trained by Lisa Lewis,  
only the fifth woman to saddle a horse for the Santa Anita Derby. 
None has won. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
