<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Removes Prosecutor, Tycoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin resumed his offensive  
against Russia's prosecutor-general on Friday, suspending him from 
his post just as a corruption probe into the Kremlin was gathering 
momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin also won backing from his colleagues in the Commonwealth  
of Independent States to fire tycoon Boris Berezovsky as executive 
secretary of the CIS, an alliance of 12 former Soviet republics. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the prosecutor and the businessman stained Yeltsin's  
reputation, Berezovsky by apparently using Kremlin connections to 
pursue his business interests, and Prosecutor-General Yuri Skuratov 
by accusing Yeltsin of ignoring the alleged corruption of his inner 
circle. 
</P>
<P>
	But Yeltsin insisted the ousters were justified. He said  
Berezovsky had meddled in government affairs. As for Skuratov, 
Yeltsin said in a letter Friday to the upper house of parliament 
that the prosecutor was facing criminal charges that hobbled his 
office's work. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin wrote an order Friday suspending Skuratov from office  
while he is investigated on charges of abuse of power. The 
president ordered Skuratov's office sealed and his phone line to 
the Kremlin cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The speaker of the upper chamber, Yegor Stroyev, said he and his  
colleagues would have to ``thoroughly study'' Skuratov's case 
before coming to a decision, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 
The upper house is the only body that can dismiss Skuratov. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's opponents accused the president of trying to block the  
prosecutor's investigation into alleged Kremlin corruption. 
Skuratov's office has been probing alleged bribe-taking by Russian 
officials and investigating Russian funds believed to have been 
illegally deposited in Swiss banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin pressured Skuratov to resign in February. But the upper  
house refused to back the president, and Skuratov withdrew his 
resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	When Skuratov returned to work, Russian state television aired  
segments of a video apparently showing Skuratov having sex with two 
prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of Russia's Federal Security Service, Vladimir Putin,  
alleged Friday that criminal suspects had provided Skuratov with 
the girls as encouragement to drop investigations against them. 
</P>
<P>
	Berezovsky had also tried to resist Yeltsin's effort to fire  
him, but the CIS heads of state on Friday heeded the president's 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Berezovsky wanted to defend himself, but could not get  
permission for his plane to enter Russian airspace. He had been in 
France, and after being unable to reach Moscow, he went to the 
Ukrainian capital Kiev. 
</P>
<P>
	Berezovsky has been a powerful player in Russian politics for  
years, thanks to close links with Yeltsin's inner circle. But he 
has fallen out of favor in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian prosecutors have opened a probe against him on charges  
of setting up an illegal bugging network to eavesdrop on government 
officials. They have also investigated his business activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
