<HEADLINE> Cienfuegos, Arce Work Out Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Los Angeles Galaxy midfielder Mauricio  
Cienfuegos and San Jose Clash forward Raul Diaz Arce have 
renegotiated contracts with Major League Soccer after vowing to 
return to their native El Salvador if they didn't get more money. 
</P>
<P>
	They are making about $118,000 each this season in the first of  
two option years in their contracts. Details of the new four-year 
deals were not disclosed Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deal was significantly more than they're currently  
earning,'' said Cory Clemetson, their agent. ``The players are 
happy and relieved that it's over with. They were very serious 
about permanently leaving the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contracts were agreed upon Thursday during a meeting in Los  
Angeles with league commissioner Douglas Logan, MLS player 
operations chief Ivan Gazidis and Clemetson. 
</P>
<P>
	Cienfuegos and Diaz Arce missed the first six weeks of training  
camp while seeking higher salaries. Both agreed to play in their 
teams' first two matches while negotiations continued. 
</P>
<P>
	The Galaxy (2-0) plays in San Jose (1-1) Saturday night.  
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Cienfuegos played in 30 of the Galaxy's 32 games,  
scoring a career-high 42 points on 13 goals and 16 assists. He was 
second in the MLS in assists and tied for third in game-winning 
goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Under MLS' single-entity ownership structure, all players sign  
contracts with the league, with its marquee players then assigned 
to teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
