<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:25:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Pursue Steel Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. steel industry won a partial victory  
Friday as the government decided to pursue trade complaints against 
six of eight countries accused of illegally pricing cut-to-length 
steel plates. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases form the second round of complaints filed by major  
U.S. steel producers who have been struggling against a recent 
surge in steel imports. In the first round, the government is 
considering tariffs on hot-rolled carbon steel from Japan and 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission voted to drop cases  
against the Czech Republic and Macedonia after finding their 
shipments of cut-to-length plates to be negligible -- less than 3 
percent of overall imports to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency, meanwhile, found evidence that shipments of that  
product from France, India, Indonesia, Italy, Japan and South Korea 
have hurt U.S. producers, paving the way for a Commerce Department 
investigation that could lead to tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic steel producers and steelworkers have blamed the  
imports for thousands of layoffs and three U.S. company 
bankruptcies. 
</P>
<P>
	Although imports have since dropped, steel producers continue to  
press the administration and Congress for help. 
</P>
<P>
	The imports reached record highs last year as the Asian economic  
crisis reduced demand for steel abroad and forced foreign producers 
to turn to U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Curtis H. Barnette, chairman and chief executive of Bethlehem  
Steel Corp., called Friday's action affirmation ``that the steel 
crisis continues and that decisive, prompt and comprehensive action 
is required in response.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Japanese steel executive, Fujio Ono, has called the cases  
unjustified, saying market forces and not artificial trade 
practices were responsible for the import surge. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Bethlehem Steel, four other steel producers and the  
United Steelworkers of America accused the eight countries of 
illegally dumping cut-to-length steel in the United States at 
prices below production costs or home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	They also accused France, India, Indonesia, Italy, Macedonia and  
South Korea of unfairly subsidizing their producers to artificially 
lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department has until mid-May to issue a preliminary  
finding on subsidies and until late July to initially rule on 
dumping. 
</P>
<P>
	Cut-to-length plate, thicker than the widely used hot-rolled  
variety, is used in agricultural and construction equipment, 
bridges, ships, railcars and buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	In the hot-rolled cases, the Commerce Department has issued  
preliminary dumping findings against Japan, Russia and Brazil. 
Final rulings are expected by summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and Brazil face tariffs of up to 71 percent if the  
findings are affirmed and found to threaten U.S. industry. Russia 
has reached a deal with the United States to avoid tariffs by 
voluntarily curtailing shipments. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 09:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Witness Testifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Called to bolster Susan McDougal's  
complaints of unfair tactics, another woman indicted by Whitewater 
prosecutors testified today that she was pressured to back up the 
story of a presidential accuser even though she ``didn't know 
anything'' about the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Julie Hiatt Steele said she was charged with obstruction of  
justice and making false statements after she refused to support 
the story of Kathleen Willey, who said President Clinton made an 
unwanted sexual advance toward her in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey has said she told Ms. Steele about the Clinton  
incident right after it happened. Ms. Steele has testified that her 
friend didn't say anything like that to her back in 1993 but later 
asked Ms. Steele to lie and say she was told. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr investigated Mrs. Willey's  
allegation as part of the Monica Lewinsky matter. 
</P>
<P>
	After testifying before two grand juries, Ms. Steele said that  
in November 1998 she was ``invited to a secret meeting at the 
office of the independent counsel to clarify my testimony. I 
believed I was to support Kathleen Willey's version of the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Were you able to do that? asked defense attorney Mark Geragos.  
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't do it. I left the meeting in tears. I didn't know  
anything,'' she replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele was called by attorneys for Mrs. McDougal, who is on  
trial on charges of criminal contempt and obstruction of justice 
for refusing twice to answer federal grand jury questions about the 
Clintons' business dealings. Mrs. McDougal said she feared Starr 
would charge her with perjury if she didn't say what he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard decided to allow limited  
testimony from Ms. Steele ``to show modus operandi'' of Starr and 
his deputies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, who lives in Richmond, Va., said despite what she  
considered her minor role in the case, prosecutors questioned one 
of her daughters, her brother, her former attorney and her 
neighbors and friends. She said a grand jury subpoenaed her 
daughter's boyfriend and even ``asked if he had sex with me.'' The 
judge ordered jurors to disregard that remark. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele said she was upset that some family members also were  
asked about the adoption of her son Adam, now 8, from Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, says both she and Ms.  
Steele have similar accounts of what happens when a person doesn't 
cooperate with a prosecutor who is out to ``get'' Clinton. As does 
Ms. Steele, Mrs. McDougal claims she cooperated with Starr's office 
in its investigations until it became clear to her that Starr did 
not want the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want the jury to get the impression that she's some  
lone voice in the wilderness,'' Geragos said of his client. ``It's 
the only way she can prove that these fears were legitimate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr prosecutor Mark Barrett said the judge's ruling to allow  
the testimony was ``mammoth'' and he expressed disbelief that Ms. 
Steele would be willing to testify under oath with her May 3 trial 
in Alexandria, Va., only weeks away. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett predicted the McDougal trial would be extended by weeks  
and could turn into ``a mini-trial'' of Ms. Steele, but later 
seemed confident the prosecution could cross-examine Ms. Steele in 
one day. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is in its fourth week. It is expected to go to the  
jury next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
