<DOCNO> APW19990402.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:57:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Canadians Celebrate New Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IQALUIT, Nunavut (AP) -- Canada's new arctic territory, Nunavut,  
mixed partying and protocol on the first day of its existence, and 
unveiled its flag -- appropriately emblazoned with the North Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Highlights of daylong celebrations Thursday included the first  
session of Nunavut's Inuit-led legislature, the first in Canada or 
the United States to be dominated by aboriginals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have successfully changed the map of Canada, and in doing  
... we have scored a victory for democracy that is being heard 
across the world,'' said Paul Okalik, the 34-year-old lawyer 
elected by fellow legislators as Nunavut's first premier. 
</P>
<P>
	Nunavut, as big as Western Europe, is formed out of the eastern  
and central portions of the Northwest Territories. It has 25,000 
people, 85 percent of them Inuit, and was created to give the Inuit 
a chance at self-government. 
</P>
<P>
	The territory is plagued by severe social ills, including high  
rates of crime, suicide and joblessness. But Prime Minister Jean 
Chretien predicted the Inuit would succeed by using a fusion of 
traditional and modern know-how. 
</P>
<P>
	``The North of today is no longer hostage to geography and  
climate,'' he said during a 90-minute ceremony. ``It is very much 
part of the wired world, with equal opportunities for growth and 
development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Okalik, Chretien and other dignitaries looking on, young  
military cadets unfurled Nunavut's flag. It depicts the North Star 
in one corner and an inuksuk -- an Inuit guidepost made of stones -- 
in the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through the centuries, they have guided you across the snow to  
your homes,'' said Canada's governor-general, Romeo LeBlanc. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony was opened by three elders who blessed the new  
territory and punctuated with entertainment by Inuit performers. An 
eight-member troupe performed a drum dance, leaping and chanting 
while beating hand-held drums, and five women demonstrated the 
ancient art of throat singing, which produces haunting sounds 
through special breathing techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	Other events included a fiddle-and-accordion festival, a rock  
concert by Inuit heavy-metal band Angava, and a community feast 
featuring caribou, raw fish and musk ox. 
</P>
<P>
	Nunavut means ``our land'' in Inuktitut, the Inuit language that  
will be one of the territory's official languages, along with 
English and French. Fifteen of the 19 new legislators are Inuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Okalik, who for many years was involved in the difficult  
negotiations to resolve Inuit land claims, requested a moment of 
silence during the legislative session to commemorate Inuit lost to 
suicide, violence and abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has always given me strength to know that those we have  
lost along the way are watching us here and smiling,'' he said in 
Inuktitut. ``We are no longer dreaming. This is reality. We have 
arrived.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:57:05 </DATE_TIME>
