<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Day Fever Hits Monterrey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- By the time the ticket window opened,  
there already were several thousand people in line. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball fever had struck this northern Mexican city, and word  
that an extra 1,000 tickets would go on sale for Sunday night's 
major league opener between the San Diego Padres and Colorado 
Rockies set off a scramble. 
</P>
<P>
	By 2 a.m. Thursday, there were close to 1,000 people waiting.  
Later in the morning, the stadium parking lot was jammed with fans 
in cowboy hats and baseball caps alike. 
</P>
<P>
	At the front of the line was Leticia Gonzalez, a 43-year-old  
homemaker who said she had been waiting a full 24 hours to buy 
tickets for herself and her three sons, all of whom play in youth 
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't go to Colorado to see Vinny (Castilla),'' she said.  
``This is probably the only chance I'll get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For most of the people in line, the extra tickets meant only  
more frustration. The tickets sold out in less than an hour, 
leaving thousands wanting. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred people jumped up and down on the car of a man  
accused of being a scalper, demanding that he sell them his tickets 
at cost. A half-dozen terrified policemen finally extricated the 
man safely. 
</P>
<P>
	As is the case across much of northern and coastal Mexico,  
baseball is big in Monterrey, an industrial center just a couple of 
hours south of the Texas border. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball had an indisputable dominance here in the 1940s, when  
the Mexican League was flush with money and brought down players 
from the Major Leagues and the Negro Leagues. Roy Campanella played 
for the local Sultans. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past decades, Mexico's television networks have pitched  
soccer and recently have stopped broadcasting Mexican baseball 
games, but in Monterrey baseball continues to be a major sport. 
</P>
<P>
	That allegiance has paid off before with visits by major league  
teams. In 1991 and 1993 U.S. teams played exhibition games in 
Monterrey, and in 1996 the Padres and the Mets staged a three-game 
series here. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents consider Sunday's opening-day game a confirmation of  
their fanaticism -- and many hope it means someday a big league 
franchise could be located here, as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a question of time and economic stability,'' said  
Hector Bencomo, a Sultans official and baseball commentator on 
local television and radio. ``The fans are ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, in addition to the Sultans, a professional team with one  
of the best stadiums in Mexico, Monterrey has 53 little leagues in 
which thousands of children hope to follow in Castilla's footsteps. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Monterrey's Guadalupe Linda Vista team of 12-year-olds  
won the Little League World Series, and in 1998 the team was Latin 
American champs. 
</P>
<P>
	On a recent afternoon, the Linda Vista Marlins -- a team in the  
city's Pacifier League -- was practicing for a big game. The 
players, all under 5 years old, struggled with the weight of their 
miniature bats, but some managed to connect and take off scrambling 
toward first base. 
</P>
<P>
	Otilia Lopez, a 30-year-old homemaker, proudly watched from the  
stands as her 4-year-old son, Naoki, stood for batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We bought him his batting cage. We bought him four gloves and  
a lot of baseballs,'' she said. ``So of course we're going to take 
him to see the game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:43:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise on Job Growth News / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices climbed Friday as the government  
reported sluggish job growth and a moderate rise in average wages 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which showed the unemployment rate sinking to a  
29-year low of 4.2 percent last month, provided little incentive 
for Federal Reserve policymakers to change their current monetary 
policy, market watchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 1/16  
point, or $10.06 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.59 percent from 5.67 percent 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market was open for a half day on Friday even as the  
stock market was closed for the Good Friday holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported the March unemployment rate fell  
0.2 percentage point from 4.4 percent in February and was the 
lowest since February 1970, when the rate was also 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But employers added just 46,000 jobs, after seasonal adjustment,  
to their payrolls, down from gains of 297,000 in February and 
217,000 in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Seto, a senior economist for Nikko Securities International,  
said the job growth fell short of expectations in part because warm 
weather in February had allowed employers to start hiring seasonal 
workers earlier than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the slower growth provided ``some indication of  
softening taking place'' in the job market and the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also said average hourly wages edged up 3 cents in  
March to $13.09, and are up 3.6 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Seto described the wage increase as moderate and said ``We are  
not seeing much wage pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the report suggests the Fed will follow ``a steady  
policy for a litle longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up by between 1/8 point and 3/8 point, and intermediate maturities 
were up by as much as 5/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.40 percent as the  
discount lost 0.01 percentage point to 4.29 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.47 percent, as the discount dropped 0.02 percentage 
point to 4.31 percent. One-year yields were 4.65 percent as the 
discount fell 0.04 percentage point from late Thursday to 4.43 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4 7/8 percent from 5 1/2 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bond Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds was  
unavailable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 03:25:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Baffled by Iowa Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Laura Watson Dalton and Maria Therese  
Lehner didn't know each other, but they apparently had a lot in 
common. Friends say both were outgoing, caring, just nice to be 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	They share a horrible link: Both were killed by multiple blows  
to the head, their bodies discovered March 19 in a gutted apartment 
that was intentionally set on fire to destroy evidence and cover up 
the slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	Police don't know if the women -- complete strangers to each  
other by all accounts -- died together or how they ended up in an 
apartment near downtown being rented by three college students. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, there is still no connection with the apartment ...  
and the two victims. There just isn't any reason for them to be 
there at this point that investigators have been able to figure 
out,'' Police Sgt. Mike Lord said this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehner, 27, lived in Belton, Mo., a Kansas City suburb, and was  
employed by Bregman &AMP; Co. of Bethesda, Md., to do environmental 
contract work with U.S. Army reserve units in Iowa, Missouri and 
Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson Dalton, 29, a native of Omaha, Neb., had been a paramedic  
for six months in Creston, 150 miles southwest of Iowa City. 
</P>
<P>
	A big question is how the woman ended up at the apartment, which  
was rented by three University of Iowa students. Two were away for 
spring break that week and a third has been studying overseas. The 
students told police they did not know the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors told investigators that they heard male voices in the  
apartment but assumed it was the students. 
</P>
<P>
	Police know this much.  
</P>
<P>
	Lehner was in Cedar Rapids, about 30 miles north of Iowa City,  
for a March 18 appointment. She left the reserve unit that 
afternoon, but never made it to an appointment the next day in Iowa 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, police arrested Johnathon Lee Memmer, 23, on a parole  
violation stemming from a 1997 burglary conviction. Memmer was 
being held on $1 million cash bond and was not cooperating with 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are questioning Memmer because he was seen  
partying on St. Patrick's Day with Watson Dalton and a group of 
people. That was two days before the bodies were discovered, while 
Watson Dalton was in town to visit a cousin and some friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are certain points in an investigation where you can  
rule a person out as a suspect,'' Lord said. ``There are also 
points where a person emerges as a suspect. So far, Memmer is 
somewhere in between those two points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Lehner's hometown of Norwalk, a tightknit community of 560  
people in western Wisconsin, grief and shock is turning into anger. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had anything to say to the police, it would be, `Get this  
guy, this person who did it. Go on every little lead. This is 
undeserving of anybody,''' said Kathy Degenhardt, Lehner's high 
school classmate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
