<DOCNO> APW19990402.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:32:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6:20 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Airstrikes Hit Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Three loud explosions rocked  
downtown Belgrade early Saturday as NATO brought its airstrike to 
the center of the Yugoslav capital. Shortly after the impact, 
flames could be seen rising from a section of town where the 
Interior and Defense ministries are located. At the Pentagon, 
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said, ``We can confirm that targets are 
being hit in downtown Belgrade.'' He provided no other details. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Jets Pound Kosovo Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets pounded targets in Kosovo,  
trying to keep Yugoslav troops on the move and force them to waste 
precious fuel. Ten days into its air campaign, NATO conceded it has 
failed to stop Serb forces from expelling tens of thousands of 
Kosovo Albanians, but insisted it would press on. Meanwhile, tens 
of thousands more refugees crossed borders out of the province, 
leading to chaotic scenes of masses overwhelming local communities 
and relief agencies struggling to supply food, medicine and 
blankets. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Carrier May Join NATO Forces  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Navy aircraft carrier was approaching the  
Mediterranean Sea today and was likely to join the fight against 
Yugoslavia, senior Defense Department officials said. As the allies 
expanded their air assault, President Clinton said it was clear to 
him from the start that the campaign against Yugoslavia would not 
be a ``week or two operation.'' Clinton again said he had no 
intention of introducing American ground forces into the conflict, 
although he did not explicitly rule it out. 

</P>
<P>
	Jury Wants Navigator Out of Marines  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury has recommended  
dismissal from the Marine Corps for a navigator who admitted 
destroying a personal videotape he made before his jet cut an 
Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 people. Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer pleaded guilty Monday to obstruction of justice and 
conspiracy for destroying the tape after his EA-6B Prowler hit the 
cable over Cavalese, Italy, on Feb. 3, 1998. The ski gondola 
plunged 370 feet into a valley. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Appeals Internet Porn Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Justice Department today appealed a  
judge's ruling that blocked enforcement of a federal Internet 
pornography law. Government lawyers had until today to decide 
whether to appeal U.S. District Judge Lowell A. Reed's Feb. 1 
preliminary injunction barring enforcement of the Child Online 
Protection Act. The law would require commercial Web sites to 
collect a credit card number or some other access code as proof of 
age before allowing Internet users to view online material deemed 
``harmful to minors.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pilgrims Meet in Gethsemane  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Easter week has increased the number of  
visitors to the garden of Gethsemane, the place where Jesus was 
betrayed by Judas' kiss. Easter 1999 signals that the season of 
millennial pilgrimage has begun in earnest. Gethsemane, a small, 
walled-in grove of ancient olive trees, is the traditional site of 
Judas' kiss, the signal to Roman soldiers that Jesus was the one 
they had come to arrest. Visitors from all over world clutch 
Bibles, listen to tour guides or find a rocky ledge to sit alone 
for a few moments in silence. 

</P>
<P>
	'Shake, Rattle, Roll' Writer Dies  
</P>
<P>
	ALTAMONTE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) -- Jesse Stone, a major influence on  
20th century music who wrote ``Shake, Rattle and Roll'' and helped 
develop many of Atlantic Records' biggest hits, has died. He was 
97. As a writer, producer and arranger at Atlantic, Stone worked 
with artists such as Ray Charles, Big Joe Turner, the Drifters and 
the Clovers. Among his other famous songs were ``Idaho'' and 
``Money Honey.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Lindros Out With Collapsed Lung  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers star center Eric Lindros  
will sit out at least the remainder of the regular season because 
of a collapsed right lung. Lindros, who is third in the NHL in 
scoring with 40 goals and 93 points, was injured when cross-checked 
during the Flyers' game at Nashville last night. Nearly three 
quarts of blood filled the space where the lung collapsed, and 
doctors are draining the blood out with a chest tube. They have 
inserted a vacuum pump in the lung to help re-expand it. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Subpeona Foreman To Testify  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Former heavyweight champion George Foreman  
will likely testify later this month before a federal grand jury 
investigating boxing's sanctioning organizations, according to his 
lawyer. Foreman, 51, has been subpoenaed by the panel looking into 
corruption charges in boxing, Larry Wechsler said. Sources told The 
Record of Hackensack that the grand jury is investigating whether 
the International Boxing Federation sold rankings and arranged 
fights in return for kickbacks. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
