<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timberwolves 107, Nuggets 88 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Terrell Brandon dominated the third quarter  
for the second consecutive game, scoring 15 of his 21 points to 
lead the Minnesota Timberwolves to a 107-88 victory over the Denver 
Nuggets on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon, who tied a team record by shooting 7-for-7 for 16  
third-quarter points Tuesday against Dallas, went 5-for-7 and 
scored 15 in the third this time. That helped the Wolves turn a 
52-50 halftime lead into an 81-68 advantage heading into the final 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon also had 15 assists and finished two rebounds shy of his  
first career triple-double. Kevin Garnett had 28 points, seven 
assists and six rebounds as the Wolves won for the fifth time in 
seven games. Sam Mitchell added 21 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota shot 57 percent, compared to 43.4 for the Nuggets, who  
are 0-16 on the road this season and have lost 23 straight away 
from home. 
</P>
<P>
	Chauncey Billups scored 30 for Denver after getting a  
career-high 32 in Thursday's win over Seattle. Danny Fortson had 15 
points and 12 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Acquired last month from Milwaukee in the three-team deal that  
sent Stephon Marbury to New Jersey, Brandon got his 10th assist of 
the first half on a jumper by Mitchell with 16 seconds left to give 
the Wolves a 52-50 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon missed his first shot of the third quarter, but Garnett  
soared to dunk the rebound. That started a 14-6 run that put the 
Wolves in control, and Brandon either scored or assisted on every 
basket but one in that stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit three straight jumpers to make it 60-52, then fed  
Mitchell for a jumper and Garnett for a fast-break dunk for a 66-56 
lead, Minnesota's first double-digit lead of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon finished the third quarter with a 3-pointer with three  
seconds left, putting the Wolves up 81-68. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Wolves have won 10 of 11 against Denver, including five  
straight. This is the last of their three meetings this season. ... 
After committing just 10 turnovers in each of their last two games, 
the Nuggets had 17 Friday. ... Nick Van Exel came in averaging 26.3 
points over his last four games, including consecutive season highs 
of 29 and 31 this week. He scored 13 on 6-for-18 shooting. ... The 
Wolves came in hitting 26.6 from 3-point range, the worst 
percentage in the league. They went 6-for-12, including 4-for-5 by 
Dennis Scott. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
