<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Family, Friends Pray for Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With bright yellow ribbons newly laced across their hometowns,  
relatives and friends of three U.S. servicemen facing trial in 
war-torn Yugoslavia wept and prayed for their safe return. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia said the men were invaders and would be tried today  
as criminals before a military court, despite demands from 
President Clinton that the soldiers be released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is devastated. We're just praying to God he'll come  
out all right,'' said Frank Jasso, great-uncle of captive Staff 
Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of  
Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of 
Smiths Creek, Mich., were captured Wednesday near the 
Yugoslav-Macedonian border. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Stone learned his son had been taken by Yugoslav forces when  
a National Guard officer knocked on his door to deliver the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a very special American and an incredibly proud  
soldier and we are very proud of him,'' Stone said, his voice 
breaking with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	As U.S. networks showed Serb television images of the three men,  
relatives and friends strung yellow ribbons -- symbols of families 
waiting for soldiers to return from war -- all around their 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we saw him on TV it was a great relief, but of course we  
realize he's in a bad situation,'' said Gonzales' mother, Rosie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steven and the two other soldiers are not criminals and should  
not be dealt with as criminals,'' she said. ``They are innocent 
young men over there as part of their duty to their country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Gonzales appeared battered and bruised, his family  
expressed relief he didn't look worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're dealing with it as best we can,'' said his father,  
Gilbert. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales was described as a likable, bright athlete during his  
high school days in Palestine, 90 miles north of Huntsville in east 
Texas. He graduated in 1995 and won a scholarship to Texas A&AMP;M, but 
left after a year to pursue a dream of joining an elite Army corps. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the type of student you'd love to have: hard-working,  
always happy, funny,'' said teacher Kay Stroud, who had Gonzales in 
her advanced placement biology class. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, whose wife, Tricia, and 4-year-old son Ryan live in San  
Antonio, was described as a talented athlete also blessed with the 
``gift of gab.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised he couldn't talk his way out of this,'' said Ken  
Marzka, Stone's cross-country coach at Capac Community 
Junior-Senior High School, about 50 miles northeast of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a tough kid ... he never quit,'' Marzka said. ``Chris  
is going to be just fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School counselor Kathy Kish said Stone was well-liked by  
students and teachers. He was a member of Students Against Drunk 
Driving. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't surprise us a bit that he's serving our country on  
a peace mission,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, outside the home of Ramirez's father, neighbors  
prayed for the captured staff sergeant and reminisced about the 
``all-American kid'' they watched grow up. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, a wrestler in high school, joined the Army after  
graduation in 1992. He wanted to follow the path of his hero, older 
brother Steven, an Army veteran who is now a Los Angeles police 
detective. 
</P>
<P>
	The detective did not speak publicly, but did talk to police  
Cmdr. David Kalish. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very worried,'' Kalish said. ``He told me that his little  
brother is a very brave soldier and he's confident that he will be 
strong through this entire ordeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some neighbors wept as they talked outside the Ramirez home.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a hero now because he did his duty as a military  
personnel,'' said neighbor and longtime friend Johnny Rios. ``We 
just thank God for putting him in our lives to serve the country.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
