<HEADLINE> Nationwide Mutual's CEO Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The president and chief executive of  
Nationwide Mutual Insurance has resigned, effective April 23, to 
pursue other interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement about Richard Crabtree came yesterday hours  
before the annual policyholders meeting of the parent Nationwide 
Insurance Enterprise. No replacement was named immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide is the country's No. 4 insurer of homes and cars.  
</P>
<P>
	Crabtree, 58, joined the company 34 years ago as an underwriter  
in its Canton office. 
</P>
<P>
	During his three years leading the property-and-casualty  
operations, he oversaw last year's acquisition of Iowa-based 
insurer Allied Group and the sale of Nationwide's money-losing 
Wausau business-insurance affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a jury in Richmond, Va., returned a $100 million  
verdict against the company in a racial discrimination case. 
Company spokesman John Millen said the award, which is under 
appeal, was not a factor in Crabtree's departure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
