<HEADLINE> Murdoch May Buy Out Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Media mogul Rupert Murdoch has agreed to buy  
out a partner to expand his control of regional cable networks and 
his stake in two New York professional sports teams, published 
reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Partner John Malone's Liberty Media will sell his 50 percent  
interest in Fox/Liberty Networks, the partnership he formed with 
Murdoch in 1995, in exchange for about $1.4 billion in stock from 
Murdoch's News Corp., reports in several newspapers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times carried the report on Thursday, and  
similar reports appears in today's editions of The New York Times 
and The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports cited unidentified people familiar with the deal.  
</P>
<P>
	James Platt, a spokesman for Murdoch in New York, refused to  
comment Thursday. A spokeswoman for Liberty Media in Denver, 
reached today, also had no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, the Los Angeles Times said News Corp. would take  
control of Fox/Liberty, which has interests in more than a dozen 
regional sports channels as well as in cable networks including 
Speedvision, Outdoor Life Network and the Golf Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty would also sell Murdoch its half of the partnership's 40  
percent stake in the Staples Center under construction in Los 
Angeles, as well as its share of the partnership's 40 percent 
interests in the New York Knicks, the New York Rangers, Madison 
Square Garden and Radio City Music Hall, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone's sale to News Corp. does not include Liberty's 50  
percent interest in Atlanta-based Fox Sports South, the Los Angeles 
Times said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
