<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harrick Takes Georgia Job After All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Jim Harrick is on the recruiting trail as  
Georgia's basketball coach, hoping to put behind an embarrassing 
day of flip-flops that surely will raise questions about his 
commitment to the Bulldogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick returned to Athens on Friday after putting two schools  
through a tortuous day of indecision before he finally settled on 
the Georgia job after all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited and ready to go to work,'' Harrick told reporters  
at yet another hastily called news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick originally accepted the job on Wednesday, then changed  
his mind Thursday morning and flew back to Rhode Island, where he 
coached the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at that school planned a welcoming-back news  
conference Thursday evening, but Harrick had another change of 
heart after meeting with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia agreed to take him back after athletic director Vince  
Dooley consulted with president Michael Adams. Harrick flew back to 
Athens on Friday for the Bulldogs' third news conference in three 
days concerning the coaching position. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got caught in my emotions. I was all wrapped up in my  
family,'' Harrick said. ``That's all it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick said his first priority was making contact with  
potential recruits, who can sign letters-of-intent on Wednesday. He 
planned to attend a high school all-star game in Detroit on Friday 
night, then return to Atlanta for the Naismith awards banquet 
tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, Harrick will meet with Georgia's returning players.  
He also hopes to convince sophomore Jumaine Jones, the team's 
leading scorer and rebounder, to make a flip-flop of his own and 
give college another season. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones announced he will enter the NBA draft, but that decision  
was made before Ron Jirsa was fired as coach after two mediocre 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick, showing a tinge of defiance as reporters probed for  
details about his decision, never explicitly apologized to either 
Georgia or Rhode Island for putting the schools through such an 
ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had it to do over again, I would probably handle it  
differently,'' he said. ``But hindsight is 20-20. Everybody in this 
room has said at some point, `I wish I had that to do over again.' 
I can say this has been an experience I don't want to go through 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Center Robb Dryden, one of the players who will be back next  
season, said he was ``shocked and a little sad'' when he first 
heard that Harrick wouldn't be taking the Georgia job. He was 
equally stunned when he heard the coach had changed his mind again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it was a tough call for him,'' Dryden said. ``It  
probably hit him all at once.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dryden, who attended the Wednesday news conference when Harrick  
was originally hired, believes the players can recapture the 
excitement they felt about getting a coach who has been to 14 NCAA 
tournaments and won the 1995 national championship at UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will work out. I'm confident it will,'' Dryden  
said. ``I don't think there will be any doubts in any of the 
players' minds. We pretty much understand what he was going through 
from his standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick doesn't think his indecision will have an impact on  
potential recruits, even though other schools are certain to point 
it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can handle whatever recruiting is required,'' Harrick said.  
``If some people want to use this as a negative, fine. But I've 
never talked about other coaches or other schools, and it always 
seems to work out for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for the Georgia fans, who flooded Internet web sites and  
radio talk shows with their doubts about Harrick, he's not worried, 
either. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first dunk we get, the people will come,'' he said  
confidently. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he admitted that Georgia faces a rebuilding job. The  
Bulldogs lost three senior starters and will have to start over if 
Jones doesn't change his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a big job to do,'' Harrick said. ``I hope we can do  
it in a year, but you never know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a white shirt embroidered with a Bulldogs logo and blue  
warm-up pants, Harrick said his indecision stemmed from his 
reluctance to leave behind two of his three sons in Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Jr. was a member of the Rams coaching staff but is barred  
from a job at Georgia because of the state's anti-nepotism law. 
Glenn Harrick recently moved to Rhode Island with his wife and two 
children to open a business. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach said his sons were waiting for him at the airport when  
he flew back to Rhode Island. They were joined via telephone by 
Harrick's other son, Monte, who lives in California. 
</P>
<P>
	``Georgia is the place for you,'' they told Harrick. ``Get on  
that plane and go back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, he did.  
</P>
</TEXT>
