<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Monitor Air-Bag Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal safety officials are working with  
automakers to ensure that testing of side air bags includes 
procedures to avoid problems that caused serious injury or death to 
children in some front air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration  
say nobody has been reported killed or seriously injured by side 
air bags in accidents. The officials, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said they are simply taking precautions to ensure the 
risks to children from side air bags are minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators are talking with nine manufacturers to try to  
make sure the best testing is being done by automakers to prevent 
problems that occurred with frontal air bag deployments, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers meeting with NHTSA include BMW, DaimlerChrysler,  
Audi, Ford and Volvo, an agency official said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also is conducting its own testing program on side  
air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA has scheduled a public meeting for April 19 to bring  
together automakers, suppliers and consumer groups to discuss 
standardized methods of testing and to share testing approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Air bags deploying from the front of autos, either on the driver  
or passenger side, have been blamed for killing 131 people, 
including 73 children. The federal safety agency has issued new 
rules to try to prevent such deaths from frontal air bags, a 
required safety feature in all new cars and light trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Side air bags are not required by law, but automakers have been  
installing them voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Agency officials also would like to see the industry voluntarily  
come up with a common approach for testing side air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to automakers in December, the agency's  
administrator, Dr. Ricardo Martinez, applauded automakers' attempts 
to go beyond federal safety standards in installing side air bags. 
At the same time, he urged caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because these devices add energy to the interior compartment  
of a motor vehicle during a crash, it is imperative that they be 
designed to 'do no harm' to occupants,'' Martinez wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``In particular, it is extremely important to thoroughly test  
these devices with both child and adult dummies ... to guard 
against the risk of serious injury to occupants who may be very 
close to these systems when they deploy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In February at the Chicago Auto Show, General Motors Corp.  
officials said some competitors' side air bags could seriously 
injure or kill children leaning against them during a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	GM played videotapes of tests that show the neck of a small test  
dummy being snapped forward violently as an air bag was deployed. 
The dummy representing a 3-year-old was positioned as if it were a 
child sleeping against the door. 
</P>
<P>
	GM officials have declined to identify the automakers the  
company believes have side air bags that pose a threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are better off with side air bags than without them,''  
said Rob Mitchell, a spokesman for BMW. The German automaker has 
side air bags as a standard feature in the front seat of its autos, 
and they are offered as an option for rear seats on four-door 
models. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell said, however, that if parents ``can't guarantee that a  
child will be properly restrained'' in the back seat, for example 
in a child seat instead of sleeping against a door, ``that may be a 
concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before deciding to buy optional side air bags for the back seat,  
he said, ``It may be something you want to think about.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Walker Wants To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- He strained a rib muscle hitting a  
batting-practice homer and came down with food poisoning eating a 
chicken dinner. It's been a rough week for Larry Walker. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, the reigning NL batting champion and 1997 league MVP,  
was feeling better Friday and remained optimistic he will be in 
right field when the Colorado Rockies open the season Sunday 
against the San Diego Padres at Monterrey, Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I feel I'm playing Sunday,'' Walker said. ``Maybe  
that's looking a little too high and too confident, but I want to 
be in the opening-day lineup if I'm not going to go out there and 
jeopardize anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, 32, strained a muscle in his right rib cage while taking  
batting practice Tuesday. To make matters worse, he came down with 
food poisoning Wednesday night about three hours after eating 
dinner with his brother at a restaurant in Tucson, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes out of nowhere,'' Walker said. ``I felt great the  
whole night until, boom! I was done. The chicken was coming out 
with feathers, the beak, everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hampered by injuries throughout his career, Walker adopted a  
rigorous offseason workout program that helped him add muscle and 
shed 11 pounds. He was rewarded with a $75 million, six-year 
extension the day before Colorado's first spring training game. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's medical history was a focal point of contract  
negotiations. He missed 32 games last season with a sore elbow and 
a sprained finger, and he has played more than 150 games in just 
one of his nine major league seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people just have great genetics,'' Walker said. ``I  
worked hard this winter to avoid things like this, yet it still 
seems to find me. Some guys are just blessed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because his rib injury has improved over the past three days,  
the Rockies have not decided whether to place Walker on the 15-day 
disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	``They talked about the DL and I didn't want to hear about it,  
so right now the DL's not an option for me unless I take a big back 
step on this,'' Walker said. ``The last few days, we've moved 
forward on it and it's felt better, so we'll see how we're doing a 
few days from now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Walker is unable to play, the Rockies can turn to Kurt  
Abbott, Lenny Harris, Pat Watkins or Angel Echevarria. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've thought about it a lot,'' Colorado manager Jim Leyland  
said after the Rockies exhibition game against Boston was canceled 
because of snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he wanted to share his lineup possibilities with  
reporters, Leyland shook his head. ``No.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
