<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Employer Sued Over Voice-Mail Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A man has sued his employer for allegedly failing  
to secure the company voice mail system, even after he complained 
that someone had hacked into the system and was passing offensive 
messages about him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that this makes other companies look at their systems  
and say, `Gee, could this happen with our company?''' Gary Thompson 
said Thursday from his home in suburban Wheaton. ``I would be 
willing to bet most companies haven't even thought about this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson is suing both Jewel Food Stores and its parent,  
American Food Stores Co. He claims that on five occasions beginning 
in 1996 someone posing as a private investigator hired by the 
company left false and defamatory messages in the voice-mail boxes 
of hundreds of American Stores' employees nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The messages included claims that he had HIV, was a drug user,  
cheated on his wife with company secretaries and stole from the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started being treated differently immediately after the  
first message. Work associates stopped shaking my hand,'' said 
Thompson, 45, who is on disability leave after suffering what he 
described as severe depression. 
</P>
<P>
	One day Thompson found a note on the front seat of his car in  
which the author said they understood he was dying of AIDS and 
wanted to know how to apply for his reserved parking space. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those kinds of things start to build up and get to you,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the law has begun to adapt to issues of privacy and  
copyright infringement relating to the Internet and e-mail, voice 
mail has produced a similar set of concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson's lawsuit, filed in January in DuPage County Circuit  
Court, seeks in excess of $50,000 in damages and also names as a 
defendant ``John Doe,'' the unidentified person who allegedly 
obtained a distribution password enabling him to send the messages 
companywide. Thompson said he assumes the messenger is a former 
employee he may have dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	The company insists it reacted swiftly to Thompson's concerns.  
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the allegations are unfounded,'' said Karen  
Ramos, a spokeswoman for Jewel. ``The company took immediate and 
appropriate action in response to the unauthorized voice-mail 
messages in question.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
