<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Still Says No to Troops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says he plans to stay the  
course with NATO's current bombing strategy against Yugoslavia and 
will not authorize the use of ground troops. Clinton said the air 
attacks on Serb targets still have the power to return the ethnic 
Albanians to Kosovo. One refugee official said ``there are about 
900,000 Kosovar Albanians left'' from a population that originally 
totaled about 1.8 million. Clinton says it's become clear that 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic wants to keep the territory 
of Kosovo. The president also issued a warning to Milosevic, 
telling the Serb leader that he holds him personally responsible 
for the safety and well-being of three captured U.S. soldiers. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Proceedings Begin in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb officials are reportedly  
gathering evidence for a trial against the three U.S. soldiers 
captured near the Yugoslavian border. It's not clear what the men 
might be charged with, but a Yugoslav lawyer said the soldiers 
could be charged with ``waging aggression,'' which carries a 
15-year prison term. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., says it would be a 
gross violation of the Geneva conventions if Yugoslavia proceeds 
with trials. 

</P>
<P>
	Arrest Made in 'Melissa' Virus Case  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A man has been arrested by federal and  
state officials and charged with originating the e-mail virus known 
as Melissa. Authorities say David L. Smith originated the virus, 
which caused worldwide e-mail disruption this week, from his 
apartment in Aberdeen, N.J. Smith is charged with interfering with 
the public communication, which carries a sentence of five to 10 
years in prison and up to a $150,000 fine. He was released on 
$100,000 bail. Police say Smith was snared with the help of America 
Online technicians, and a computer task force composed of federal 
and state agents. 

</P>
<P>
	Trial of 2nd Marine Goes to Jury  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A jury has begun deliberating the  
sentence for a Marine aviator involved in a deadly accident at an 
Italian ski resort. Capt. Joseph Schweitzer pleaded guilty Monday 
to obstruction of justice and conspiracy to obstruct justice for 
destroying a videotape made before the Feb. 3, 1998, accident near 
Cavalese, Italy. He was the navigator of the EA-6B Prowler that 
severed a ski lift cable, sending a gondola carrying 20 people 
crashing to the ground. All 20 were killed. Schweitzer could be 
sent to prison or kicked out of the Marines. 

</P>
<P>
	Jr. Gotti Wants To Return to Jail  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Suspected crime family boss John A. ``Junior''  
Gotti has asked to be put back in jail because he cannot afford to 
pay for security guards hired to watch him. Gotti, the son of 
convicted murderer and racketeer John Gotti, faces his own federal 
racketeering trial in five days. He was released on $10 million 
bail in October under strict conditions, meaning he must wear an 
electronic ankle bracelet to track his movements, and he has to pay 
about $24,000 a month for security guards posted outside his house. 
Prosecutors allege Gotti, 35, acted as head of the Gambino crime 
family after his father was convicted of murder in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	'Fame' Actress Sues Husband  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Actress Lori Singer is suing her estranged  
husband, accusing him of stealing millions from her. The star of 
the 1980s television series ``Fame'' and the 1984 movie 
``Footloose'' claims that Richard Emery and their accountant took 
the money from Kuba Productions, the company they created to manage 
her finances. Ms. Singer, 41, filed for divorce from Emery in 1996 
after 16 years of marriage. 

</P>
<P>
	200 Hurt on Bangladesh Train  
</P>
<P>
	DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- A passenger train filled with people  
returning to work after a religious holiday derailed today, killing 
one person and injuring at least 200 people in Bangladesh, 
officials said. Six of the 11 coach cars jumped the tracks at 
Sohagi station in Mymensingh, 70 miles north of Dhaka, Bangladesh's 
capital, an official of state-run Bangladesh Railways said. More 
than 80 of the injured people were hospitalized, 20 of them in 
serious condition, he said. The cause of the accident was not 
known. 

</P>
<P>
	Courier Beats Henman; U.S. Leads  
</P>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) -- Jim Courier outlasted Tim Henman 7-6  
(7-2), 2-6, 7-6 (7-3), 6-7 (12-10), 7-5 today in the opener of the 
best-of-5 Davis Cup series between the United States and Britain. 
Britain returned to the World Group for the first time since 1992 
and is aiming for its first win over the United States since 1935. 
The second match pits Greg Rusedski against Todd Martin. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

</P>
</TEXT>
