<DOCNO> APW19990402.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:57:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Refugees Facing Horrors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Serb forces are systematically rounding up  
ethnic Albanians, herding them into trains and other vehicles and 
transporting them to neighboring countries, U.N. and arriving 
refugees said. 
</P>
<P>
	The forced deportations are bringing Serbs closer to their goal  
of ridding Yugoslavia's Kosovo province of its ethnic Albanian 
majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Pristina, the provincial capital, has become a ghost town, said  
refugees arriving Thursday in Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of the city were crammed onto a train and carried  
away, said Judith Kumin, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees in Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 180,000 refugees have overwhelmed Macedonia, Albania  
and Montenegro since NATO airstrikes began March 24, U.N. spokesman 
Fred Eckhard said Thursday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Even that estimate may be outdated, said Kumin. ``Nobody knows  
how to count them any more,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people died in overloaded trains arriving at the Macedonia  
border Thursday, refugees said. A 72-year-old man, Rexhep Liman, 
survived the trip to the frontier with three dozen other people in 
a tractor-drawn wagon, but died after spending his first night on 
the road in the rain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was not sick, but it was very cold,'' said Skender Mauriqi,  
the tractor driver. ``We left Pristina at 1 p.m. yesterday. All the 
way, he kept saying that he wanted to go back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arrivals from Pristina tell the same story -- being dragged from  
their homes by Serb gunmen and herded onto a hillside in the 
diplomatic quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	A weeping elderly woman recounted how she and other people  
``were pushed, made to go faster and faster'' to get to the train. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said they will kill us and the older people unless we  
moved faster,'' she said. ``Oh my God, what have they done?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mauriqi said he counted about 15 dead in his street, including  
the body of a 17-year-old. ``I know his father,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said some of his Serb neighbors cried to see them leave.  
</P>
<P>
	``One Serb who lived near the mosque came out begging the  
soldiers not to kick us out, but they were shooting in the air, 
just like in Hitler's time,'' he said. ``I never thought I would 
live long enough to see this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Between the Albanian border crossing at Morini and the nearby  
town of Kukes, at least 350 cars packed with people waited on the 
road. The cars had been stripped of their license plates by Serb 
border guards. One car had a wheelchair tied to the roof. 
</P>
<P>
	Other refugees were jammed tightly in Albanian military  
transport trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	At Blace, the border crossing near the Macedonian capital  
Skopje, thousands of people streamed down the railroad tracks 
through the no-man's land separating Yugoslavia and Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	International organizations have rushed to get more supplies to  
the refugees, while Western European nations who met in an 
emergency conference in Bonn, Germany, promised more aid. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-based AmeriCares disaster relief organization announced  
it flew a plane Thursday to Skopje with medical supplies. It was 
planning four more flights in the coming week. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fleeing refugees had no alternative but to walk. Women and  
children said they left men behind in the mountains on their 
two-day trek to Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were afraid to come with us. They are hiding all over,''  
said Bukurie Morina. ``When the Serbs find men, they arrest them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:57:07 </DATE_TIME>
