<DOCNO> APW19990402.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jockey Mourned in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- An apprentice jockey who fell from her horse  
and was trampled to death was remembered Friday at her funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	A horseshoe-shaped wreath surrounded Willy Kan Wai-yue's  
picture. Kan's hearse was driven past dozens of fans who had 
gathered at suburban Shatin race course, where Kan died March 21 
after falling off Happy King during a meter race. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourners burned offerings of 14 paper horses, which Taoists  
believe the dead can receive and use in the next world. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Hong Kong Jockey Club officials, jockeys and fans  
attended Kan's funeral to pay respects to the 20-year-old woman who 
began racing in 1997 and last month became the first female jockey 
to ride in the Hong Kong Derby. Kan won 17 races in her brief 
career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Gov. Undergoes Heart Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- Gov. Paul Cellucci was resting today  
after undergoing an angioplasty, a procedure meant to widen an 
artery on the surface of his heart. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's narrowed artery never posed a serious danger to  
his health and the surgery was not a medical necessity, doctors 
said. Cellucci, 50, had experienced occasional tightness in his 
chest while exercising and the operation was done to allow him to 
exercise at a greater intensity. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor tolerated the whole procedure very well. In fact,  
he was exchanging pleasantries with us the whole time,'' Dr. Gordon 
M. Saperia said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cellucci was expected to be discharged from St. Vincent Hospital  
on Saturday and back at work Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	During angioplasty, a thin tube with a deflated balloon on its  
tip is passed into the narrowed segment, the balloon is inflated 
and the narrowed segment widened. Stents serve as a scaffolding to 
hold the artery open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 06:55:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week mixed  
Friday, with the key index slipping in Tokyo but surging in Taipei. 
Many other bourses were closed for the Easter holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 37.37 points,  
or 0.23 percent, closing at 16,290.19 points. On Thursday, the 
average surged 490.97 points, or 3.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Export-oriented blue chips were among Friday's gainers, while  
some investors took profits by selling issues of other companies, 
including banks and telecommunications, which have recently led the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Tokyo were also hurt by lethargic trade as many  
foreign investors were away for the Easter holidays and because 
dealers remained reluctant to take positions before Monday's 
announcement of the Bank of Japan's quarterly ``tankan'' survey of 
business sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which marked the 50th  
anniversary of its founding on Thursday, held a small ceremony 
Friday morning at the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the ceremony, Bank of Japan Governor Masaru Hayami  
said that the central bank is maintaining a very easy monetary 
stance to help support the nation's struggling economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 120.66 yen in the late  
afternoon, up 2.14 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above 
its late New York level of 120.43 overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan shares soared, with the key index rising 3.0 percent as  
investors bought blue-chip stocks on optimism that the island's 
economy is on the mend. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally that began late in Thursday's session was well  
supported by foreign investors, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei exchange's Weighted Stock Price Index rose 213.83  
points to 7,232.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices on the Seoul Stock Exchange closed generally mixed,  
but the key index rose on buying from local institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 9.89 points, or 1.6  
percent, to 646.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices closed mixed in very quiet trading, The Stock  
Exchange of Thailand index edged up 0.25 point to 357.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were closed for the Easter holidays in Singapore,  
Indonesia, New Zealand, Australia and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
