<DOCNO> APW19990402.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 17:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Collapsed Lung Sidelines Lindros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers center Eric Lindros will  
sit out the remainder of the regular season because of a collapsed 
right lung, the team announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros apparently was hurt when cross-checked during the  
Flyers' game at Nashville on Thursday, team president and general 
manager Bob Clarke said. Television replays also showed Lindros 
falling on his stick in the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly three quarts of blood filled into the space where the  
lung collapsed, and doctors at Baptist Hospital in Nashville were 
draining the blood out with a chest tube, the team said. Flyers 
team physician Dr. Gary Dorshimer said doctors in Nashville 
inserted a vacuum pump in the lung to help re-expand it. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said Lindros would be in Nashville for at least  
another two or three days. His status for the postseason will be 
determined when he returns to Philadelphia, Dorshimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Listening to Dr. Dorshimer and after talking to the doctors in  
Nashville, this is a serious injury,'' Clarke said. ``The players' 
health is of major concern to us. We won't be playing him until all 
doctors are very confident that his health is fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros spoke with reporters in the dressing room for several  
minutes following the Flyers' 2-1 victory over the Predators on 
Thursday night and did not appear to be in pain. He awoke Friday 
morning with chest pain and went to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said Lindros was in stable condition and resting  
comfortably Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was checked in the ribs on the right side. He either  
suffered a rib fracture, or there was enough force with the sudden 
impact trauma that it caused a small microtear in the lung,'' 
Dorshimer said. ``That cause the lung to collapse and blood to fill 
in the space.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said it would be at least seven days before doctors  
could determine the length of Lindros' recovery period and whether 
he would be healthy enough to play should the Flyers make the 
playoffs. Philadelphia is tied with Pittsburgh for second place in 
the Atlantic Division with seven games remaining in the regular 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros' recovery should be aided, though, because he is in  
``peak physical condition,'' Dorshimer added. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Lindros, Eric's father and agent, did not immediately  
return a telephone message seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Lindros' first game following a two-game suspension for  
high-sticking and cutting Petr Nedved of the New York Rangers 
during Philadelphia's 3-1 victory Saturday. He missed two other 
games this season because of a concussion. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was a blow to the Flyers, who already are without top  
defenseman Eric Desjardins. Lindros leads the Flyers with 40 goals 
and 93 points in 71 games. They are 1-1-2 without him this season 
and 44-47-11 during his career with the Flyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 11:32:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chip-Makers Feel Economic Pinch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- Worldwide shipments of equipment  
used to make computer chips fell 21 percent last year due to the 
Asian slowdown and an oversupply of smaller wafers and a delay in 
making the transition to larger wafers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The totals for 1998 confirm what we knew and felt all year.  
1998 was a tough year,'' said Stanley T. Myers, president of 
Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International. 
</P>
<P>
	SEMI represents the businesses that manufacture the equipment  
used to make computer chips. Although the products of the 
semiconductor equipment market are somewhat obscure -- plasma etch 
processing chambers, aluminum low pressure seed sources, wafer 
defect detection tools and more -- they are crucial to supplying key 
products for the Information Age. 
</P>
<P>
	SEMI reported this week that last year, semiconductor equipment  
shipments totaled $21.8 billion, down from the $27.6 billion in 
sales posted in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian markets bore a larger portion of the industry  
downturn, reflecting last year's financial difficulties. Total 
semiconductor equipment sales in Korea declined to $1.3 billion, 
down 51 percent from 1997. Shipments in Japan reached $4.7 billion, 
down 31 percent. The rapid growth of the Taiwan market did carry 
over somewhat into 1998, with sales reaching $3.3 billion, down 14 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers said most segments seemed to hit their low point late in  
the third quarter and have been steadily improving since. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a silver lining, it's that the industry ended 1998  
on an up note and now appears to be stabilizing and headed towards 
recovery,'' said Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts agree. ``We are in the foothills of a long period of  
growth lasting until 2002,'' said to Jean-Philippe Dauvin, chief 
economist for STMicroelectronics. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that although 1998 was tough, ``there is a long way to  
grow before we reach maturity'' in the semiconductor device 
industry. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 06:17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Family, Friends Pray for Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With bright yellow ribbons newly laced across their hometowns,  
relatives and friends of three U.S. servicemen facing trial in 
war-torn Yugoslavia wept and prayed for their safe return. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia said the men were invaders and would be tried today  
as criminals before a military court, despite demands from 
President Clinton that the soldiers be released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is devastated. We're just praying to God he'll come  
out all right,'' said Frank Jasso, great-uncle of captive Staff 
Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of  
Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of 
Smiths Creek, Mich., were captured Wednesday near the 
Yugoslav-Macedonian border. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Stone learned his son had been taken by Yugoslav forces when  
a National Guard officer knocked on his door to deliver the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a very special American and an incredibly proud  
soldier and we are very proud of him,'' Stone said, his voice 
breaking with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	As U.S. networks showed Serb television images of the three men,  
relatives and friends strung yellow ribbons -- symbols of families 
waiting for soldiers to return from war -- all around their 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we saw him on TV it was a great relief, but of course we  
realize he's in a bad situation,'' said Gonzales' mother, Rosie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steven and the two other soldiers are not criminals and should  
not be dealt with as criminals,'' she said. ``They are innocent 
young men over there as part of their duty to their country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Gonzales appeared battered and bruised, his family  
expressed relief he didn't look worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're dealing with it as best we can,'' said his father,  
Gilbert. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales was described as a likable, bright athlete during his  
high school days in Palestine, 90 miles north of Huntsville in east 
Texas. He graduated in 1995 and won a scholarship to Texas A&AMP;M, but 
left after a year to pursue a dream of joining an elite Army corps. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the type of student you'd love to have: hard-working,  
always happy, funny,'' said teacher Kay Stroud, who had Gonzales in 
her advanced placement biology class. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, whose wife, Tricia, and 4-year-old son Ryan live in San  
Antonio, was described as a talented athlete also blessed with the 
``gift of gab.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised he couldn't talk his way out of this,'' said Ken  
Marzka, Stone's cross-country coach at Capac Community 
Junior-Senior High School, about 50 miles northeast of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a tough kid ... he never quit,'' Marzka said. ``Chris  
is going to be just fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School counselor Kathy Kish said Stone was well-liked by  
students and teachers. He was a member of Students Against Drunk 
Driving. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't surprise us a bit that he's serving our country on  
a peace mission,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, outside the home of Ramirez's father, neighbors  
prayed for the captured staff sergeant and reminisced about the 
``all-American kid'' they watched grow up. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, a wrestler in high school, joined the Army after  
graduation in 1992. He wanted to follow the path of his hero, older 
brother Steven, an Army veteran who is now a Los Angeles police 
detective. 
</P>
<P>
	The detective did not speak publicly, but did talk to police  
Cmdr. David Kalish. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very worried,'' Kalish said. ``He told me that his little  
brother is a very brave soldier and he's confident that he will be 
strong through this entire ordeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some neighbors wept as they talked outside the Ramirez home.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a hero now because he did his duty as a military  
personnel,'' said neighbor and longtime friend Johnny Rios. ``We 
just thank God for putting him in our lives to serve the country.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 06:17:57 </DATE_TIME>
