<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smile Again Wins at Santa Anita </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Smile Again pulled ahead of River Keen in  
the stretch to win by a half-length Friday in the $64,170 feature 
race at Santa Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	Smile Again, a 4-year-old colt, stalked the pacesetters and  
rallied on the outside. River Keen held a narrow lead along the 
rail until Smile Again pulled ahead to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Smile Again, ridden by Corrie Nakatani, finished the mile in  
1:36 and paid $4.20, $2.40 and $2.20. River Keen paid $2.40 and 
$2.10 and third-place Busy Little Beaver paid $2.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Smile Again earned $37,200 to boost his earnings to $142,695.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minority Admissions Up at Cal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- The number of black and Hispanic  
students admitted to the University of California rebounded in the 
second year without affirmative action, an increase credited to 
strong recruitment and a more comprehensive application review. 
</P>
<P>
	Figures released Friday show the number of underrepresented  
minorities -- blacks, Hispanics and American Indians -- admitted to 
all eight undergraduate campuses this fall is only 27 students 
short of the number admitted in fall 1997, the last year race could 
be considered. 
</P>
<P>
	``The gloom and doom that was being preached by the proponents  
of preferences was grossly premature,'' said Ward Connerly, a 
member of the Board of Regents who led the fight to stop 
considering race in admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Connerly said the figures vindicate his argument that the old  
system of affirmative action didn't do much more than create 
ill-will. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been saying that we need a new paradigm about affirmative  
action and that's really where we're headed,'' he said. 
``Everybody's looking at California to see how we can come up with 
a new concept of affirmative action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But affirmative action supporter Pedro Noguera, an ethnic  
studies professor at Berkeley, viewed the numbers slightly 
differently. 
</P>
<P>
	``It tells me that the university, the admissions office in  
particular, has been working hard at getting students to apply,'' 
he said. ``I think they're still working against the damage which 
was done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, admissions of underrepresented minorities dropped 61  
percent at Berkeley and 36 percent at UCLA. Other campuses had 
smaller declines, and some even posted slight increases, so the 
system-wide total was a less dramatic drop of about 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Berkeley, which turned away about three of every four  
applicants, admitted 29 percent more underrepresented minorities 
than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkeley took a more detailed approach to admissions, looking at  
such things as parental education and income levels, how the 
student did in comparison to others in his high school and how many 
honors courses the students took compared to how many were offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking at all eight undergraduate campuses, Hispanic admissions  
increased considerably this year, actually surpassing 1997 levels 
by 2 percent (5,622 to 5,753) while the numbers of American Indian 
and black students were higher than 1998 but still below 1997 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the improvement, Noguera said the figures don't come  
close to reflecting California's racial makeup. Hispanics, for 
example, comprise 29 percent of the state population but only 12 
percent of fall 1999 admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a long way to go,'' Noguera said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
