<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Finish Mixed / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen today and a top  
official of Japan's Finance Ministry renewed pressure against the 
Japanese currency's rise. Japanese stocks turned mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.66 yen in the late afternoon, up 2.14 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level 
of 120.43 overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 37.37 points, or 0.23  
percent, closing the week at 16,290.19 points. On Thursday, the 
average advanced 490.97 points, or 3.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved higher against the yen on  
good buying by U.S. banks at around 120.50 yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback's strength also derived from remarks by Haruhiko  
Kuroda, a senior official at Japan's Finance Ministry, who 
reiterated the ministry's stance that excessive yen strength is 
undesirable. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuroda, director-general of the ministry's international bureau,  
spoke to a small group of reporters without specifying an 
appropriate level for the currency. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen tends to make Japanese exports more expenses  
aboard, and thus less competitive, cutting into earnings of 
export-oriented Japanese companies. Japan is struggling to bail 
itself out of its worst recessions since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade remained thin ahead of the weekend and holidays in Europe  
and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.41 yen and 120.88 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro was traded at 130.02 yen, up from 128.42 yen  
late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, export-oriented blue chips were among  
today's gainers, while some investors took profits by selling 
issues of other companies, including banks and telecommunications, 
which have recently led the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices were also hurt by lethargic trade as many foreign  
investors were away for the Easter holidays and because dealers 
remained reluctant to take positions before Monday's announcement 
of the Bank of Japan's quarterly ``tankan'' survey of business 
sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was fairly active, with about 614 million shares  
changing hands on the exchange's first section, compared with 
Thursday's turnover of 726 million shares. Declines outnumbered 
advancers 614 to 601, with 108 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 3.73 points, or 0.29 percent, to 1,304.17. The 
TOPIX rose 33.22 points, or 2.6 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which marked the 50th  
anniversary of its founding on Thursday, held a small ceremony 
today morning at the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the ceremony, Bank of Japan Governor Masaru Hayami  
said that the central bank is maintaining a very easy monetary 
stance to help support the nation's struggling economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.740 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.720 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.51 yen from 100.69 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
