<DOCNO> APW19990402.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 17:51:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Storm Blankets Prairies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Just when Bill Ellis thought it was safe to stow  
his snow shovel, a storm delivered a few feet of snow Friday to his 
mountain home in southwestern Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``It caught us unaware,'' Ellis said, just days after he had  
been out bicycling in the sun. A week ago, he said, ``we were using 
the snow shovel to ... clean the yard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy, wet snow on Friday coated budding trees and grass in  
Denver that already had begun turning green. Temperatures hovered 
in the high 20s, a sharp drop from highs in the 70s Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The spring storm blanketed thirsty prairies and mountains with  
the first significant precipitation in weeks, sending residents 
hunting for gloves and parkas that they haven't used much all 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Snowfall amounts ranged from 5 inches in metropolitan Denver to  
2 feet in the Durango area, with more snow expected. 
</P>
<P>
	At lower elevations, commuters crept to work and home on slushy  
streets while mountain travelers contended with wet, ice-spotted 
roads. Some schools canceled classes or delayed start times, and 
skiers and snowboarders flocked to resorts. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with a thick layer of snow across Coors Field, the  
Colorado Rockies canceled their first home appearance of the 
season, an exhibition game against the Boston Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	The precipitation came to Colorado after a winter that officials  
said was the driest there in 18 years. A federal survey conducted 
Thursday determined the state's snowpack is 65 percent of normal. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wyoming, snow continued to fall Friday after winter-like  
conditions stymied the state Thursday, canceling flights and 
closing schools. Snowfall amounts ranged up to 31 inches in Sinks 
Canyon in central Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Dakota, several cities had piles of snow from a storm  
that blew through Thursday. About 4,000 residents lost power for a 
time Friday as the state cleaned up from one storm and prepared for 
the next one, expected Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
