<DOCNO> APW19990402.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Baldness Drug Sales Are Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They've finally come up with a pill that  
prevents baldness. So why isn't it flying off the shelves? 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, men are reluctant to take a prescription drug  
when they're healthy. For another, this one carries a slight risk 
of causing impotence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to convince people to try it in the first place,''  
said John Ertel, who uses the hair loss pill Propecia and runs an 
Internet site on hair loss from his Austin, Texas home. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmaceutical giant Merck &AMP; Co. last year spent a hefty $91  
million promoting Propecia directly to U.S. consumers, according to 
Competitive Media Reporting, a media research firm. 
</P>
<P>
	For the effort, Merck posted just $68 million in U.S. sales last  
year and an additional $15 million overseas. Even though drug 
companies often spend more to promote new drugs than they initially 
receive in sales, Propecia's financial performance is only about 
two-thirds of what Wall Street was expecting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an outright disappointment,'' said Neil Sweig, a  
drug analyst with Southeast Research Partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck officials say they are still bullish on Propecia, which  
was first introduced in January 1998 to treat mild to moderate hair 
loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased with the results,'' said Merck spokeswoman  
Mary Elizabeth Basaman. She said the advertising spending estimates 
were inflated, but refused to disclose how much Merck spent on 
direct-to-consumer Propecia ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Propecia works by suppressing a hormone that shrinks hair  
follicles. It's a lower dosage of Merck's drug Proscar, which 
millions of men have taken to treat enlarged prostates. 
</P>
<P>
	The main side effect seen with Propecia is decreased libido and  
impotence, in just 2 percent of men. The problems disappear when 
men quit taking the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of this helps the product sell to men who are in their  
20s and 30s and are sexual athletes,'' Sweig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Propecia can also cause a certain birth defect in pregnant  
women, and doctors warn women should not even touch the pills. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors say men who take the one a day pill are generally  
satisfied, but the small chance of impotence is a barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only hesitation is there has been a lot of notoriety on  
the side effects associated with the pill,'' said Dr. Ken Washenik, 
a dermatologist at New York University Medical Center who conducts 
research on Propecia. 
</P>
<P>
	Another weakness is that Propecia does little for men with  
receding hairline. It only tends to grow hair on top and back of 
the head, doctors say. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Propecia, the nation's 40 million balding men had only  
one option: slathering nonprescription Rogaine on their scalps 
twice a day. The convenience of Propecia comes at a price. Propecia 
cost $50 a month, twice as much as Rogaine. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the men who use Propecia grow varying amounts of  
hair, though men often have to use it for six months to a year 
before they see more hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies show that after two years of use, 66 percent of Propecia  
patients had regrown hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Propecia is more effective at slowing hair loss. In studies,  
only 17 percent of balding men who took Propecia for two years were 
still losing their hair vs. 72 percent of men who took a placebo. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is definitely the best medical treatment for hair loss,''  
said Dr. Paul McAndrews, a Pasadena, Calif. dermatologist 
specializing in hair loss. He's had just one of 350 Propecia 
patients experienced decreased libido. And that patient stayed on 
the drug because he liked the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Propecia was never expected to become a billion-dollar a  
year blockbuster, analysts said Merck saw the pill as a chance to 
sell a drug that millions of men would take for rest of their 
lives-- or as long as they wanted to keep their hair. 
</P>
<P>
	But selling a hair-loss drug has proved a tougher challenge than  
selling a heart drug. 
</P>
<P>
	``Treatment for hair loss requires a lot more groundwork because  
men are just not used to taking drugs for that condition,'' said 
Alex Zisson, analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. In addition, Propecia 
isn't covered by insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ertel, 27, who runs Regrowth.com web site has been taking  
Propecia since it first came out. He uses Rogaine as well. So far, 
Ertel likes what he sees when he looks in the mirror: A fuller head 
of hair. ``I look better with hair than without.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:31:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capture of U.S. Soldiers Hits Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Wearing dark sunglasses to shield her tears,  
the mother of a U.S. soldier captured by Serb forces says she has 
faith her son will survive his ordeal in Yugoslavia and return home 
safely. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way I can say how I feel. Everyone knows,'' said  
Vivian Ramirez, whose son, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, was 
captured Wednesday near the Yugoslav-Macedonian border. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to thank all the people for their prayers, their  
letters ... the phone calls. I know all of you are praying for my 
son, mi hijo,'' she said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia are hitting home for many  
Hispanic-American residents of East Los Angeles, which over the 
years has sent thousands of its native sons into uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernie Rios' heart sank when he flipped on his television and  
saw a picture of his boyhood friend, wearing camouflage fatigues 
and looking tired and bruised. 
</P>
<P>
	Rios, 33, grew up two houses down from the Ramirez family in a  
blue-collar East Los Angeles neighborhood, played touch football 
with him on the street and saw him grow from a boy into a clean-cut 
young man. 
</P>
<P>
	And then this image on his TV screen. ``When it's one of your  
own,'' Rios said, ``it really touches you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hispanic-Americans have come into harm's way long before Ramirez  
joined the Army, and they'll do so for years to come, said Daniel 
Ortiz, a Gulf War veteran and commander of the local Veterans of 
Foreign Wars post. 
</P>
<P>
	Ortiz's VFW branch is housed at American Legion Post 804, a navy  
blue building tucked among modest storefronts on Cesar Chavez 
Avenue. Inside, the names of Hispanic-American veterans are etched 
on murals, plaques and pictures covering the walls. 
</P>
<P>
	The veterans' fierce patriotism is obvious. One bumper sticker  
with an American flag reads, ``YOU'LL BURN IT OVER MY DEAD BODY!'' 
A flier tacked on a bulletin board features a sniper's target 
superimposed over a mug shot of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being the hyphenated 'Mexican-American,' a lot of people take  
it for granted that we ARE American, first and foremost,'' Ortiz 
said. ``A lot of people join the military to show we want to be 
counted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Hispanic-Americans enlisted because they didn't  
have enough money to go to college, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our people needed an alternative, so they joined the military  
and had pride in being an American,'' Ortiz said. ``When our 
country calls, we're proud to step forward and defend our 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They enlist to break free from a landscape of few opportunities  
and low-paying jobs, said Rios, whose father was a Marine corporal 
during the Korean conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good thing,'' Rios said. ``They're over there on the  
other side of the world protecting us. Without people like them, we 
wouldn't be able to have the freedom that we have now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ramirez said she wrote her son a letter that will be sent  
by the International Red Cross. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him of how everyone is praying for him and for the  
other two soldiers,'' she said. ``I know how their parents feel, 
how their wives feel. I know we will get them back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rios was among friends, family and supporters participating in a  
candlelight prayer vigil for Ramirez. Similar outpourings of 
support were happening in the hometowns of the two other captured 
soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Capac, Mich., people headed to church to pray for Army  
Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Christopher Stone's family is also carrying a cross,'' the  
Rev. Jasper Sirianni said during a Good Friday observance attended 
by Stone's sisters. ``They're carrying a cross today, the cross of 
suffering, the cross of uncertainty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, the parents of Army Spc. Steven Gonzales wrapped a  
yellow ribbon around a pecan tree in the Huntsville town square. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you to all of the community for the support and prayers  
and the thoughts for our son,'' said Gilbert Gonzalez, whose wife, 
Rosalie, clasped a long stem yellow rose at the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
