<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen and the euro  
during lethargic trading Friday, as U.S. foreign exchange trading 
ended early while other major U.S. markets and all European markets 
were closed to observe Good Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0779, down  
from $1.0793 late Thursday. The dollar also was quoted at 120.55 
Japanese yen, up from 120.43 yen on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the yen during Asian trading as U.S.  
banks bought dollars when the U.S. currency hit 120.50 yen. The 
dollar also was bolstered by remarks by a senior Japanese Finance 
Ministry official who reiterated the ministry's position that 
excessive yen strength is undesirable. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan expects its exports to help the economy revive from its  
worst recession since World War II and a higher yen makes exports 
more expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	With European markets closed, U.S.-based traders declined to  
move the dollar in either direction because of mixed signals from 
the Labor Department's report Thursday on unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. unemployment rate declined to a 29-year low of 4.2  
percent in March even as job losses mounted in manufacturing 
accompanied by sluggish job growth elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading also was calm because European and some Asia-Pacific  
markets were to remain closed Monday for the remainder of the 
Easter holiday. In addition, the situation in Kosovo continued with 
uncertainty and Japan was to release its quarterly survey on 
business sentiment Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are reluctant to hold positions over the weekend''  
given those circumstances, said David Gilmore, a partner at Foreign 
Exchange Analytics in Essex, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4799 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4808, and 1.4960 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4993. The British 
pound fell to $1.6036 from $1.6041. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8146 German 
marks, up from 1.8123; 6.0864 French francs, up from 6.0790; and 
1,795.33 Italian lire, up from 1,792.11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
