<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Meares out 5-7 days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) -- Pittsburgh Pirates shortstop Pat Meares  
will be out five to seven days with a sprained left wrist and will 
miss opening day Monday against Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares was injured fouling off a pitch in the fifth inning  
Thursday against the Phillies in Clearwater, Fla. He started to 
take the field in the bottom of the inning, but manager Gene Lamont 
pulled him back and Meares returned to the Pirates' camp in 
Bradenton for X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	The X-rays showed no break, but Meares will be re-examined by  
team physicians once the team returns to Pittsburgh on Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a little clicking sound in there and they're going to  
check the cartilage, but there doesn't appear to be any ligament 
damage,'' Lamont said. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is cartilage damage, Meares might need arthroscopic  
surgery that could sideline him for 4-6 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	If the cartilage is OK, Meares expects to play again April 9, so  
the Pirates did not put him on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Abraham Nunez was added to the 25-man roster and will  
travel north with the team. The Pirates did not have to clear a 
spot for him because they had not yet added right-hander Kris 
Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	Benson will be activated before making his major league debut  
against the Cubs on Friday, when Nunez is expected to return to 
Triple-A Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	During Meares' absence, rookie Warren Morris will play every day  
at second base and Mike Benjamin will start at short. If Meares' 
injury lingers longer than anticipated, Nunez may make a start or 
two at shortstop against a left-handed starter, with Benjamin 
moving to second. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think a whole lot about injuries, because they're  
going to happen, but four to five days before the season starts you 
like to be injury free,'' Lamont said. ``If somebody gets hurt 10 
days before the season starts, you usually have time to get them 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meares' injury came at an inopportune time for the reconstructed  
Pirates, who have rebuilt their lineup with five new starting 
position players since finishing 69-93 last season. 
</P>
<P>
	With Meares contributing four homers and 12 RBIs, the Pirates  
have hit more homers than in any spring since they first began 
compiling detailed statistics in 1986. Not coincidentally, they 
will leave Florida with their first winning spring record since 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates sought to improve their offense after hitting an  
NL-low 107 homers last season -- only 37 fewer than Mark McGwire hit 
by himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The most significant upgrade has been at shortstop, where Meares  
has hit and fielded far better than 1998 starters Kevin Polcovich 
and Lou Collier, who combined for a .223 average, two homers, 48 
RBIs and 38 errors. 
</P>
<P>
	``He makes us a different team,'' Lamont said of Meares.  
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates lucked into landing Meares, one of the majors' most  
productive offensive shortstops with 70 RBIs last season for the 
Twins. He turned down their $10 million offer shortly after the 
season ended, but the Twins later pulled it off the table and 
decided to dramatically cut their payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares suddenly found himself without a team six weeks before  
the start of spring training, and the Pirates were the only team 
that could offer him a chance to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is pretty good,'' general manager Cam Bonifay said. ``We're  
going to catch the ball better, our offense is going to be more 
consistent, we're going to score more runs.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
