<HEADLINE> N.H.'s Krog Gets Hockey Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Jason Krog had two goals and an assist to  
send New Hampshire to its first NCAA championship game. Some 12 
hours later, the school had another first when Krog won the 1999 
Hobey Baker Award, given to college hockey's best player. 
</P>
<P>
	Krog, the nation's scoring leader this year, was presented with  
the award Friday at a ceremony that seemed like a New Hampshire pep 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony was held at the team hotel for the NCAA Frozen  
Four, and the crowd packing the ballroom included Krog's teammates 
and coaches, many of his relatives and a group of cheering Wildcats 
fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thank my teammates for making the year so successful and  
enjoyable,'' said Krog, a senior center. ``I feel this award is 
just as much theirs as mine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He invited his teammates onto the podium, and some helped him  
hold the trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he's accomplished is not by accident,'' coach Richard  
Umile said. ``He has led our team by example. He doesn't talk a 
lot, he just does it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krog was a unanimous selection for the Hockey East Player of the  
Year, leading the Wildcats to the conference title. He ranked in 
the top 10 percent of his academic class with a 3.67 grade-point 
average last semester. He was a finalist for college hockey's 
Humanitarian Award. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the ice or in the classroom, everybody looks up to Jason.  
He's respected as a hard worker in everything he does,'' Umile 
said. ``For me, it's been a special honor to coach Jason Krog and 
spend four years with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krog has 84 points on 34 goals and 50 assists, with one more  
game to go -- New Hampshire faces Hockey East rival Maine on 
Saturday for the 1999 NCAA title. 
</P>
<P>
	Krog had a pair of goals and an assist in Thursday night's 5-3  
semifinal victory over Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats made it to the semis last year, but were eliminated  
4-0 by eventual champion Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	There were 10 finalists for this year's Hobey Baker Award.  
Michigan State center Mike York was the runner-up, but no other 
spots were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The finalists are picked by a vote of the NCAA's Division I  
coaches, then a committee consisting of coaches, print and 
electronic media representatives, NHL scouts and one USA Hockey 
representative choose the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	The other finalists were Jason Blake of North Dakota, Hugo  
Boisvert of Ohio State, Brian Gionta of Boston College, Jeff 
Hamilton of Yale, Eric Heffler of St. Lawrence, Steve Kariya of 
Maine, Michel Larocque of Boston University and Brian Swanson of 
Colorado College. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristine Pierce, a star for the Rochester Institute of  
Technology, received the 1999 Humanitarian Award for her volunteer 
work. She helped at a soup kitchen and worked with children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
