<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Jury Dismisses Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury issued the first  
punishment against an aviator involved in the Italian ski gondola 
accident today, kicking the jet's navigator out of the Marines for 
destroying a videotape shot during the fatal flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Joseph Schweitzer had pleaded guilty to obstruction of  
justice and conspiracy -- charges that carried up to 10 years in 
prison. He admitted throwing the tape into a fire two days after 
his jet clipped an Alpine gondola cable, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	After deliberating for more than three hours, a jury of nine  
Marine officers recommended that Schweitzer be dismissed from the 
military -- the equivalent of a dishonorable discharge for an 
enlisted person. 
</P>
<P>
	He smiled at his lawyers after court adjourned.  
</P>
<P>
	``I respect the decision that was made by my peers,'' said  
Schweitzer, 31, who has been an officer for 10 years. ``A long, 
painful chapter of my life was finally concluded, and I was happy 
to start a new one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Alvin Keller, the judge, accepted the jury's  
recommendation, which was virtually identical to the punishment 
proposed in his plea agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence still must be approved by Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, who  
convened the court-martial. Pace, commander of Marine Forces 
Atlantic in Norfolk, Va., may approve the sentence or recommend a 
lighter one, and Schweitzer has the right to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Dave Beck said he would urge Pace to reduce the  
sentence to a reprimand or no punishment at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer and Capt. Richard Ashby, the pilot of the EA-6B  
Prowler jet, originally faced manslaughter charges that could have 
sent them to prison for more than 200 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A military jury acquitted Ashby in February, and similar charges  
against Schweitzer were then dropped by the government. Ashby still 
faces an obstruction court-martial for the destruction of the 
videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ashby verdict enraged and embittered relatives of the  
victims, as well as Italian leaders, who said they would explore 
options in pursuing their own case against the crew. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the victims' relatives was present when Schweitzer was  
sentenced. Schweitzer, of Westbury, N.Y., sat stoically as the 
verdict was read. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, families of the Belgian victims issued a statement  
criticizing the U.S. government for not agreeing to settle with 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why will the U.S. government not accept responsibility and  
exercise its authority to close this case as soon as possible in a 
humane and amicable manner?'' asked Yves Eyskens, whose sister, 
Rose-Marie was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Margo Anthonissen, who lost her daughter, Hadewich, complained  
that the victims' relatives weren't permitted to fully describe 
their loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are unhappy we twice flew all the way from Belgium to tell  
our story, only to be restricted from discussing the essence of 
this whole case,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maj. Stu Couch, a government prosecutor, had argued that  
Schweitzer should not only be kicked out of the Marines, but should 
also be sent to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this a character flaw or just a crime?'' Couch asked in his  
closing statement Friday. ``Everybody trusted him. ... That makes 
the perfect conspirator, somebody who has that amount of trust 
built up over a period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch said the tape so worried Schweitzer and Ashby that they  
stayed in the cockpit after making an emergency landing at the 
Aviano, Italy, air base to swap the tape for a blank one. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer testified Thursday that he stopped taping 10 minutes  
before the jet severed the cable, but had smiled once into the 
camera and feared the image would be used in media reports of the 
tragedy. Destroying the tape was the biggest mistake of his life, 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
