<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Jury Says To Dismiss Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury on Friday recommended  
dismissal from the Marine Corps for a navigator who admitted 
destroying a personal videotape he made before his jet cut an 
Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-man panel of Marine officers deliberated 3 1/2 hours  
Friday before recommending the punishment for Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer sat stoically and the courtroom was silent as the  
judge, Col. Alvin Keller, imposed the recommended sentence. But 
after court adjourned, Schweitzer smiled at his lawyers and nodded 
his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty Monday to obstruction of justice and  
conspiracy for destroying the tape after his EA-6B Prowler hit the 
cable over Cavalese, Italy, on Feb. 3, 1998. The ski gondola 
plunged 370 feet into a valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge had the option of sentencing Schweitzer to a  
previously undisclosed punishment recommended as part of 
Schweitzer's guilty plea, or to accept the jury's recommendation -- 
whichever is more lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	He chose the jury's recommendation. The sentence proposed in the  
plea agreement, divulged after the jury made its recommendation, 
called for forfeiture of pay and allowance and dismissal from the 
Marine Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence doesn't take effect until it is approved by Lt.  
Gen. Peter Pace, who convened the court-martial. Pace, commander of 
Marine Forces Atlantic in Norfolk, Va., may approve the sentence or 
recommend a lighter one. Schweitzer then could choose to pursue his 
decision through the military appeals process. 
</P>
<P>
	A prosecutor, Maj. Stu Couch, urged the jury earlier Friday to  
recommend Schweitzer's dismissal from the service and prison, but 
said the government didn't wish to see him sentenced to the maximum 
10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this a character flaw or just a crime?'' Couch asked.  
``Everybody trusted him. ... That makes the perfect conspirator, 
somebody who has that amount of trust built up over a period of 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Dave Beck said the harshest punishment should  
be a letter of reprimand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Capt. Schweitzer has got to get up every day and know his  
career in the Marine Corps is over,'' Beck said. ``This good and 
faithful Marine, this outstanding Marine officer made some bad 
decisions over a three- to five-day period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck reminded the jurors that Schweitzer ``looked you in the  
eye. ... He told you things that nobody had any way of knowing 
until he came forward to tell the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch said the tape so worried Schweitzer and the pilot, Capt.  
Richard Ashby, that they stayed in the cockpit after making an 
emergency landing at the Aviano, Italy, air base to swap the tape 
for a blank one. Schweitzer said he later tossed the cassette into 
a bonfire. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's the one thing on his mind?'' Couch asked. ``That tape.  
That tape was stressing him out ... driving him nuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer testified Thursday that he stopped taping 10 minutes  
before the jet severed the cable, but said he smiled once into the 
camera and feared the image would be used in media reports of the 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	He described his destruction of the tape as the biggest mistake  
of his life and said he wanted to die after learning people in the 
gondola had been killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Involuntary manslaughter charges against Schweitzer were dropped  
after Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was acquitted last month 
of the same charges. Ashby still faces the two obstruction charges 
and his trial is scheduled April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Two back seat crewmen in the radar-jamming aircraft were charged  
after the accident, but the charges were dismissed last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
