<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mixup Costs Record at Swim Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Matthew Dunn should have swum third and Ray  
Hass fourth in Australia's 800-meter freestyle relay at the world 
short-course swimming championships. 
</P>
<P>
	But the order was reversed, and the difference was a lost chance  
at $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	For not following the order listed on the entry card,  
Australia's relay quartet was disqualified today in the 
preliminaries for the event. 
</P>
<P>
	The team in the heats came within two seconds of breaking its  
own world record, and for the final, the team planned to substitute 
-- legally -- three world champions, giving them a strong chance at a 
short-course world record. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'd have broken the record by a considerable amount,''  
Australian coach Don Talbot said. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury dismissed an appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first time at these championships, FINA, swimming's  
world governing body, is offering $15,000 for each world record 
broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Record breakers so far include Australian Ian Thorpe in the  
200-meter freestyle; the Swedish women's 800-meter freestyle relay 
team; Slovakia's Martina Moravcova, who beat American Jenny 
Thompson's world mark in the 100-meter individual medley; and 
Thompson, who promptly broke it again. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbot said he had submitted the entry card with Dunn third and  
Hass fourth, behind Todd Pearson and Daniel Kowalski. Preparing to 
send the swimmers into action, an Australian staffer sought to 
reach an officials' table to check the card and make sure they were 
following the correct order, Talbot said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, officials ``don't let people move around freely''  
in the Hong Kong Coliseum, and the staffer wasn't allowed access to 
the table. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Talbot said, a meet official who should have ensured in  
advance that swimmers were in the correct order did not do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly there was fault with us,'' Talbot said, ``but I  
think everybody has a right to argue their case. They didn't want 
to hear that there was error on their side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was prepared to point out to the appeals jury that a Canadian  
women's relay quartet swam out of order Thursday without penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury refused to hear explanations, he added.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to rebound from the disappointment. They were set on  
getting a world record, and there's bonus money for that,'' Talbot 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team that swam in the heats finished in 7 minutes, 4.73  
seconds, close to the world mark of 7:02.74 set by Australia at the 
last short-course championships in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	For the final, the Australians had planned to have Thorpe, Grant  
Hackett and Michael Klim join Dunn for a run at the record. 
</P>
<P>
	Thorpe is the world long-course champion at 400 meters, and  
holds the short-course world records at 200 and 400. Last week, 
Hackett broke the world 200-meter long-course record. He also is 
the world long-course champion at 1,500 meters and the short-course 
world record holder in that event. Klim is the long-course world 
champion in the 200 freestyle and 100 butterfly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
