<HEADLINE> Jr. Gotti Wants To Return to Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just five days before his federal racketeering  
trial was to begin, John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, who fought to obtain 
release on bail, asked a judge to put him back in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti, indicted in January 1998, was released on $10 million  
bail in October under strict conditions. Two dozen friends and 
relatives put up their homes and businesses to help him make bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors allege Gotti, 35, acted as head of the Gambino crime  
family after his father, John J. Gotti, was convicted of murder in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors did not object to Thursday's unusual request, and  
Gotti is to surrender to marshals on Tuesday, the day his trial is 
scheduled to start. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of Gotti's release, he must wear an electronic  
ankle bracelet to track his movements, his phone calls are 
monitored, and he has to pay about $24,000 a month for security 
guards posted outside his house. 
</P>
<P>
	In U.S. District Court, defense lawyer Gerald Shargel began to  
explain his client's request before Gotti stopped him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can no longer afford,'' Shargel said when Gotti cut him  
off, saying, ``Never mind, never mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Gotti's lawyers sought to lower his bail conditions in  
December, defense attorney Sarita Kedia said her client was broke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
