<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bomber May Have Targeted Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal investigators examined charred remains  
of a mail bomb here for evidence it may have been sent by a man who 
tried Friday to plead guilty in a bomb incident in Las Vegas, 
government officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators also looked for evidence the device found at a  
Washington post office was intended for President Clinton, said law 
enforcement sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. A law 
enforcement source would not say why authorities think Clinton may 
have been targeted. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources said initial examination of the device showed  
similarities to a bomb that exploded at a Dallas post office and to 
explosive devices found in Las Vegas, where Frank Darwin Alexander 
was arrested Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, 53, appeared Friday before a federal magistrate in  
Las Vegas, where he attempted to plead guilty to charges related to 
a bomb allegedly addressed to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and 
Firearms office in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plead no contest, ... guilty,'' Alexander told Magistrate  
Robert Johnston. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston, however, refused to accept the plea and appointed a  
public defender for Alexander. An April 9 arraignment was scheduled 
and Alexander was ordered held without bail. 
</P>
<P>
	During the hearing, Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas O'Connell  
said Alexander told Las Vegas police he had mailed two devices and 
attempted to mail a third. O'Connell said one detonated in a Dallas 
postal facility and another likely detonated in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries were reported in connection with any of the devices.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Connell said Alexander also told police he had ``an admiration  
for Theodore Kaczynski and Timothy McVeigh'' and would do the same 
thing again if released. The prosecutor said police found canisters 
of gunpowder and pipe, ``enough to construct eight or so devices,'' 
in Alexander's room. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander also faces state charges in connection with explosive  
devices found in his Las Vegas motel room. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said federal investigators are comparing remnants of  
the Washington device with unexploded bombs found in Las Vegas and 
components of the pipe bomb that exploded and ignited a small fire 
Sunday inside the Dallas Bulk Mail Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ... looking at components that have been taken to the  
ATF lab, and getting together with the postal lab,'' ATF special 
agent Brad Earman said in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The Secret Service, which investigates threats against the  
president, is involved because of the possibility the Washington 
bomb was addressed to the White House, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Secret Service referred questions about Alexander to the  
U.S. attorney's office in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still investigating his days prior to Sunday. We  
continue to try to understand everything that was going on,'' said 
Tracy Hite, an ATF agent in Las Vegas. ``We're not going to talk 
about motive,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	ATF agents helped collect the debris from the Washington bomb  
Thursday night -- nearly a week after the device apparently started 
a smoky fire inside a truck trailer at the post office loading 
dock. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, post office employees and local Washington  
firefighters thought ``something combustible, or careless smoking, 
or something else innocuous'' ignited the March 26 fire, said 
postal inspector Douglas Bem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Three containers of mail were charred severely,'' and left  
behind at the loading dock when firefighters left, Bem said. The 
containers sat undisturbed until Thursday, when investigators in 
the Alexander case asked about the possibility ``of another device 
that might be headed this way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Local postal officials then noticed the routine internal report  
of the loading dock fire, Bem said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bomb investigators who then headed to the loading dock  
determined almost immediately that the damage was not from an 
ordinary fire, one source said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Remains of the device arrived at the Postal Inspection Service  
laboratory near Washington, where analysts were already examining 
remains of the Dallas bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander told authorities the Dallas mail bomb was addressed to  
San Antonio television evangelist John Hagee, pastor of the 
17,000-member Cornerstone Ministries, said Linda Kirksey, a postal 
inspector in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief statement, Hagee said he was cooperating with the  
investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
