<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Collapsed Lung Sidelines Lindros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The regular season came to an abrupt end for  
Philadelphia Flyers center Eric Lindros after he suffered a 
collapsed right lung. His status for the playoffs remains unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros, the Flyers' on-ice and emotional leader, apparently  
suffered the injury after being cross-checked during the Flyers' 
2-1 win at Nashville on Thursday. Television replays also showed 
Lindros falling on his stick in the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury was never considered career-threatening, team  
officials stressed. Lindros will remain at Baptist Hospital in 
Nashville for at least another day to stabilize his lung, and his 
status for the playoffs will be re-evaluated when he returns to 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Listening to Dr. (Gary) Dorshimer and after talking to the  
doctors in Nashville, this is a serious injury,'' team president 
and general manager Bob Clarke said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Flyers spokesman said the rest of the team, which played the  
Bruins in Boston today, was caught off-guard, because Lindros did 
not complain of chest pains after the Predators game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The players' health is of major concern to us. We won't be  
playing him until all doctors are very confident that his health is 
fine,'' Clarke added. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros spoke with reporters in the dressing room for several  
minutes following the victory and did not appear to be in pain. He 
awoke Friday morning with chest pain and went to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly three quarts of blood filled into the space where the  
lung collapsed, and doctors at the hospital drained out the blood 
with a chest tube. Droshimer, the Flyers' team physician, said 
doctors in Nashville inserted a vacuum pump in the lung to help 
re-expand it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was checked in the ribs on the right side. He either  
suffered a rib fracture, or there was enough force with the sudden 
impact trauma that it caused a small microtear in the lung,'' said 
Dorshimer, who added that Lindros was in stable condition and 
resting comfortably at Baptist Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that he is in excellent physical shape and a strong  
person to begin with will help in his recovery,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He estimated it would be at least seven days before doctors  
could determine the length of Lindros' recovery period and whether 
he would be healthy enough to play in the playoffs. Philadelphia is 
tied with Pittsburgh for fifth place in the Eastern Conference; 
eight teams make the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Lindros, Eric's father and agent, did not immediately  
return a telephone message seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Lindros' first game following a two-game suspension for  
high-sticking and cutting Petr Nedved of the New York Rangers 
during Philadelphia's 3-1 victory last Saturday. He missed two 
other games this season because of a concussion. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was a major blow to the Flyers, who already are without  
top defenseman Eric Desjardins. Lindros leads the Flyers with 40 
goals and 93 points in 71 games. They are 1-1-2 without him this 
season and 44-47-11 during his career with the Flyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The team also announced that Lindros' regular left wing, John  
LeClair, would miss at least the next two games because of a sore 
back. The Flyers have seven games left. 
</P>
<P>
	Right wing Mark Recchi's status was to be evaluated before the  
Boston game after he complained of headaches and nausea. Dorshimer 
said Recchi's condition might be partly related to the March 22 
concussion that kept him out of the lineup for three games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
