<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets' Williams Goes on Injured List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- New Jersey Nets interim coach Don  
Casey calls it ``center by committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what it's come down to for the Nets, now that All-Star  
center Jayson Williams has joined the team's big men on the injured 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	But after practice Friday, Casey was confident of his team's  
ability to cope with the latest in a series of troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a resilient bunch of players, and this is another  
challenge,'' Casey said. ``I don't know of any team that's had 
their whole center corps wiped out, but this team will work hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams broke his right leg in a season-ending collision with  
teammate Stephon Marbury late in the fourth quarter of the Nets' 
90-85 win over the Atlanta Hawks Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Russell Warren inserted a plate and five screws into  
Williams' leg Friday at the Hospital for Special Surgery in New 
York City. Williams will be hospitalized until Monday and will 
start motion therapy over the next two days, the team said. He will 
wear a brace and will not be able to put weight on the leg for 10 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren also is orthopedic surgeon for the New York Giants.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams joins backup center Jim McIlvaine on the injured list.  
Backup Rony Seikaly has seen limited action because of a foot 
injury. Williams had been playing with a broken nose and an injured 
thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	For Saturday's game, against Alonzo Mourning and the Miami Heat,  
the team will be using William Cunningham as center. Cunningham, 
playing on his second 10-day contract with the team, has played in 
four games. In his last outing, he committed three fouls in four 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're confident that Willie will be a bother to Mourning, and  
we're going to help him as much as possible,'' Casey said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wasn't sure if the team would sign another player to  
help fill in at center. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Cunningham's fouling, Casey said it might not be as much  
of a problem against a big player. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's so eager, I can't fault him,'' Casey said, ``We use the  
phrase here `unintelligent hustle,' and that what's he's 
demonstrating. He's inexperienced ... but he's got the good reach 
for the rebound, and we're going to go with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem with losing Williams, an acknowledged leader, may be  
as much psychological as physical. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard,'' Keith Van Horn said. ``What makes it the hardest  
is that he's already playing through so much this year with his 
thumb, and he is one person on this team who has given his all this 
year. It's tough to see him go through that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Van Horn was hopeful that the Nets could finish the season  
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can still get something out of the season,'' he  
said. ``I think regardless of our win-loss record, this is a 
talented team that is going to be reckoned with in the future. The 
more we can play together, the better we can be.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
