<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tech, Index Funds Lead 1st Quarter / Mutual Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology funds and stock index portfolios kept  
their dominant positions out front in the mutual-fund performance 
race through the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Funds specializing in medium-sized to small stocks continued to  
struggle, as they have since early 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Extending a trend that has prevailed through much of the late  
1990s, Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index funds, up 4.79 percent, posted 
the best gain for the January-March period among broad stock-fund 
categories tracked by the research firm of Lipper Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Among specialized funds, science and technology funds, up 17.04  
percent, and telecommunications funds, up 16.37 percent, fared even 
better in the quarterly numbers made public by Lipper Friday. They 
thrived, as before, on the mania for Internet stocks and other 
companies riding the wave of technological innovation. 
</P>
<P>
	The S&AMP;P 500 funds outpaced growth funds, which gained 4.36  
percent, and capital appreciation funds, which rose 4.44 percent, 
by roughly half a percentage point. All those categories have a 
stake in the big blue-chip stocks heavily favored by investors in 
recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, funds specializing in medium-sized to smaller  
stocks came in with negative numbers again after losing ground in 
1998. Mid-cap funds had a first-quarter decline of 0.35 percent; 
small-cap funds of 5.98 percent, and micro-cap funds of 1.82 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, funds that invest in bonds, or mix stocks and bonds  
together in their portfolios, generally showed only slight or no 
gains for the quarter, restrained by a February rise in interest 
rates that pushed bond prices lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipper's average of more than 2,000 domestic long-term  
fixed-income funds edged up 0.21 percent. Equity income funds 
slipped 0.39 percent; balanced funds rose 1.05 percent, and growth 
and income funds gained 1.77 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the international stock arena, Japanese funds, up 15.81  
percent, scored the best gains as the Tokyo market rallied on hopes 
that Japan might at last be ready to pull out of its long 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Latin American funds, up 11.56 percent, also enjoyed a  
double-digit rebound from 1998 losses. But European funds, coming 
off strong gains last year, slipped back 2.64 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, more than 1,660 world equity funds tracked by Lipper  
showed an average gain of 3 percent for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Among domestic sector funds, natural resources funds gained 7.01  
percent with a boost from a late-March rally in world oil prices. 
But natural resources funds, down 4.62 percent, remained in a 
slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Some categories of funds that showed some life in the first  
quarter still have a lot of ground to make up from previous 
prolonged declines. The Japanese funds, for instance, still show an 
annualized loss of 4.05 percent over the past five years and have 
cost their owners 2.06 percent a year over the decade since March 
31, 1989, when the Japanese market was nearing a peak. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. stock funds, by contrast, boast extrordinary long-term  
records of prosperity. Lipper's tally of more than 3,900 domestic 
equity funds of all types shows a gain of 15.41 percent a year, on 
average, over the last 10 years, and 18.48 percent over the last 
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
