<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions Imposed on Russia Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has  
decided to impose sanctions on three Russian firms involved in the 
sale of anti-tank guided missiles to Syria, the State Department 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions involve a ban on purchases from and exports to the  
three firms and also suspends U.S. assistance to them. The amount 
of the aid was not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Albright could  
have cut up to $90 million in assistance to the Russian government 
but decided against doing so because she believed it would not 
serve U.S. national interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The law applicable to such cases is invoked when sales of lethal  
equipment are made to countries on the State Department's terrorism 
list. Syria is one of seven countries on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	The three firms are the Tula Design Bureau, the Volsk Mechanical  
Plant and the Tsniitochmash plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures will remain in place until one year after the  
transfers have ceased or until the secretary determines that it is 
important to U.S. interests to waive them, Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
