<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Lauds Anti-Smoking Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Florida experienced the largest annual drop in  
teen-age smoking in nearly two decades after launching a $70 
million anti-tobacco campaign aimed at children, federal health 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoking dropped 19 percent among middle schoolers and 8 percent  
among high schoolers between February 1998 and February 1999, the 
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was the largest nationwide since 1980.  
</P>
<P>
	Florida's aggressive anti-smoking campaign, which began last  
April, includes vigorous enforcement of smoking age limits and 
broadcast and print ads, produced with the help of teen-agers, that 
poke fun at the tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC said higher cigarette prices also may have lowered the  
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Florida middle-school students who reported having  
smoked cigarettes declined from 18.5 percent to 15 percent. 
Cigarette use among high schoolers dropped from 27.4 percent to 
25.2 percent during the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar declines were found with cigar and smokeless tobacco.  
Middle school students using cigars dropped from 14.1 percent to 
11.9 percent and those using smokeless tobacco decreased from 6.9 
percent to 4.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Cigar and smokeless tobacco use dipped only slightly among high  
schoolers. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based on 1998 and 1999 Florida Department of  
Health surveys of about 20,000 public school students. 
</P>
<P>
	``These results show why every state should have a comprehensive  
program to reduce youth smoking and why I oppose any legislation 
waiving the federal government's claim to tobacco settlement funds 
without making a commitment from the states to fund such efforts,'' 
President Clinton said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were released as state lawmakers are debating  
whether to reduce funding for the campaign in the fiscal year that 
starts July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jeb Bush and the Florida Senate have proposed spending  
about $61 million on the program, a cut of $9 million. The state 
House, however, had proposed slashing the budget by more than half, 
to $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads run in Florida's so-called ``Truth'' campaign have  
pushed the edge of taste, in the minds of some critics. 
</P>
<P>
	One had a chubby man lounging in a woman's swimsuit, smoking a  
cigarette, with the caption, ``No wonder tobacco executives have to 
hide behind sexy models.'' Another features youngsters making prank 
calls to tobacco executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Another ad portrayed a chic Academy Awards-like event ``in  
downtown Hades'' where an award for most deaths in a single year is 
up for grabs among Suicide, Illicit Drugs, Tobacco and Murder. In 
the audience are infamous killers such as Adolf Hitler and Josef 
Stalin. 
</P>
<P>
	When Tobacco, represented by a clean-cut executive type, wins  
the award, he exclaims: ``I want to thank all you smokers out 
there. This one is for you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
