<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke's Brand Named Player of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Duke's Elton Brand collected another player  
of the year honor Friday, winning the John R. Wooden Award as 
college basketball's top player. 
</P>
<P>
	The sophomore center who led the Blue Devils to the NCAA  
tournament title game had already been honored by The Associated 
Press, the Atlanta Tipoff Club, the United States Basketball 
Writers Association and the Atlantic Coast Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``My name will go down in history with these individual  
accolades, but if you could win with your team, it's so special,'' 
he said after accepting the trophy at the Los Angeles Athletic 
Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand received 4,312 points in a nationwide vote of  
sportscasters and sportswriters. He finished 696 points ahead of 
Andre Miller of Utah, who had 3,616 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami of Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak was third with 3,108 points,  
followed by Mateen Cleaves of Michigan State (2,964) and Richard 
Hamilton (2,865), whose Connecticut team defeated Brand and Duke 
77-74 in Monday night's NCAA championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hard to sleep that night because we were so close. I  
ran about a thousand plays through my head that I could have done 
to help win the game,'' Brand said. ``Then when I did sleep the 
next day I was dreaming of winning it. That's going to stick with 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton admitted he's still living the dream of winning the  
NCAA title, and wasn't disappointed to finish fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll take a national championship over anything,'' he said.  
``You can always win an MVP trophy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brand became the only sophomore winner in the Wooden Award's  
23-year history. He's the third consecutive ACC player to win, 
joining last year's honoree Antawn Jamison of North Carolina and 
Wake Forest's Tim Duncan in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand averaged 17.8 points and 9.8 rebounds for the Blue Devils,  
who finished 37-2, including a perfect record in ACC play. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand said he has no timetable for a decision on whether he'll  
stay in college or enter the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not in any rush,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wooden described Brand as ``a very nice young man'' who should  
stay in school. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he goes pro, the only thing that would be beneficial about  
it is money, and that'll all get away in time,'' said Wooden, who 
coached UCLA to 10 national championships. ``He'd be sacrificing 
two of the most wonderful years of his life with people his own 
age. Almost any youngster would be better to finish school.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
