<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Works Cuts in Connecticut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- The Stanley Works is moving some  
hardware manufacturing out of the city and cutting about 400 at its 
headquarters here. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Thursday that the cost of doing business at a  
100-year-old plant was the major reason for the moves. Some items 
now travel up to several miles through numerous multi-story 
buildings during production, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That infrastructure places us at a competitive disadvantage  
against the growing number of low-cost producers in the market,'' 
said John Trani, Stanley's chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Product lines including hinges, brackets, latches, and vent  
tubes will be relocated to other Stanley plants in Asia and North 
America, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first layoff notices are expected to go out in May or June,  
and the cuts will be completed by the end of the year, said company 
spokesman Vance Meyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley is in the midst of a major restructuring announced in  
July 1997 with plans to cut 4,500 jobs, or 24 percent of its 
worldwide work force, and close more than 50 of its 123 factories 
and distribution centers. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
