<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cases of Child Abuse on Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a decline in the number of reported  
cases, nearly 1 million children are victims of abuse and neglect, 
according to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Health and Human Services on Thursday said  
reported cases of child abuse, provided by the states, decreased 
for the fourth year in a row in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But the states still found that 963,870 children were victims of  
abuse and neglect. There were nearly 3 million reports of alleged 
mistreatment investigated by child protective services. 
</P>
<P>
	``Though we're reporting a slight decline in children as victims  
of abuse and neglect, these numbers nevertheless represent an 
unacceptable human tragedy we must do more to prevent,'' HHS 
Secretary Donna Shalala said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents and relatives comprise the majority of those responsible  
for abuse and neglect, according to the HHS. Parents account for 75 
percent of perpetrators, relatives 10 percent and non-related 
individuals make up 6 percent of those responsible for 
maltreatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also stressed the link between substance abuse  
and child abuse. Substance abuse was a factor in one-third of all 
cases of child abuse and neglect. The HHS report recommended closer 
coordination between the child protection and substance abuse 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Families where there is child abuse and neglect often face  
multiple problems that require comprehensive solutions,'' said 
Nelba Chavez, administrator of the Substance Abuse and Mental 
Health Services Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures are based on reported cases, and the department  
noted that separate studies have found that the number of victims 
may be higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, a private group that works against child  
abuse came out with a report that found a slight increase in 
reports of child abuse. In 1988, there were nearly 2.3 million 
reports of child abuse, which grew to nearly 3.2 million by 1997, 
according to the report by Prevent Child Abuse America, which bases 
its numbers partly on projections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is getting safer except for our children,'' said  
Kevin Kirkpatrick, spokesman for the group, which has just changed 
its name from the National Committee to Prevent Child Abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of National Child Abuse and Neglect Prevention Month in  
April, the HHS plans to distribute information packets to child 
welfare agencies and community groups. The prevention material can 
also be obtained by calling the National Clearinghouse on Child 
Abuse and Neglect at 1-800-FYI-3366. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:24:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Approves Satellite TV Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A merger between two big satellite TV  
companies has won approval by federal regulators with the hope that 
the deal will bring more competition to cable TV providers. 
</P>
<P>
	The action Thursday by the Federal Communications Commission's  
International Bureau cleared the way for DirecTV to buy United 
States Satellite Broadcasting Co., its main programming affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, valued at $1.3 billion when it was announced in  
December, would create a powerful force in the delivery of 
television beamed directly to American homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies provide TV programming to customers who use  
pizza-sized dishes mounted outdoors to receive the signals. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's action coincided with the first day of cable TV  
deregulation, which lifts limits on what cable companies can charge 
customers wanting to watch many of their favorite cable channels. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators view satellite TV companies, which compete against  
local cable TV companies, as the best way of trying to check rising 
cable TV rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC concluded the satellite TV merger would serve the public  
interest by making the companies a stronger competitor to cable TV 
providers. 
</P>
<P>
	The end of federal price controls on cable TV ``makes it even  
more critical that we provide consumers with competitive 
alternatives to cable in the video programming market,'' FCC 
Chairman Bill Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV President Eddy Hartenstein said the merger will let the  
company ``enhance our programming lineup, strengthen our 
competitive position against cable and allow us to deliver new 
services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase will expand DirecTV's 185-channel programming  
lineup to more than 210 channels. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's approval removed the last major regulatory hurdle to  
the merger, which USSB shareholders still must approve. The 
companies hope to close the deal by midyear. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC did require DirecTV to offer programming on three  
satellite channels by Dec. 31, or risk losing them. The company is 
not now using those channels, but does plan to offer 
Spanish-language programming on them. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV has more than 4.7 million subscribers. USSB provides  
premium movie channels such as HBO and Showtime and pay-per-view 
programming -- usually as an add-on to DirecTV. USSB has about 2 
million subscribers, including 1.8 million who also subscribe to 
DirecTV. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:43:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Cycling Team Denies Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The manager of Belgium's Lotto cycling  
team on Friday dismissed claims of drug use made by the man at the 
center of last summer's Tour de France scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Willy Voet, former masseur of the French Festina team, was  
quoted in the Het Belang Van Limburg newspaper on Friday as saying 
a Spanish doctor working with the Lotto supplied him with the 
performance-enhancing drug EPO after Festina's supplies ran out 
during races last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I categorically deny the accusations, that were put forward in  
a perfectly gratuitous way without the slightest hint of 
evidence,'' Lotto team manager Jean-Luc Vandenbroucke. 
</P>
<P>
	Voet was suspended from cycling for three years for his part in  
the drug scandal overshadowed last year's Tour de France. He 
admitted Festina riders used banned drugs and is one of a dozen 
people under investigation by French courts. 
</P>
<P>
	In another case, it was reported that a package containing  
amphetamines intercepted by Belgian authorities this week was 
addressed to former world champion Gianni Bugno of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly I wasn't expecting anything like that and at this  
moment I can only say I'm completely extraneous to the affair,'' 
Bugno told the Italian news agency ANSA. 
</P>
<P>
	Bugno's former team, Mapei was pulled from a race in Belgium  
Thursday and questioned by police after the discovery of the 
package which was sent from the team's hotel in Kortrijk. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators released the team's riders and management Thursday  
night, saying there was no evidence linking them to the banned 
drugs. But an Italian member of the team's medical staff remained 
in custody. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Daniel Baal, president of the French Cycling  
Federation, was placed under investigation by a French judge in 
connection with the Tour de France scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Baal was charged with ``complicity to facilitate and incite  
doping,'' said his lawyer, Paul Mauriac. Baal, who says he has 
always tried to prevent drug use, was ``shocked'' by what he called 
an unjust decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 11:52:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Writer Seeks U.S. Asylum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERVILLE, Maine (AP) -- A Pakistani journalist who was  
imprisoned and accused of being a traitor in his homeland for 
exposing child-labor conditions said Friday he plans to seek 
political asylum in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Zafaryab Ahmed was allowed to leave Pakistan to fulfill a  
fellowship at Colby College. He was due back home March 2, when his 
90-day permit from Pakistan expired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their objective is to break me. Now I'm here,'' he said. ``The  
Pakistani government can say nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmed, 45, faces sedition charges in Pakistan for his stories  
that exposed slave-like working conditions of children in Pakistan 
and attracted international attention. He was arrested in 1995 
after he wrote about the murder of a 12-year-old activist. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmed was allowed to come to Colby College, a private liberal  
arts school in Waterville, in December after pressure from U.S. 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that if he returned home, he would not be allowed to  
work as a journalist or a human rights activist, and he would face 
constant surveillance. He said he is worried that his defection 
would endanger his mother, brother, sister and nephews and nieces 
in Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmed's U.S. visa expires on May 23. But because he has filed  
for political asylum, he will be allowed to remain in the country 
until his case is reviewed by the Immigration and Naturalization 
Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
