<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Followers Concerned About Farrakhan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials in Louis Farrakhan's Nation of Islam  
say they're seriously concerned about the health of the man who has 
headed their organization for two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan is recovering from surgery he underwent Wednesday  
related to his prostate cancer. His chief of staff said then that 
Farrakhan's treatment ``continues to be successful and his 
prognosis is excellent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a Nation of Islam member, who spoke Thursday on condition of  
anonymity, said there are serious worries within the organization 
about Farrakhan's health. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nervousness,'' said the member, who requested  
anonymity. ``At this point, we are simply hoping for the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The source said members of the Nation of Islam recognized the  
gravity of the situation when Farrakhan's family accompanied him on 
this round of medical treatments. Farrakhan, his family -- including 
his wife, daughter and son-in-law -- and an entourage flew here 
Tuesday from Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Members were also stunned at how Farrakhan looked at an event in  
February, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post, quoting a source at Howard University  
Hospital where Farrakhan is being treated, said he remains in 
``very bad shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said he was rushed to Washington, bleeding and in  
great pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan, 65, was first treated for prostate cancer in 1991,  
using a hormonal therapy. Three years later, doctors began 
implanting bits of radioactive metal in a bid to kill cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan has 238 such seeds. Two weeks ago, his doctor, Abdul  
Alim Muhammad, said Farrakhan's score on a prostate specific 
antigen test has ranged from an ominous 16 to below one -- a level 
shown by men who are free of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post reported that Farrakhan was again receiving the  
radioactive seed treatment this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan has been ill since early January with an undiagnosed  
condition, according to an article last month in Final Call, the 
Nation of Islam newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Final Call quoted the minister as saying in a Feb. 28 speech  
that he had lost 20 pounds in two weeks and had ``no appetite, 
night sweats ... the after-effects of radiation therapy and other 
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, civil rights leader Jesse Jackson revealed that  
Farrakhan had undergone surgery for his cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fortunately because he has kept up with it and maintained the  
discipline he's been able to more or less control it,'' Jackson 
said. ``And my sense is that the doctors today are satisfied with 
the effect of their work today. We can only pray and hope for the 
best results.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
