<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Belgrade Hit by NATO Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the most dramatic attack yet in  
11 days of air raids, NATO fired cruise missiles into the heart of 
Yugoslavia's capital early Saturday, blasting the headquarters of 
security forces accused of waging a terror campaign to eradicate 
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. The strikes signaled a promised 
escalation of the NATO air campaign intended to force Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace plan in the 
separatist province. It is the police of Serbia who are leading the 
campaign that has so far driven more than 200,000 ethnic Albanians 
from Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Strikes Kosovo Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets are trying to keep  
Yugoslav troops on the move and force them to waste precious fuel 
by continuing to pound targets in Kosovo. NATO has conceded that so 
far it has failed to stop Serb forces from expelling tens of 
thousands of Kosovo Albanians, but it insisted it would press on. 
Meanwhile, tens of thousands more refugees crossed borders out of 
the province, overwhelming local communities and relief agencies 
struggling to supply food, medicine and blankets. 

</P>
<P>
	Whitewater Witness Steele Testifies  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Susan McDougal's defense got an unusual  
endorsement today from another woman charged by Kenneth Starr's 
prosecutors. Julie Hiatt Steele testified that she, too, was 
indicted because she refused to give false testimony against 
President Clinton. Ms. Steele has been charged with lying to grand 
jurors investigating former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey's 
claim that Clinton made an unwelcome sexual advance toward her in 
1993. Ms. Steele's testimony undercut part of Mrs. Willey's 
account. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubans Enjoy Good Friday Freedoms  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Carrying large wooden crosses and singing hymns,  
several hundred Cuban Catholics walked slowly through the streets 
of the capital's Chinatown in a rare public procession in 
observance of Good Friday. Believers walked behind a group of 
children from Our Lady of Charity parish, dressed as Mary, Jesus, 
Roman soldiers and all the characters from a typical passion play. 
It was the second Good Friday in a row that the parish has 
organized Stations of the Cross since Pope John Paul II's historic 
visit in January 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	'Melissa' Virus Suspect Nabbed  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- One week after the e-mail virus named  
``Melissa'' began swamping computers across the country, 
authorities arrested a man who is accused of creating the bug in 
his apartment and naming it for a topless dancer. David L. Smith, 
30, was charged with interruption of public communications, 
conspiracy and theft of computer service. He faces a maximum of 40 
years in prison and a $480,000 fine. Melissa appeared on March 26 
and spread rapidly around the world, slowing e-mail systems to a 
crawl. Government agencies, companies and thousands of other 
institutions have been affected. 

</P>
<P>
	Military Jury Dismisses Marine  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury today issued the first  
punishment against an aviator involved in the Italian ski gondola 
accident, kicking the jet's navigator out of the Marines for 
destroying a videotape shot during the fatal flight. Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer had pleaded guilty to obstruction of justice and 
conspiracy -- charges that carried up to 10 years in prison. He 
admitted throwing the personal tape into a fire two days after his 
jet clipped an Alpine gondola cable, killing 20 people. The judge 
accepted the jury's recommendation. 

</P>
<P>
	Redskins' Trademark Revoked  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A three-member federal trademark panel ruled  
today to revoke the Washington Redskins' federal trademark 
protection, saying the team's name may disparage American Indians 
or bring them into disrepute. The Trademark Trial and Appeal Board 
granted a petition filed by seven American Indians in September 
1992 to cancel the team's trademark registrations because of a 
federal law that prohibits registering ``disparaging'' names and 
logos. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke's Brand Named Player of Year  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Duke's Elton Brand collected another player  
of the year honor today, winning the John R. Wooden Award as 
college basketball's top player. The sophomore center who led the 
Blue Devils to the NCAA tournament title game had already been 
honored by The Associated Press. Brand finished ahead of Andre 
Miller of Utah and Miami of Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 08:23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Arrest Made in 'Melissa' Virus Case  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A man has been arrested by federal and  
state officials and charged with originating the e-mail virus known 
as Melissa. Authorities say David L. Smith originated the virus, 
which caused worldwide e-mail disruption this week, from his 
apartment in central New Jersey. Melissa appeared last Friday and 
spread rapidly around the world on Monday like a malicious chain 
letter, causing affected computers to fire off dozens of infected 
messages to friends and colleagues and swamping e-mail systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Proceedings Begin in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb officials began gathering  
evidence today against three U.S. soldiers captured Wednesday and 
held in Kosovo, the state-run Tanjug news agency reported. The 
investigating judge said ``court proceedings'' began today and that 
``more detailed information will be known Saturday,'' Tanjug said. 
Judge Jovica Jovanovic did not say how long the preliminary phase 
would last or whether the soldiers would eventually be charged. 
Meanwhile, air strikes pounded targets deep inside Yugoslavia today 
in a mission that NATO said has failed to stop Serb forces from 
creating ``ghost towns'' in Kosovo, where nearly one-third of the 
population was reported displaced. 

</P>
<P>
	US Blasts Plan To Try Soldiers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration strongly condemned  
today Yugoslavia's plans to put three captured U.S. soldiers on 
trial, calling for their immediate release. The Pentagon said the 
men at least deserve human treatment as called for in treaties 
agreed to at the Geneva Convention. As POWs, the Army soldiers 
could be held until the end of hostilities. The Pentagon was trying 
to determine whether the soldiers were captured in Macedonia or had 
blundered into Serb territory while on the run. Yugoslav 
authorities said they were caught in Serbia and resisted arrest. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Denies Iraqi Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- The United States is denying that it  
conducted air strikes on Baghdad that the Iraqi government said 
destroyed two houses. Military officials say there were no air 
strikes in southern Iraq, although there were two Iraqi violations 
of the ``no-fly'' zone. The official Iraqi News Agency said 
aircraft, including F-14s, F-16s and Tornados, carried out 18 
sorties from Kuwaiti skies and 33 from Saudi skies. 

</P>
<P>
	Jerusalem Pilgrims Mark Good Friday  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Thousands of pilgrims walked through  
Jerusalem's Old City in a Good Friday procession today, retracing 
Jesus' step to his crucifixion. Worshippers sang hymns and read 
prayers in Arabic, Italian, English and several other languages. A 
California group re-enacted Jesus' last walk in full costume, with 
one man dressed as Jesus, crowned with thorns and his face streaked 
with blood. 

</P>
<P>
	Snow Blankets Northern Plains  
</P>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Plains residents braced for more stormy  
weather today after more than a foot of snow blanketed parts of the 
region. In the Black Hills in South Dakota, Deadwood got 13 inches 
of snow yesterday and nearby Lead received about a foot. In North 
Dakota, Bismarck and Dickinson both received 9 inches of snow. A 
winter storm watch was still in effect for parts of North Dakota, 
and as much as 6 inches of snow were possible by tonight. 

</P>
<P>
	Ill Grandmother Robbed Buying Pot  
</P>
<P>
	WINNABOW, N.C. (AP) -- A grandmother who says she uses marijuana  
for medicinal purposes was robbed and attacked while on a pot run 
with her 13-year-old grandson in the car. Now police are 
considering filing charges against her from bringing the child 
along. Tinkey Mae Sullivan usually goes alone to buy a 
quarter-ounce to an ounce of pot, which she says eases her 
rheumatoid arthritis and her other ailments. But she took the 
teen-ager along while running some errands. North Carolina has not 
approved use of pot for medical purposes. 

</P>
<P>
	Lyme Disease Vaccine Now Available  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new vaccine for Lyme disease is now  
available and doctors are pushing people to get their shots. 
Doctors say the urgency comes from the fact that it takes a series 
of three shots to build up to full immunity to the disease that is 
caused by pin-sized ticks that live in wooded and grassy areas 
nationwide. Symptoms include fatigue, chills, fevers and joint pain 
that can persist for weeks. Some people develop serious arthritis. 
If untreated, Lyme disease also can severely damage the heart and 
nervous system. 

</P>
<P>
	Murdoch May Buy Out Partner  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Media mogul Rupert Murdoch has agreed to buy  
out a partner to expand his control of regional cable networks and 
his stake in two New York professional sports teams, published 
reports said. Partner John Malone's Liberty Media will sell his 50 
percent interest in Fox/Liberty Networks, the partnership he formed 
with Murdoch in 1995, in exchange for about $1.4 billion in stock 
from Murdoch's News Corporation. The deal gives Murdoch control of 
40 percent of the New York Knicks, the Rangers and Madison Square 
Garden. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
