<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 09:56:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Markets Closed for Good Friday / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock and most commodity markets are closed  
today in the United States and many other countries in observance 
of Good Friday. U.S. bond markets will close at noon and some 
commodity markets will hold abbreviated morning sessions. 
Government offices and most banks are open. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks closed mostly higher on a late burst of buying Thursday  
as optimism generated by merger announcements overcame worries 
about interest rates and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 46.35 to 9,832.51 after  
changing direction several times over the course of the day. The 
pre-holiday trading was light, making price swings sharper than 
usual. The Dow ended up 10.27 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
rose 7.35 to 1,293.72, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite 
index rose 31.97 to 2,493.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in both the stock and bond markets were trading  
cautiously ahead of the long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were nervous about the continuing U.S. military presence  
in Yugoslavia and worried that the situation might escalate over 
the weekend. They were also wary about Friday's scheduled release 
of March employment data, especially because the stock market would 
be closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can make much of this afternoon's  
recovery,'' said Ricky Harrington, technical analyst at 
Interstate/Johnson Lane in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's just a little more caution in the air, and people are  
going into the long weekend trying to not have a great deal of 
exposure either on the up or down side. When the Dow's at 9,800, it 
doesn't take much of a movement in a few Dow stocks to put the 
market up 20 or 30 points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, corporate mergers helped lift the market.  
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! announced a $5.7 billion planned purchase of  
Broadcast.com, sending Yahoo! shares up 11 3/8 to 179 3/4, and 
Broadcast.com up 11 13/16 to 130. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, BP Amoco announced plans to buy Atlantic Richfield  
for $26.6 billion, a deal that would create the world's 
second-largest oil company. Atlantic Richfield shares fell 11/16 to 
72 7/16, and BP's shares fell 5 3/16 to 95 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	And CBS said it would pay $2.5 billion for King World  
Productions, the largest TV-syndication company. CBS shares fell 
11/16 to 40 1/8, but King World's rose 5/8 to 31 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger talk produced an opening rally, but that soon  
evaporated when the National Association of Purchasing Management 
reported its monthly index of business activity rose to 54.3 
percent last month, an increase of 1.9 percentage points from its 
February level. 
</P>
<P>
	In another sign of economic vigor, the Commerce Department  
reported construction spending jumped a much-stronger-than-expected 
2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also reported personal income increased a  
seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent in February after a 0.6 percent 
gain in January. Consumer spending, meanwhile, jumped 0.7 percent 
after a 0.4 percent rise the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent bond prices lower as traders feared the strong  
economy would reignite inflation and lead to higher interest rates. 
The yield on the 30-year Treasury rose to 5.67 percent from 5.62 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks followed bonds' lead until late afternoon.  
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues narrowly led advancers on the New York Stock  
Exchange, and consolidated volume was moderate at 848.68 million 
shares, down sharply from Wednesday's pace of 922.16 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 1.40 to 604.99, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.00 to 711.30. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.11 to 398.74. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas stock markets, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo surged  
3.10 percent, as domestic and foreign investors scooped up shares 
on the first day of Japan's new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	European stock markets rose on widespread expectations that the  
European Central Bank will lower its main refinancing rate when its 
governing council meets April 8, traders said. The DAX index in 
Frankfurt climbed 1.01 percent, the FT-SE 100 in London advanced 
0.55 percent, and the CAC in Paris added 0.76 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 11:13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Jobless Rate Record 6 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Wan Pui-ying wants to know how to bleach toilet  
stains, iron silk shirts and clean up dog poop -- and the government 
of Hong Kong is helping teach her. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with 30 other middle aged women, Wan is taking  
government-funded classes at a local YWCA on how to be a maid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think being a maid is inferior,'' says Wan, a 55-year  
old former jewelry saleswoman. ``Every job deserves respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With unemployment at a record 6 percent and the number of  
vacancies shrinking, the Hong Kong government is trying to upgrade 
the skills of displaced workers competing with others half their 
age. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless figure is low by world standards. But in Hong Kong --  
where the high-octane, entrepreneurial spirit feeding the city's 
dynamism is bred to the bone -- 206,000 people out of work is 
alarming. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong once saw its financial markets awash with money and  
banks teeming with clients. Stockbrokers, lawyers, flashy 
restaurateurs and discreet powerbrokers commingled amid what seemed 
like a constant boom. 
</P>
<P>
	The bust came with Asia's economic crisis, which threw Hong Kong  
into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Wan says she was happy peddling watches and necklaces from store  
to store in the busy shopping district in Kowloon, across the 
harbor from Hong Kong Island. But when her employer buckled under 
the recession, Wan found herself out of work and with grim 
prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't speak English,'' Wan said in Cantonese. ``I have no  
office skills. How can I compete with younger misses?'' 
</P>
<P>
	To try to set things right, the government is spending $64  
million this year to fund more than 150 retraining centers all over 
the territory offering classes in computers, typing, English, and 
household chores. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to play a significant role, to release productivity  
and keep Hong Kong ticking,'' said Matthew Cheung, newly-appointed 
commissioner of labor. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics say the government is missing an important point.  
While the government's listing of job vacancies is plentiful -- 
about 130,000 -- most of them are in finance, real estate, 
restaurants, and business services. The training being offered 
won't land anybody one of those positions. 
</P>
<P>
	S.S. Kwong, executive director of the government's Employees  
Retraining Board, says the problem of job mismatch ``happens 
everywhere in the world.'' Critics say the jobs many retrained 
workers will get won't provide a decent living. 
</P>
<P>
	Many unemployed are training to be security guards and office  
clerks, but employers are looking for financial consultants, 
managers, or engineers. In the end, many will have to move down the 
societal ladder instead of up, said So Yuk-yan of the international 
welfare agency Oxfam Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government refuses to accept the fact that the jobs in the  
market are not enough to provide a satisfactory standard of living 
for many low-skilled workers,'' said So, who researches poverty and 
unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	So predicts things will get worse before they get better. She  
sits in a 17-member coalition of welfare agencies, labor activists, 
and trade unions who oppose recent proposals to cut the already 
meager welfare benefits for the unemployed. 
</P>
<P>
	Social welfare director Andrew Leung defends the cutbacks,  
saying no one capable of work should be on permanently on the dole. 
Welfare applications could swell without serious reforms, and the 
government faces a $1.67 billion welfare bill this year, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hong Kong's success is its work ethic and we must encourage  
the unemployed to re-enter the job market,'' says Leung. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts suggest joblessness could hit 7 percent by midyear. The  
government has announced major infrastructure projects in the next 
two years -- including a high-tech industrial park -- to create more 
than 120,000 new jobs. Hong Kong is also in talks with Disney about 
building a theme park here. 
</P>
<P>
	But all the details have yet to be finalized, and any new jobs  
won't be created instantly. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, experts say the recession will linger.  
</P>
<P>
	``The worst may be over, but the economy hasn't bottomed out  
yet,'' said Guonan Ma, an economist at the U.S. investment bank 
Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:34:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stewart Leaves as Missouri Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Norm Stewart recently said he wanted to  
coach another half-dozen years. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he ended a 32-year run at Missouri that produced 634  
victories when he announced his retirement Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	There was speculation that he was pushed out the door by new  
athletic director Mike Alden, who's been at the school only eight 
months, but Stewart said it was his call. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the inspiration came during a game at Kansas in January  
and a familiar chant from Jayhawks fans, ``Sit down, Norm!'' took 
on an entirely different meaning. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what I said to myself that day? `I think I will,' ''  
Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	From then on, although he never let on to players or  
administration, Stewart said there was no turning back. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't always make all the right decisions, and you can't  
coach a perfect game,'' Stewart said. ``So you make the decision 
and that's it. I got to make mine. I wish more people in this 
profession got to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart will serve the last four years of his contract as a  
special assistant to the school's chancellor. If there are any hard 
feelings, it was tough to tell as Stewart and Alden shared the 
podium at a center-court news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart was in such a light-hearted mood that when he received a  
standing ovation from several hundred fans and players -- past and 
present -- in attendance, he asked if it had been timed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've decided not to coach at Missouri, in basketball or in any  
other sport,'' Stewart said. ``I came to Missouri a young man and 
I'm leaving a young man. Everybody has been really nice and good to 
work with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alden said he was shocked when the coach brought up retirement  
for the first time on March 15, three days after Missouri was 
eliminated by New Mexico in the first round of the NCAA tournament, 
in what he thought would be a typical end-of-season review. He said 
Stewart reiterated his desire to step down the following day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked him, are you sure?'' Alden said. ``He said he had  
decided what he wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players weren't notified until Wednesday, more than two weeks  
after the meeting. They, too, were shocked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was getting ready for class and my mom called me and she was  
like `Tell me the scoop, tell me the scoop,''' sophomore forward 
Johnnie Parker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Presumably, Stewart had earned the right to orchestrate his  
departure. He leaves with an impressive resume, at least from a 
numbers standpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He's the third-winningest active coach with 731 victories,  
trailing only James Phelan of Mount St. Mary's (800) and Bobby 
Knight of Indiana (742), and he's seventh on the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He averaged 19 victories a season at Missouri, and as player,  
assistant coach and head coach was involved in more than half 
(1,127) of the 2,151 games ever played at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He bounced back from colon cancer in 1989 and NCAA probation  
in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He produced an undefeated conference champion in 1993-94, a  
team that included zero future NBA stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart also leaves the program in good shape, with three  
starters back and two others with significant experience. That's a 
huge difference from his arrival in 1967, when Missouri totaled six 
victories in 49 games the previous two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I got here there wasn't much springboard,'' Stewart said.  
``There wasn't any pool, there wasn't any water. If you jumped in, 
you had problems. There's a better springboard now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Missouri hasn't had much success in the  
postseason with a succession of first-round upsets to lightly 
regarded opponents that began in the late 1980s. Missouri missed 
the NCAAs for three years beginning in 1995-96, going a combined 
51-47, before ending that drought this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's Missouri teams twice made it to the final eight, in  
1976 and 1994, but never to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement also came amid reports of a falling-out between  
Stewart and Alden, who wasn't happy with Stewart's lack of response 
last week when junior Albert White announced he wanted to jump to 
the NBA, and of repeated problems with players. Nine players have 
transferred in the last five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight of Stewart's current players attended the news conference,  
and the group did not include White or freshman point guard Keyon 
Dooling, who quarreled with Stewart during a game at Colorado in 
January. Stewart said the reason for the no-shows was he told them 
to attend class. 
</P>
<P>
	Dooling downplayed talk that he and fellow freshman guard  
Clarence Gilbert, a former high school teammate in Fort Lauderdale, 
Fla., might have transferred if Stewart stayed. Gilbert was another 
news conference no-show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't nothing like that,'' Dooling said. ``From what I  
know, Coach made his decision a long time ago. It really had 
nothing to do with us. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was somewhat of a roller coaster, but it's all good. I mean  
it. I respect him a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alden said he has no short list of candidates in mind to succeed  
Stewart. Possible candidates include Duke assistant Quin Snyder, 
Bob Bender of Washington and longtime Missouri assistant Kim 
Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I would be interested,'' Anderson said. ``As time goes  
on, we'll see what happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:34:26 </DATE_TIME>
