<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compromise Answer on Index Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the long-running debate over the virtues of  
actively managed stock mutual funds or passive index funds, the 
choice is usually portrayed as an either-or decision. But for some 
investors, a better answer might be ``both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, anyway, suggests Mark Riepe, head of the investment research  
center at the brokerage firm Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., which has just 
completed a study on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	Riepe advocates a strategy he calls ``core and explore,'' which  
mixes index funds with actively managed funds in an effort to give 
a portfolio a chance to outperform the market while keeping down 
the risk that it might lag substantially behind. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a compromise approach, which may not appeal to people who  
care about coming down on the right side of every argument. But on 
the plus side, it bears more than a passing resemblance to the 
strategy being used by some very successful and practical-minded 
fund managers themselves these days. 
</P>
<P>
	In Riepe's view, fund investors should start with an  
asset-allocation plan, parceling out their money among five types 
of investments: Big stocks, small stocks, international stocks, 
long-term bonds and short-term money market securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Next, you look at the money you have allocated to each category,  
and decide which funds to use. In the big-stock arena, for 
instance, you might turn first to an index fund modeled on Standard 
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which is dominated by blue chips. 
</P>
<P>
	In Riepe's plan, the index fund becomes your core holding in  
that category. Then, if you wish, Riepe goes on to say, ``more 
specialized, actively managed funds are layered on to 'explore' the 
potential of outperforming the overall market.'' The same approach 
can be taken with small stocks and international stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	To test how this system might work in the real world, Riepe and  
his staff checked out how thousands of portfolios -- some using 
core-and-explore, some using ``explore,'' or managed funds, only -- 
would have fared over various three-year spans in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The results: In the 1995-97 time period, for instance,  
core-and-explore, or C&AMP;E, portfolios got better results on balance 
than either explore-only or core-only portfolios. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports Riepe, ``The C&AMP;E portfolios remained less volatile than  
their all-explore counterparts 57 percent of the time. Their higher 
returns, therefore did not come at the price of increased risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his other conclusions: ``An anchor of core (or index)  
funds can provide an effective counterbalance to more specialized, 
actively managed funds, some of which will underperform and some of 
which will outperform the benchmarks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, ``emphasizing actively managed explore funds  
in the small-cap and international asset classes tended to increase 
a portfolio's potential to beat the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What is an individual investor with a modest-sized nest egg in  
funds to make of all this? The most important message may be not to 
get too doctrinaire about any aspect of fund investing, but to keep 
a balanced view as you put together a portfolio of a few funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Index funds in the big-stock sector of the market have  
consistently achieved better results than most managed funds in 
recent years. But other types of index funds have not outshone 
their managed competitors so decisively. In either case, it's 
impossible to know for certain whether these patterns will hold in 
the future. 
</P>
<P>
	More often than not, the choice of an investment must depend on  
your own situation and temperament. Riepe notes that some investors 
may be completely content with an all-core fund portfolio, aiming 
simply to capture a return equal to a market index's while 
minimizing the costs of research and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Conversely, he says, a preference for ``explore'' funds might  
make sense for ``investors who seek the chance of outperforming the 
market, who favor a certain manager's abilities, or who have a 
strong personal conviction about market trends or a particular 
fund's objectives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If you aren't sure which side you favor, Riepe's study supports  
the idea that you can put one foot in either camp and still give 
yourself a decent chance of success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
