<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Markets Closed for Good Friday / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock and most commodity markets are closed  
today in the United States and many other countries in observance 
of Good Friday. U.S. bond markets will close at noon and some 
commodity markets will hold abbreviated morning sessions. 
Government offices and most banks are open. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks closed mostly higher on a late burst of buying Thursday  
as optimism generated by merger announcements overcame worries 
about interest rates and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 46.35 to 9,832.51 after  
changing direction several times over the course of the day. The 
pre-holiday trading was light, making price swings sharper than 
usual. The Dow ended up 10.27 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
rose 7.35 to 1,293.72, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite 
index rose 31.97 to 2,493.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in both the stock and bond markets were trading  
cautiously ahead of the long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were nervous about the continuing U.S. military presence  
in Yugoslavia and worried that the situation might escalate over 
the weekend. They were also wary about Friday's scheduled release 
of March employment data, especially because the stock market would 
be closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can make much of this afternoon's  
recovery,'' said Ricky Harrington, technical analyst at 
Interstate/Johnson Lane in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's just a little more caution in the air, and people are  
going into the long weekend trying to not have a great deal of 
exposure either on the up or down side. When the Dow's at 9,800, it 
doesn't take much of a movement in a few Dow stocks to put the 
market up 20 or 30 points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, corporate mergers helped lift the market.  
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! announced a $5.7 billion planned purchase of  
Broadcast.com, sending Yahoo! shares up 11 3/8 to 179 3/4, and 
Broadcast.com up 11 13/16 to 130. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, BP Amoco announced plans to buy Atlantic Richfield  
for $26.6 billion, a deal that would create the world's 
second-largest oil company. Atlantic Richfield shares fell 11/16 to 
72 7/16, and BP's shares fell 5 3/16 to 95 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	And CBS said it would pay $2.5 billion for King World  
Productions, the largest TV-syndication company. CBS shares fell 
11/16 to 40 1/8, but King World's rose 5/8 to 31 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger talk produced an opening rally, but that soon  
evaporated when the National Association of Purchasing Management 
reported its monthly index of business activity rose to 54.3 
percent last month, an increase of 1.9 percentage points from its 
February level. 
</P>
<P>
	In another sign of economic vigor, the Commerce Department  
reported construction spending jumped a much-stronger-than-expected 
2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also reported personal income increased a  
seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent in February after a 0.6 percent 
gain in January. Consumer spending, meanwhile, jumped 0.7 percent 
after a 0.4 percent rise the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent bond prices lower as traders feared the strong  
economy would reignite inflation and lead to higher interest rates. 
The yield on the 30-year Treasury rose to 5.67 percent from 5.62 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks followed bonds' lead until late afternoon.  
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues narrowly led advancers on the New York Stock  
Exchange, and consolidated volume was moderate at 848.68 million 
shares, down sharply from Wednesday's pace of 922.16 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 1.40 to 604.99, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.00 to 711.30. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.11 to 398.74. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas stock markets, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo surged  
3.10 percent, as domestic and foreign investors scooped up shares 
on the first day of Japan's new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	European stock markets rose on widespread expectations that the  
European Central Bank will lower its main refinancing rate when its 
governing council meets April 8, traders said. The DAX index in 
Frankfurt climbed 1.01 percent, the FT-SE 100 in London advanced 
0.55 percent, and the CAC in Paris added 0.76 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
