<DOCNO> APW19990402.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 05:24:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed. Considered Reversing Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve policy-makers in February  
considered -- but rejected -- the idea of taking back at least one of 
the quarter-point interest-rate cuts they engineered last fall, 
according to minutes of their meeting that were released today. 
</P>
<P>
	In three steps from late September to mid-November, the Fed  
reduced the benchmark rate on overnight loans between banks from 
5.5 percent to 4.75 percent to prevent the world market turmoil 
that followed the collapse of the Russian ruble from harming the 
U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In a meeting on Feb. 3, members of the Federal Open Market  
Committee noted that ``the market unsettlement that had in large 
measure prompted the committee's easing actions during the fall had 
now lessened appreciably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In the view of some,'' the minutes continued, ``those actions  
might need to be reversed, at least in part, to restore what they 
regarded as a policy stance that seemed most likely to prove 
consistent with desirable economic trends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the minutes revealed, the panel voted unanimously  
against changing the benchmark rate, which is known as the federal 
funds rate. The panel met again Tuesday and decided again to leave 
the rate unchanged. Minutes of that meeting are due out in mid-May. 
</P>
<P>
	At the February session, one member -- the minutes did not reveal  
who -- argued the Fed should adopt a policy directive declaring 
higher rates were more likely than lower rates in the future. But, 
in the end, all accepted a directive giving equal weight to the 
possibility of a rate cut or rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``The members agreed on the need to continue to monitor the  
economy with care for signs either of a potential upturn in 
inflation or greater softness in the expansion than they were 
currently forecasting and to be prepared to respond promptly in 
either direction,'' the minutes said. 
</P>
<P>
	In their discussion of the economy, the panel found ``few signs  
that the economic expansion had moderated to a more sustainable 
rate, but most continued to anticipate substantial slowing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the reasons were ``the waning effects of the earlier  
increases in stock market wealth on consumer spending and some 
slowing in the extraordinary growth in business expenditures for 
equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On another subject, the panel agreed that they favored extending  
the legal requirement that they be required to report to Congress 
twice a year. The requirement is scheduled to lapse at the end of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The members agreed that the semiannual reports and associated  
congressional hearings had been quite useful and should be 
continued,'' the minutes said. ``They had given the committee an 
effective means to explain its policies and communicate its views 
on a variety of issues and had enhanced its accountability to the 
public and the Congress.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990402.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:24:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Melissa' Virus Suspect Nabbed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A man has been arrested and charged with  
originating the e-mail virus known as Melissa, which swamped 
computers around the world, spreading like a malicious chain 
letter. 
</P>
<P>
	David L. Smith, who was arrested Thursday night, named the virus  
after a topless dancer from Florida, where he used to live, the New 
Jersey attorney general's office said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 30, of Aberdeen was arrested at his brother's house in  
nearby Eatontown, said Rita Malley, a spokeswoman for Attorney 
General Peter Verniero. Smith created the virus from his apartment, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces several charges, including interruption of public  
communications, conspiracy to commit the offense, attempt to commit 
the offense, and third-degree theft of computer service. All 
together, the charges carry a maximum penalty of 40 years in prison 
and a $480,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he is tried and successfully convicted, he will do hard  
time.'' Verniero said at an afternoon news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Verniero said Smith was a network programmer for a company that  
did subcontracting for AT&AMP;T Corp. The company's name was not 
immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was tracked down with the help of America Online  
technicians, and a computer task force composed of federal and 
state agents, Malley said. Authorities would not elaborate on the 
methods used to trace the virus, saying the investigation was 
ongoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa appeared last Friday and spread rapidly around the world  
by Monday, swamping the e-mail systems of thousands of computers -- 
including those at government agencies. The virus caused infected 
computers to fire off dozens of messages to friends and colleagues, 
temporarily clogging e-mail systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, experts had said there were clues that  
Melissa's author had distributed the virus using an account stolen 
from America Online 15 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Several antivirus software makers, including McAfee, Symantec,  
Trend Micro and Sophos, posted patches on their Web sites that 
detect and reject the Melissa virus. 
</P>
<P>
	It came in the form of an e-mail, usually containing the subject  
line ``Important Message,'' and appeared to be from a friend or 
colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of the e-mail message said, ``Here is that document you  
asked for ... don't show it to anyone else'' with a winking smiley 
face formed by the punctuation marks ;-). 
</P>
<P>
	Attached to the message was a document file. If the user opened  
that file, the virus dug into the user's address book and sent 
infected documents to the first 50 addresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was released on $100,000 bail and was scheduled to appear  
in state Superior Court in Monmouth County Monday for arraignment. 
</P>
<P>
	Several computer experts earlier this week said they had found  
clues linking the virus to a writer who uses the computer handle 
``VicodinES.'' Malley said Smith was ``definitely not'' the person 
who used that handle, but also said investigators believe he took 
two viruses, one of which came from VicodinES, and combined them 
with another virus to create Melissa. 
</P>
<P>
	VicodinES, which also happens to be the name of narcotic pain  
killer, is well know to a group of virus writers who gather online 
on what's known as The Virus Exchange Underground. 
</P>
<P>
	No one answered the door at Smith's second-floor apartment in  
the Ken Gardens complex in Aberdeen today. The blinds were drawn to 
his windows and on a sliding glass door to a small balcony. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
