<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stiltsville Snubbed as Landmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISCAYNE NATIONAL PARK, Fla. (AP) -- It looks like it could be  
splitsville for Stiltsville. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Register of Historic Places has decided that the  
seven stilt homes that have become a veritable landmark don't 
qualify as an official landmark -- so they'll probably be 
demolished. 
</P>
<P>
	``The history of the area is certainly interesting,'' said  
Marilyn Harper, a Register historian. ``But the houses that are 
there now are all post-1960.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buildings less than 50 years old must show ``exceptional  
importance'' to earn historic status, according to Register 
guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners had hoped to stave off demolition by winning historic  
status. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a serious setback,'' said Gail Baldwin, a Miami architect  
and co-owner of one of the homes. ``We're disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stiltsville homes rise from the shallow waters dividing  
Biscayne Bay from the reefed fringe of the Atlantic Ocean a few 
miles southeast of Miami. They are the descendants of a community 
that began in the early 1930s when structures were built on sunken 
barges. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years other homes were added, mostly on pilings driven  
into the bottom. At its height, there were about 25 dwellings, used 
for weekend retreats and parties but seldom as full-time homes. 
</P>
<P>
	For many years, they had a colorful reputation as hangouts for  
gamblers, boozers and flashy women. They have appeared repeatedly 
in novels and on television. Inhabitants bragged of being able to 
catch fish right off their porches or watch boats go by, all within 
sight of the Miami skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	The state allowed the bay bottom under existing houses to be  
leased but prohibited new construction after the Legislature passed 
the Biscayne Bay Aquatic Preserve Act in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	The last seven leases expire on June 30 and won't be renewed on  
orders of the Florida Cabinet, which controls bay bottoms in the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service has controlled the waters around  
Stiltsville since the area was annexed into Biscayne National Park 
in 1980. Superintendent Dick Frost is determined to remove the 
structures, and he is supported by environmental groups such as the 
National Audubon Society. 
</P>
<P>
	``The presence of privately owned houses is generally considered  
contrary to the purposes of designated national parks,'' Frost 
wrote in a recent letter. ``There is nothing ... that supports 
retaining any of the buildings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who tried to get the homes listed as historic was  
Miami novelist Les Standiford, who had a Stiltsville home become a 
kidnapper's hideaway in his novel ``Done Deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No one who chances upon the phenomenon of Stiltsville for the  
first time will ever forget the sight of homes that hover above the 
waters, miles from any shore, like structures from a dream,'' he 
wrote in a letter to the Register. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
