<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:25:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chisox' Konerko Learns Hard Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Paul Konerko wanted to be one of those  
players who wears the same uniform his entire career. 
</P>
<P>
	He was drafted by the Los Angeles Dodgers, came up through their  
farm system, made his big league debut at Dodger Stadium and hoped 
he'd retire one day still wearing the Dodger blue. But he learned 
the hard way last season that loyalty in baseball has gone the way 
of baggy uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a business,'' the first baseman-designated hitter for  
the Chicago White Sox said. ``I've always given people the benefit 
of the doubt and trusted them right off the bat, and I was always 
pretty fortunate because I had good people around me. But it kind 
of all came at once last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Konerko, 23, was Los Angeles' first-round pick -- 13th overall --  
in the 1994 free-agent draft. In 1997, ``Baseball America'' and 
``Baseball Weekly'' named him minor league player of the year after 
he batted .323 with 37 homers and 127 RBIs in Triple-A. He was the 
Dodgers' minor league MVP a second year in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	He was called up for six games at the end of the 1997 season,  
making his first start in the season finale. When opening day 
rolled around last year, Konerko was the Dodgers' starting first 
baseman. 
</P>
<P>
	Duplicating his success in the minors right away wasn't easy. In  
49 games, he hit .215 with four homers and 16 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just all stemmed from the fact there wasn't a place for me  
and they didn't want me to go back to Triple-A because they knew I 
didn't have anything to prove there,'' he said. ``I was on the 
team, but I really didn't have a role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he was willing to do whatever the Dodgers wanted to stay  
with the organization. They sent him down to Triple-A for a spell, 
and that was fine. He sat on the bench, and that was fine, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a company guy -- I wanted to play for that company,'' he  
said. ``Some people are like, `Oh, it's not a perfect situation 
here, I want to be traded. I'll play for any team.' It wasn't like 
that. I was willing to have a bad situation for year or whatever to 
get eventually to what I play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was willing to take it for the team, be there and play or do  
whatever was asked of me. And then one day you turn around and it's 
like, `Thanks for coming. See you later.''' 
</P>
<P>
	On July 4, the Dodgers shipped him and left-handed pitcher  
Dennys Reyes to the Cincinnati Reds for reliever Jeff Shaw. The 
trade was completed during a game with the San Francisco Giants, 
and Konerko left the Dodgers dugout before the bottom of the first 
inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Lasorda, the Dodgers' interim general manager then, said he  
didn't want to trade Konerko, but the Reds wouldn't give up Shaw 
without him. There was just one problem. The Reds didn't have a 
place for him, either. They had a first baseman, Sean Casey, and he 
didn't play another position. 
</P>
<P>
	So Konerko turned into a utility player, spending time at first,  
third and left field. Although he was still struggling at the 
plate, he was stunned when the Reds sent him down to Triple-A just 
25 days after the trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't one time last year that I didn't try as hard as I  
could or give 100 percent,'' he said. ``I didn't play well at times 
and, at times, I don't think I was given a chance to play well or 
treated the right way. It just didn't work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the season, he was traded to the White Sox for  
outfielder Mike Cameron. Chicago needed someone to split the duties 
at first and DH with Frank Thomas, and Greg Norton was moving to 
third to replace Robin Ventura, who signed with the New York Mets 
as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the best news Konerko had all year.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was thrilled,'' he said. ``After seeing what the situation  
was here and that I'd have a role on the team, I couldn't ask for 
anything better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Konerko doesn't want to wear blue the rest of his  
career. Black and white will suit him just fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's a statistic that the average player changes  
teams four times. So last year, maybe I'm just all done with it,'' 
he said. ``Maybe I'll play with these guys for the next however 
long. I just look at it that way.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
